[White "Introduction"]
[Black "About This Repertoire"]
[Result "*"]

{ About This Repertoire At the top level, the Open Spanish often involves defending some sort of very slightly worse but completely holdable endgame.   In this repertoire, I've done my best to avoid those types of situations. You can't have everything in chess, of course, but I've tried, where possible to choose lines that lead to imbalances.   Sometimes you may notice a particular line results in a lot of draws at the elite level. This can be discouraging, but my sense is that in most of the lines in this course, there remains plenty of room for both sides to make mistakes and outplay their opponent.   Plus, we can't expect that our opponents will always know theory perfectly, and you can certainly hope for an interesting game on any given day, in my opinion.   Naturally, there are going to be some precise tactical sequences you'll just have to know, but I've attempted to explain the nature of these sequences, and why they represent best play for both sides. }
