[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Open Spanish fundamental introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ Open Spanish Intro } 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
a6
{ Traditionally, this is the most popular move.  3...Nf6  is also pretty trendy these days. }
4. Ba4
{ 4.Bxc6  is an alternative. After  4...dxc6  ,  5.Nxe5  is inadvisable due to  5...Qd4  regaining the pawn. However,   5.O-O  is a serious try for an advantage. }
4... Nf6
{ This is far and away Black's main move. He develops a piece while putting pressure on White's centre. }
5. O-O
{ White ignores the e4 pawn and brings the King to safety.   5.d3  ,  5.Qe2  ,  5.Nc3  ,  5.d4  and  5.Bxc6  are alternatives. The first three make a future c2-c3 and d2-d4 more difficult. The fourth plays the central break somewhat prematurely. The last gives up the Bishop unprovoked and is thus harmless. }
5... Nxe4
{ Black grabs a central pawn. He won't be able to keep it, but he is not playing to win a pawn anyway. He intends to play ...b7-b5 and ...d7-d5, establishing a stronghold on the light squares. Appropriately, this is known as the Open Variation. }
6. d4
{ White attacks the e5 pawn and provokes a further opening of the e-file.   6.Re1  is harmless, as after  6...Nc5  , White will be forced to give up the Bishop pair. }
6... b5
{ 6...exd4?!  is known as the Riga Variation. It is quite risky after  7.Re1  d5  8.Nxd4  , when there are problems with pins along both the a4-e8 diagonal and e-file.   6...Be7!?  , meanwhile, is playable and was recommended by Yuri Krykun in his Unleash the Bull course for Chessable. It is much less popular than  6...b5  and objectively somewhat dubious. It may be worth examining as a secondary option if you're looking for one, however. }
7. Bb3 d5
{ Black establishes his foothold in the centre, covering the e4 Knight. } 8.
dxe5 { White regains his pawn.   8.Nxe5  is a less common alternative. } 8...
Be6
{ Black develops a piece and defends his d5 pawn. This is a key tabiya of the Open Spanish.   Black may proceed with either ...Be7 or ...Bc5, followed by castling. Common themes include ...Nc5  (either intending to harass the Bishop or to drop back to d7 to target e5)  , a future ...c7-c5, playing ...f7-f6 or ...f7-f5, breaking in the centre with ...d5-d4 and the ...Bg4 pin. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Pros and Cons of the Open Spanish "]
[Result "*"]

{ Pros and ConsThis is my completely honest list of the pros and cons of playing the Open Spanish with Black. We will start with the pros, naturally.  PROS:  
 Black avoids the 'Spanish torture' of the main lines.   There are good chances for active piece play.   We immediately get to establish a foothold on the light squares.   If White plays inaccurately in the opening, Black's activity can mean he has chances for an attack.   By reaching 'our variation' on move 5, we avoid various deviations that White can play compared to say, the Marshall, White has fewer chances to deviate before we get to play 'our' opening.   For this reason, there isn't as much theory to know.   It's possible that White may also be less prepared for the Open Variation than the traditional main lines of the Ruy Lopez.  

CONS:  
 The forcing nature of the play means that sometimes the game can fizzle out into something relatively dry.   If White knows his theory perfectly, there are probably fewer winning chances to be had for the second player than in a quieter setup.   Black's path to equality is somewhat narrower than in some other openings.   There are certain concrete lines that must be memorized.   White has a space advantage.   The pawn on e5 can signal a future Kingside attack should Black play inaccurately. }
1. -- {  } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Spanish: Summary of Options"]
[Result "*"]

{ Black has many options to choose from when deciding what to play against the Ruy Lopez.   In my  (FD)  course on the Open Sicilian, I did a quick breakdown of nearly all of White's options against the Najdorf, and why I didn't feel they were suitable for the repertoire. The Najdorf is such an important opening and White has so many options against it that it's worth having some idea about many 6th move options if you intend to play the Open Sicilian. The same is true with playing the Black side of the Ruy Lopez, so I thought I would do a  similar thing here.   The following is a quick breakdown of all of the Spanish variations at Black's disposal, highlighting some of their pros and cons. Please note that these conclusions are extremely oversimplified and should not put you off any of these lines if you personally enjoy them : }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ For the record, any 3rd move that I don't mention here is just not sound enough to be particularly reliable. Anyway, 3...a6 has been an extremely important move since Morphy. I've played it far more than any other 3rd move, and as far as I can remember, I've played it exclusively in tournament games.   a The Steinitz with  3...d6  4.d4  is too passive. Black cannot effectively hold the centre and therefore tends to have to enter a not particularly inspiring version of the e4 vs d6 structure.   b  3...Be7  is similar to 3...d6.   c The Bird's defense with  3...Nd4  4.Nxd4  exd4  5.O-O  is pretty good for White. Practically speaking it's also not too fun to face a kingside attack following the eventual advance of the f-pawn.   d The Classical variation after  3...Bc5  is a natural move with a long history, but there's no fully satisfying answer to  4.c3!   e  3...Nge7  is not a move I held a very high opinion of a few years ago, but the Cozio seems to be undergoing a bit of a revival.  4.d4  is recommended by my co-author in the course Ruy Lopez Rebooted as being a nice path to an edge for White.   4.Nc3  is dangerous, when the best move seems to be  4...Ng6  Here, White can choose between  5.d4  with slightly passive positions for Black and  5.h4  which is very sharp and dangerous.   4.c3  is not meant to be theoretically strongest anymore, but it's still a bit tricky for Black.  4...d5!  I vaguely remember David Howell saying that this line is part of his blitz repertoire, but that it doesn't really work. However, it has been rehabilitated recently, not least by Erwin L'Ami in his Chessable course.   4.O-O  is a 'default' move and perhaps not strictly the best, but Black comes under some pressure here as well.  4...g6  5.c3  and so on.   f There's the Smyslov with  3...g6  4.d4  exd4  5.Bg5  For practical purposes, this is my main issue with the 3...g6 Smyslov. White has a tiny edge, and these positions are just not very fun for Black in my opinion. There's also the matter of more theoretically critical options.   5.c3  is probably more dangerous theoretically and also does not seem particularly fun to face.    Finally  4.c3  is also critical.   g  3...f5  The Schliemann often sees Black needing to hold various positions a pawn down. It's often not so much compensation for the material in the form of attacking chances, but moreso having enough play to maintain the balance. In certain lines White is playing for two results.  4.d3  fxe4  5.dxe4  Nf6  6.O-O  Bc5  7.Bxc6  is one such variation.     4.Nc3  fxe4  5.Nxe4  Nf6  6.Nxf6+  Qxf6  7.Qe2  Be7  8.Bxc6  and both pawn recaptures are decent, but personally I don't find either of them entirely satisfying from a practical perspective. Of course, your tastes may differ.   h  3...Nf6  The Berlin is a very good defense. However, I'm not sure I'd personally want to invite an early queen exchange in every game against 1.e4 as my main repertoire. Again, tastes vary.  4.O-O  Nxe4  5.Re1  is what puts a lot of sub-GM players off the Berlin.  5...Nd6  6.Nxe5  Be7  7.Bf1  Nxe5  8.Rxe5  O-O  9.d4  White can obtain some modest pressure in a position with a symmetrical structure.     7...Nf5!?  is a touch more dynamic, but also gives White slightly better chances for an edge.     5.d4  Nd6  and here there are several options:     6.dxe5  leads to a forced draw in one of the main lines. It's avoidable, but that's another thing to keep in mind.     6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.dxe5  Nf5  8.Qxd8+  Kxd8  This queenless middlegame/endgame is not as boring as its reputation, especially if Black opts for a plan with ...Kc8. I've played this in blitz a bunch of times, and my main complaint is that the kingside majority is sometimes scary to face. I don't think I'd want to aim for this as my main choice with Black, but many players are willing and able to play this line for a win.     4...Bc5  5.Nxe5!  is better for White.     4.d3  is also challenging and was explored in detail in my co-author's course on the Ruy Lopez. }
4. Ba4
{ 4.Bxc6  dxc6  5.O-O  and Black has about as many serious options as he did on move three! I'm not going to summarize them all here, however. }
4... Nf6
{ 4...Bc5  5.c3  is similar to 3...Bc5.   4...g6  5.d4  exd4  6.Nxd4  is better for White.     5.c3  is another good option.   4...b5  5.Bb3  Na5  6.O-O  is very risky for Black. He falls very far behind in development for the sake of the bishop pair.   i The deferred Cozio  4...Nge7  5.c3  is better for White. In comparison to 3...Nge7 4.c3, the ...d5 push doesn't work nearly as well here.   j The deferred Steinitz  4...d6  is better than 3...d6, because the inclusion of ...a6 and Ba4 means that Black can break the pin with a timely ...b5. Therefore, an immediate d2-d4 is not terribly effective.  5.O-O  Bd7  6.c3  g6  7.d4  Bg7  8.Re1  Nf6  9.h3  O-O  These sorts of positions are playable for Black, but they can be a bit passive. Personally the plan of d4-d5* and swapping light squared bishops concerns me, because it feels like a less exciting version of a KID.     5.c3  f5!?  can be fun although the name, the 'Siesta Variation', doesn't imply such, although it is risky, and one main line leads to a quite drawish position. }
5. O-O
{ 5.d3  ,  5.Qe2  ,  5.d4  ,  5.Nc3  and  5.Bxc6  are among the other options, but none are anywhere near as popular as 5. O-O. }
5... Be7
{ I played various lines beginning with this move for a long time. However, one annoyance is sheer number of deviations that can occur before reaching 'your' opening. Compare, for example, the Breyer and the Schliemann. One big advantage of the latter is the opportunity to impose a certain type of game from an early stage.   k  5...Bc5  is an interesting finesse on the usual Arkhangelsk Systems. The drawbacks are as follows:  6.c3  O-O   6...b5  7.Bc2  leads to an improved version of various main lines for White if ...d6 is played, while the sharp line  7...d5  8.a4  is quite dangerous.  7.d4  Ba7  8.dxe5  Black also has to be willing to entertain positions with a Bg5 pin and a potential sacrifice on g5 after ...h6 and ...g5.  8...Nxe4  9.Qd5  Nc5  10.Bc2  Ne7  11.Qd1  d5  12.exd6  Qxd6  13.Qxd6  cxd6  and Black is fine, but probably not having that much fun.   l  5...b5  6.Bb3  Bc5  The Modern-Arkhangelsk, also known as the Neo-Arkhalgelsk, is a good line. I played it in a tournament game once. I was once crushed, but that's not really the opening's fault. It's a very attractive variation, in my opinion, with reasonable chances for exciting play if White goes wrong. However, some of the main lines weren't all that appealing to me.   6...Be7  is just an inaccurate move order. 5...Be7 6.Re1 b5 should be preferred.   6...Bb7  can lead to some sharp and interesting positions. I explored these a while ago and here are two lines that did the most to dissuade me from playing this way on a regular basis.  7.d3  is a nice move, solidifying e4 and thereby arguing that the bishop on b7 is misplaced.   7.Re1  Bc5  8.c3  d6  9.d4  Bb6  10.Be3  O-O  11.Nbd2  h6  12.h3  Re8  13.d5  Ne7  14.Bxb6  cxb6  I wasn't a massive fan of this sort of thing for Black.  7.a4  Rb8   7...Bb7  and again White can either play d2-d3 or go for the c3/d4/Be3 plan. There are other options as well, of course but these are the two that annoy me the most.  8.c3  d6  9.d4  Bb6  10.axb5   10.a5  is currently pretty well regarded. This is what I faced in my game, although my position was reasonable until completely misplaying it.  axb5  11.Na3  The chess elite seem to have moved on from this pawn grab, but I was never all that happy to sacrifice a pawn for compensation that somehow feels a bit vague. Admittedly, this variation has never been a huge part of my repertoire with either side, and I have no practical experience in it, but it feels like the sort of 'learn a bunch of theory in order to hold' type of pawn-down position.  11...O-O  12.Nxb5  Bg4  etc.   m  5...Nxe4  The Open Spanish is what this course is about! It's not perfect obviously, but I think it's as good a repertoire choice as anything else. See the'pros and cons' section for further discussion. }
6. Re1
{ 6.d3  is a particularly important deviation.   6.Qe2  ,  6.d4  ,  6.Bxc6  ,  and  6.Nc3  are possible sidelines. }
6... b5 7. Bb3 d6
{ n  7...O-O  invites the Marshall Attack. I played this for several years. I never really bothered to learn that much theory, which proved to be an issue once or twice. I met the main lines of the Marshall itself fairly infrequently, which meant that when I did face a prepared opponent, it would often go badly. Of course, my poor preparation is hardly an argument against playing a certain opening, and even still my results were decent. However, in many ways the Marshall Attack is quite impractical for non-Grandmasters.  8.c3  d5  etc.     8.a4  are the main 'Anti-Marshalls'.     8.h3  Bb7 }
8. c3 O-O 9. h3
{ I quite like  9.d4  here for White, but that's a topic for another time. }
9... Na5
{ o  9...Nb8  The ingenious Breyer Variation, which is very heavily strategic and can be difficult to play well at least I have found this to be the case.  10.d4  Nbd7  11.Nbd2  Bb7  12.Bc2  etc. White is a bit better theoretically and also has an easier position to play.   p  9...Bb7  The Zaitsev Variation is interesting, reasonably sound and quite dynamic. Unfortunately, White has an opportunity to invite a draw.  10.d4  Re8  11.Ng5   11.Nbd2  Bf8  12.a4   12.d5  is dangerous as well.   Meanwhile, Alex recommends  12.a3  in The Ruy Lopez Rebooted.  h6  13.Bc2  exd4  14.cxd4  Nb4  15.Bb1  c5  16.d5  Nd7  17.Ra3  is, historically, the main line. Interesting and dynamic stuff, but there is some concern over the safety of Black's king.  Rf8  12.Nf3  You many be wondering whether people actually do try to go for a draw in this way. Well, it's probably not all that fun to have to worry about it anyway, but I did once have a lower rated opponent try to repeat the position in a rapid game. I deviated with ...Qd7 not a terrible move, but not particularly ideal either and was crushed. Okay, you don't need to get massacred just because you avoided a draw by playing a slightly dubious line, but you get the point.   q  9...Nd7  isn't a move I know very much about, but it's named after Karpov, so it must be decent. That being said, it's never really caught on to the extent of the Chigorin, Breyer or Zaitsev, so I doubt it's that great either.   r  9...h6  is a bit too passive.   s  9...Be6  I don't know very much about this move either, but swapping the bishops doesn't appear to be that much to write home about.   t  9...a5  is in some ways logical; it makes sense to gain queenside space. However, concretely it doesn't give Black enough counterplay. }
10. Bc2 c5
{ is the venerable Chigorin Variation. Unfortunately, it seems to be in some theoretical trouble these days. }
11. d4 Nd7
{ was my go-to for several years before I took up the Marshall. It's a dynamic line, but it was pretty risky even at the time. Nowadays, White has come up with   11...Qc7  12.d5  is somewhat difficult for Black, both theoretically and practically. White has a space advantage and some clear plans, and it can be a struggle to find adequate counterplay. }
12. a4
{ is a challenging option.   12.Nbd2  is another option.  12...exd4  13.cxd4  Nc6  14.d5  Nce5  15.Nxe5  Nxe5  and play is very interesting, but sometimes frightening for Black.   Feels like we went through almost the entire alphabet, Black really does have many options!   In summary, you almost definitely have different stylistic preferences, tolerance for risk, tolerance for drawishness, amount of time to learn theory, and so on. However, hopefully you found this discussion useful. You may get a bit of a pessimistic picture of the Ruy Lopez for Black from this discussion, but that's because I focused on the negatives in a bit of a 'process of elimination' exercise. Any line that is regularly employed by Grandmasters would be a good addition to your repertoire if you like the positions that arise from it. }
