[SetUp "1"]

{ This position appeared on the board in Svidler-Sutovsky, Heraklio 2007, as well as a few prior games. The first player has a solid advantage due to an inaccuracy from his opponent. }
15. Qc2
{ In this structure with d4/e5 against d5 occuring generally after ...NxNd4 and c3xNd4, Black needs to get the ... c5 break in. Otherwise, he remains stuck with a big hole on c5 and a backward c-pawn on a half-open file. The text crucially prevents this pawn break.   15.Be3  is also reasonable. }
15... Qd7 16. Bd2
{ 16.Nc5  is also possible. Svidler opts not to enter the position with bishops of opposite colour. }
16... Bf5 17. Nc5
{ 17.Qc1  a4  18.Nc5  Qc6  19.Bb4⩲  is the computer's preference. Black is hardly losing, but his position remains unpleasant. }
17... Bxc2 18. Nxd7 Rfd8 19. Rac1 Bf5 20. Nc5 Ra7
{ 20...Bxc5?  21.Rxc5+-  wins a pawn and is therefore hardly a solution for Black. }
21. Bf4 b4 22. e6 fxe6
{ leaves the e7 bishop exposed.   22...Bf6  23.exf7  Kxf7  was the way to go. }
23. Nxe6 Bxe6 24. Rxe6 Bf6
{ is a mistake.   24...Bd6  25.Bxd6  cxd6  26.Rc6  Kf7  27.Rexd6  Rxd6  28.Rxd6  Rc7  29.g3  Rc1+  30.Kg2  Ra1=  would have maintainted the balance. }
25. Be5 Bxe5 26. Rxe5 Rd6 27. Re7
{ The reason why I included this entire sequence is because White now picks up the unfortunate c7-pawn. Svidler went on to win. }
