[FEN "r3kb1r/2p3pp/p1n1p3/1pn1P3/8/1BPq4/P2N1PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 0 14"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ One thing to keep in mind in the Open Spanish is that White has castled on move five, whereas Black sometimes delays it for longer. Under the right or wrong set of circumstances, this can prove extremely dangerous. The following is probably the most famous ever Open Spanish game I guess there's that one where Black takes on d4 on move six and then plays 14...f5 running into 15. Bg5#. Can you actually tell me the names of two players that have played that game though?; Kasparov-Anand, New York World Championship, 1995. }
14. Bc2
{ This was the second time Anand had entered this variation in the match. He got away with it the first time, but Kasparov had prepared a stunning improvement for the second encounter.   14.Nf3  was not only Kasparov's choice the first time around, but was also played by Karpov in his 1978 World Championship Match against Korchnoi in Baguio City. It's relatively harmless and both games were drawn. }
14... Qxc3 15. Nb3 Nxb3 16. Bxb3
{ Black's king is still two moves away from relative safety on g8, and White's pieces are ready to spring into action. }
16... Nd4
{ 16...Qxa1?  17.Qh5+  g6  18.Qf3  Nd8  and now one winning line is the very pretty:  19.Qf6  Rg8  20.Bxe6  Be7  21.Bd7+!  Kxd7  22.e6+  Nxe6  23.Qxa1+- }
17. Qg4 Qxa1 { 17...Be7  is better, but the trouble is far from over. } 18.
Bxe6 Rd8 19. Bh6 { What a move, the bishop is untouchable! } 19... Qc3
{ 19...gxh6  20.Qh5+  Ke7  21.Qf7  is the point. } 20. Bxg7 Qd3 21. Bxh8 Qg6
22. Bf6 Be7 23. Bxe7 Qxg4 24. Bxg4 Kxe7 25. Rc1
{ with a winning endgame that Kasparov converted. } *

