1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Qe2
{ This is the least common of White's four main lines on move 9. The general idea is to play Rd1 followed by c4. }
9... Be7 10. Rd1 O-O 11. c4 bxc4 12. Bxc4 Bc5 13. Be3 Bxe3 14. Qxe3 Qb8 15. Bb3
Na5
{ Unfortunately, this variation does have drawish tendencies. In many lines, a Rook endgame is reached by force, in which neither side should be able to make progress. The good news is that if Black memorizes the lines I've provided, he should have no problems, and if White deviates, the game goes on  (with good chances for Black)  . The bad news is of course that you're basically committing drawing sequences to memory, which isn't terribly appealing. }
