[White "Repertoire Outline"]
[Black "9.Be3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Be3
{ This is White's third most common move. It's a logical move, which both develops a piece and discourages ...Bc5. }
9... Be7 10. c3 Qd7
{ This slightly unusual line is my suggestion.   I initially wanted to recommend  10...Nc5  11.Bc2  Nd7  , but wasn't entirely satisfied with the position after  12.Nd4   which is an interesting pawn sacrifice.   The main line is  10...O-O  11.Nbd2  Qd7  , but I think that Black can extract some benefit from delaying castling. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Repertoire Outline"]
[Black "Repertoire 1 | 9.Nbd2 Nc5 and 9.c3 Bc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 { If you opt to follow Repertoire 1, we recommend } 9... Nc5 10. c3
{ And here we give you the choice between two different approaches:   a The solid  10...Be7  when Black only pushes the d-pawn after  11.Bc2  d4  intending to push ahead with ...d3 to restrict White's light-squared bishop.   b The immediate central break  10...d4  which is Black's most enterprising continuation. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Repertoire Outline"]
[Black "Repertoire 2 | 9.Nbd2 Be7 and 9.c3 Be7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2
{ This is the main line.   9.c3  is the former main line and currently the second most common move. White fights for the d4 square and gives the Bishop a retreat square on c2.   If you're following Repertoire 2, I suggest  9.Nbd2  Be7  . Note that this would not be consistent with Repertoire 1, as we do not play an early ...Be7 against the Nbd2 system there. Therefore, 10. Nbd2 would take us out of that repertoire. Following this one, however, 10. Nbd2 amounts simply to a transposition to the main line.   9.c3  Be7  10.Bc2  O-O  11.Nbd2  f5  would also transpose into the main line, although White has alternatives on move 11.   Finally,   10.Be3  transposes to the 9.Be3 system, while    10.Re1  is a sharp, independent line. }
9... Be7
{ The main line, which is usually recommended here for Black, is  9...Nc5  10.c3  Be7  11.Bc2  d4  is a good choice as well. I have a particular fondness for the variation with ...Be7, ...O-O, and ...f5. We did, however, also recommend  9...Nc5  10.c3  d4  . }
10. c3 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 { This system makes up the core of this repertoire. } 12.
Nb3 { 12.exf6  is a major alternative. } 12... Qd7 13. Nbd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 c5
15. Nxe6 Qxe6 16. f3 Ng5 17. a4 Rad8 18. axb5 axb5
{ This is the very main line of this variation, which we will discuss in detail in the course. }
