[White "Repertoire Outline"]
[Black "Spanish Sidelines"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4
{ 4.Bxc6  The exchange Spanish is White's only serious 4th move alternative. }
4... Nf6
{ We cover all of White's reasonable alternatives to  5.O-O  , namely   5.d3  which is White's 2nd most popular 5th move.   The Worrall variation with  5.Qe2  is 3rd most common.   The delayed exchange Spanish with  5.Bxc6  .   The simple developing move  5.Nc3  where White foregoes any intentions of establishing a big center with  c3  and  d4  .   And finally  5.c3  which is seldom seen. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Exchange Spanish"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6
{ The Exchange Spanish, where White gives up the two bishops to slightly damage our queenside pawn structure. Ideally, White would like to trade down to an endgame where the superior pawn structure plays a major role. Conversely, Black should in general avoid piece exchanges and strive for active play, particularly making use of the two bishops.  Nowadays, the Exchange variation is rarely played at the top level nowadays given that Black has several lines that promise easy equality. }
4... dxc6 5. O-O
{ This flexible option is White's main move. With the king on g1, the first player is now threatening to take on e5. }
5... Qf6
{ Black has several good options at this junction. This queen sortie is my preferred option as it gives Black more chances to play for a full point than  5...Bd6  or  5...Bg4  . }
6. d4 { Expanding in the center is the only testing continuation. } 6... exd4
7. Bg5
{ 7.Qxd4  has been seen but the resulting endgame is once again very comfortable for Black.  7...Qxd4  8.Nxd4  Bd7= }
7... Qd6
{ It may seem as if White has gained time on our queen. On closer inspection, these tempi are irrelevant given that we're only two or three moves away from castling long. }
8. Nxd4 Be7
{ Neutralizes the bishop on g5, which is White's most active piece. Once the bishop moves away from the h4-d8 diagonal, we'll easily castle long. }
9. Bxe7 Nxe7
{ Now that White's bishop is gone from g5, there's no stopping ...Bd7 followed by ... O-O-O. }
10. Nc3 Bd7 11. Nb3 O-O-O
{ Black has no problems whatsoever. Given enough time, we can even consider anchoring the knight on e5 and following up with ...g5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "5.Qe2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. Qe2
{ This is the Worrall Variation, which has been part of my repertoire at various points in time. White covers the e4 pawn, thus avoiding the Open Variation, while also clearing the d1 square for a Rook to use in the future. }
5... Be7
{ I've chosen to recommend a Marshall-adjacent approach, which gains in strength with White's Queen on e2. Naturally, lines with ...Bc5 are also totally okay. }
6. O-O
{ This and  6.c3  are quite liable to transpose into each other, although both have their own independent options. }
6... b5 7. Bb3 O-O
{ As in the Marshall, Black delays ...d6, so he can push in the centre with ...d5. }
8. c3
{ White prepares d2-d4. If he's allowed to get that in, he may have chances for an advantage. We should beat him to it. }
8... d5
{ This Marshall-style Gambit is very strong. It's so strong, in fact, that White is generally advised not to accept it. }
9. d3
{ This solid move secures the centre. The Queen being on e2 means that there is no Queen trade available to Black, and Rd1 followed by d4 often exists as an idea. }
9... Be6
{ This move hasn't been terribly common in practice so far, but relatively recently, it came to light that it is quite strong. Black avoids spending a move on ...h6, arguing that Bg5 is harmless, and Ng5 backfires after ...Bg4.  With a well-defended central pawn duo and good development, Black can look to the future with confidence. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "5.d4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d4
{ I can personally attest that this line is tricky to meet when you don't know very much about it. However, once you've learned a few key details, it becomes significantly less scary. }
5... exd4 6. O-O Be7 7. Re1 b5 8. Bb3 d6 9. Bd5
{ This is a reasonable attempt to win the pawn back without getting his Bishop trapped, but White has to give up this Bishop in the process. }
9... Nxd5 10. exd5 Ne5 11. Nxd4 O-O
{ Black has two Bishops and a well-placed Knight on e5. The first player may have a space advantage due to his d5-pawn, but this pawn is also liable to become weak in the future. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "5.d3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 d6
{ Black has many good options at this junction. The text is a favorite of mine as its very practical and easy to learn. I'll be recommending Black fianchetto the dark-squared bishop on g7, from where it covers the e5 pawn and can become very active once we break with ...d5. }
6. c3
{ White creates a square for the bishop on c2, thus neutralizing the positional 'threat' of ... b5 followed by ...Na5. }
6... g6 7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1 O-O 9. Nbd2 Re8
{ We're now planning ...b5 followed by ...d5 and there is very little White can do to stop this. Black has a good game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "5.O-O 6.Re1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. Re1
{ This is a move which is often played by more inexperienced players. White does indeed win his pawn back, but Black obtains the Bishop pair. }
6... Nc5 { This attacks the Bishop on a4, prompting an exchange. } 7. Bxc6 dxc6
8. Nxe5 { 8.d4  Ne6  9.Nxe5  Be7  comes to the same thing. } 8... Be7
{ Developing a piece and blocking the e-file. } 9. d4 Ne6
{ This is not primarily a theory driven position. Play revolves more around strategy for the next few moves, and since this line is far from critical for Black, I won't have you memorize variations from here. We will, however, take a look at some games from this position in the Annotated Games section, in order to become familiar with the ideas. Black has the two Bishops and, incidentally, despite the doubled pawns on the queenside, this structure is less challenging for the second player than, say, the Exchange Spanish, because White lacks a pawn majority to advance in an endgame. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "6.d4 9.a4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5
{ Black takes a stake in the center, opens up the light-squared bishop and anchors the knight on e4. }
8. dxe5 Be6 9. a4
{ Immediately undermining the queenside yields White very little as Black can simply bypass the a-pawn. }
9... b4 10. a5
{ This is what 'everyone' plays here, splitting the a6 and b4-pawns Go-style, taking away a5 from Black's Knight and opening the a4 square for White's Bishop. The computer is really not a fan of it, however. }
10... Nc5
{ Black introduces the possibility of taking on b3 while also depriving the Bishop of the a4 square. }
11. Bg5
{ This is, again, the follow-up that almost everybody plays, and once again, it seems dubious. }
11... Qd7
{ Black removes his Queen from attack, places it on quite a natural square, and will now gain time against the errant Bishop on g5. }
12. Nbd2 h6 13. Bh4 g5 14. Bg3 Be7
{ Black will likely castle long and pursue dangerous play on the kingside, both in connection to harassing White's pieces ...h5-h4/...g4 and trying to undermine the support of the e5 pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "9.Qe2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Qe2
{ This is a fairly natural move with a specific point in mind. White wants to put his Rook on d1, opposing Black's Queen, and then break with c2-c4 to disturb Black's solid position. }
9... Be7 { Black, for his part, is content to develop naturally. } 10. Rd1 O-O
11. c4 bxc4 12. Bxc4 Bc5
{ With White's Rook no longer on f1, Black hopes to ease some of the pressure on his position by threatening the f2 pawn prompting an exchange of Bishops. }
13. Be3 Bxe3 14. Qxe3 Qb8
{ This is a key idea for Black to escape the entanglement along the d-file. This move unpins the d-pawn, thereby pseudo-threatening the Bishop on c4, and also attacks the b2 pawn. It also prepares to swing the Queen around to a decent square on b6.   Importantly  15.Bxd5??  loses to  15...Bxd5  16.Rxd5  Qxb2  as the rook on a1 is trapped. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "9.Be3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Be3
{ This is the third most common move, but it's an extremely natural one. White develops a piece and fights for control of the dark squares. }
9... Be7 10. c3 Qd7
{ This is not the most common move, but I think it's a decent way to get an interesting game. Black prepares ...Rd8 while activating his Queen. I'm going to recommend delaying castling for a few moves, to avoid attacks from White down the b1-h7 diagonal. }
11. Nbd2 Nxd2
{ This is a somewhat uncommon move. The problem with allowing Nxe4 not that this is a bad approach at all is that it leads to exchanges and an endgame where Black has a worse pawn structure. Such endgames tend to be holdable, but they're not so much fun. }
12. Qxd2 Na5
{ A typical move for this line; Black prepares both ...c5 and ...Nc4 hitting the Queen and Bishop with a good game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "9.c3 Bc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. c3
{ The text used to be White's main move but is now second to  9.Nbd2  popularity-wise. It should be noted that there are plenty of possible transpositions between the two.  White establishes a stronghold over the d4 square and creates a square for the light-squared bishop on c2, which effectively takes the sting out of ...Nc5. }
9... Bc5
{ is the most popular and ambitious continuation. The bishop is most active on c5 from where it controls key central squares and stares down f2.  The more solid   9...Be7  is analyzed in the next chapter. }
10. Nbd2 O-O 11. Bc2 Nxf2
{ Boom goes the dynamite or better put the Dilworth attack! This enterprising move is named after Vernon Dilworth, who was the first to play it consistently in the 1940s. In exchange for two minor pieces, Black gets a rook, typically 1-2 pawns and most importantly a dangerous initiative. We're in for some very exciting, attacking chess! }
12. Rxf2 f6
{ is a key follow-up. There is no need to take on f2 right away given the rook isn't going anywhere. Instead, Black adds gasoline to the fire by blasting open the f-file! }
13. Nb3 { Moving pieces away from the kingside is inadvisable. } 13... Bxf2+
{ lands White in hot water. } 14. Kxf2 fxe5
{ With ...e4 and ... Bg4 on the way, White is in big trouble.   14...fxe5  15.Kg1  Bg4  16.h3  Bxf3  17.gxf3  e4∓  White's pieces are all on the queenside while his king is completely bare on g1. Black's attack will be practically decisive. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "9.Nbd2 Be7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2
{ This is White's main move. He challenges the central Knight on e4 while developing a piece. }
9... Be7
{ The modern main line is  9...Nc5  10.c3  Be7  11.Bc2  d4  , which can lead to sharp positions revolving around Black's advanced d-pawn or one of a few endgames. The text leaves the Knight on  e4  for the time being, with one idea being to support it with  ...f7-f5  . }
10. c3 { This is the main line, preparing Bc2. } 10... O-O
{ Black continues to leave his Knight in the centre. } 11. Bc2 f5
{ Black supports his Knight on e4. ...Nc5 is legal, but having already kept it on e4, it makes sense to continue to leave it there. }
12. Nb3
{ White's knight is headed to the d4 outpost - a very natural continuation. }
12... Qd7
{ Black has comfortably developed all his pieces and the a8 rook is about to come to d8.   In case of  13.Nbd4  Black can continue with  13...Nxd4  14.Nxd4  c5=  with good prospects. There's a large body of theory stemming from this position, which is covered in detail in themain theoretical section of the course. }
