1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. Re1 Nc5 7. Nc3
{ This is a tricky attempt, but not really anything more than that. White wants to play Nd5 and cause confusion in Black's position. }
7... Be7
{ 7...Nxa4  8.Nxe5  Be7  9.Nd5!  wins the piece back after, e.g.  9...Nc5  10.Nxc6  dxc6  11.Nxe7  , but  11...Be6  nonetheless avoids trouble. }
8. Nd5 f6
{ Black defends the e5 pawn. White can win his pawn back by force, but we have an idea in mind. }
9. Bxc6 dxc6 10. Nxe7 Qxe7 11. d4 Ne6 12. dxe5 f5
{ Black is already slightly better here, as the e5 pawn is completely blockaded, while he is free to expand on both sides of the board. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "White Avoids the Main Line"]
[Black "7.d5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. d5
{ This is a rare move which does not work out very well for White. } 7... bxa4
8. dxc6 d6
{ Black is already significantly better. White can regain his pawn back on a4 sooner or later, but Black has excellent play with ...f7-f5 coming up, not to mention the potential weakness on c6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "White Avoids the Main Line"]
[Black "7.Nxe5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Nxe5
{ This is a very unusual move order, but it isn't so bad. } 7... Nxe5
{ 7...bxa4  is equally possible, but leads to complications after  8.Qe2  , which aren't practical to learn for such a rare variation. }
8. dxe5
{ White's point is that  8...bxa4  is met by  9.Qd5  , regaining this piece. This is a plausible option for Black, but I've chosen to recommend something else. }
8... d5
{ This is the easiest move to learn.   Now, the best move -  9.Bb3  - would transpose into the  8.Nxe5  variation, which covered starting here. Instead, the alternatives are bad. }
9. exd6 Bxd6
{ Black has very active pieces, and will likely have a very strong kingside initiative. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "White Avoids the Main Line"]
[Black "8.Nxe5 #1 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. Nxe5
{ This is a quite rare but interesting option for White. The basic idea is that by exchanging knights, the f-pawn will now be free to advance. }
8... Nxe5 9. dxe5 c6
{ With the d-pawn under threat, Black solidly covers it, not yet committing his c8 Bishop, which may rather go to f5 than e6. This is the downside of White's idea to exchange knights: we are able to use our c-pawn from a very early stage. }
10. Be3 Be7 11. Nd2 Nxd2 12. Qxd2 O-O 13. c3 Bf5
{ Black is totally fine here. His pieces occupy decent squares and he's under no particular pressure at the moment. Future plans may include ...a5-a4 and ...f6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "White Avoids the Main Line"]
[Black "8.Nxe5 #2 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. Nxe5
Nxe5 9. dxe5 c6 10. Nd2
{ This is slightly more challenging than  10.Be3  , which we previously looked at. White immediately provokes an exchange of Knights, and will subsequently look for play on the Kingside. }
10... Nxd2 11. Bxd2
{ This is the most played move, but my co-author chessforlife believes that it is not the best. His reasoning is that White would like to be able to play c3, Bc2 and Qd3 with a battery towards the kingside, but recapturing with the Bishop inhibits this idea. }
11... Be7 12. Qh5
{ This is an interesting move. White puts his Queen in the general vicinity of Black's King and stops ...Bf5.   12.c3  Bf5  leads to fine play for Black in the style of the previous variation. }
12... Be6 13. c3
{ White has the idea of targeting h7 with Bc2. Hence, we should delay castling for a bit longer. }
13... Qd7
{ This introduces the idea of ...Bg4, but also generally takes further control over the light squares, which is useful in a structure where f4-f5 is one of White's major ideas. It also allows for Bc2 to be met with ...Bf5 in the future. }
14. Bg5 Bg4 15. Qh4 Bc5
{ Exchanging these Bishops is also okay, but Black reasons that the g5 Bishop is now hitting air, whereas c5 is a nice square for his own piece. Chessforlife stops here, with an assessment of equality. Let's look at a couple more moves. }
16. Rae1 O-O
{ It is now safe to castle, as the Bc2 idea no longer carries so much weight. }
17. Bc2 Bf5
{ Black has neutralized White's kingside pressure and is completely fine. Black can now look to activate his Rooks and expand on the Queenside at some point. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "White Avoids the Main Line"]
[Black "8.Nxe5 #3 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. Nxe5
Nxe5 9. dxe5 c6 10. Nd2 Nxd2 11. Qxd2 Bf5
{ This makes sense, developing the Queen's Bishop first pre-empts the c3/Bc2 plan. }
12. Qf4
{ This is another idea of recapturing with the Queen. White attacks the Bishop on f5 and later may swing the Queen back to g3, from where it can participate in a Kingside attack. }
12... Bg6 13. a4 Be7 14. c3 O-O 15. Be3
{ was my recommendation in the Chessable course The Ruy Lopez Rebooted. As mentioned there, White has interesting play based on Qg3 and f2-f4 but the position remains balanced. }
15... Qd7
{ Admittedly, White's position is slightly more pleasant here, but it's to hard to ascertain exactly how he will make progress. The eventual f4-f5 plan suggests itself, but Black has a decent stronghold on the light squares, which may be furthered by ...h7-h5. As far as counterplay goes, ...f6 is possible, as is ...bxa4 followed by ...a5, with the idea to use the half-open b-file. }
