[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9th Move Sidelines"]
[Black "9.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nc3
{ This is an odd move that gets played from time to time. White invites the doubling of his pawns for no particular gain. }
9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 Be7
{ Now, as far as I can tell, the only way to make sense of White's play is to play: }
11. Nd4
{ This provokes the undoubling of the c-pawns due to the pseudo-threat to take on e6. }
11... Nxd4 12. cxd4
{ 12.Qxd4  would not only be very inconsistent, but it would also get Noah's Ark'd after  12...c5  13.Qd1  c4  , when the Bishop on b3 is trapped. }
12... c5 { Black has sufficient counterplay against White's centre. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9th Move Sidelines"]
[Black "9.Re1 (Short Variation) #1 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Re1
{ This move is not bad at all. Nigel Short has played it several times. The downside is that it's a fairly generic move; far from useless but also not really the most useful move in the position. }
9... Bc5
{ This seems like the most logical move to me. Black develops a piece while attacking f2. This 'attack' isn't really going anywhere, as White will in all likelihood play Be3 and swap Bishops. Nonetheless, this does relieve a bit of the pressure on Black's position. }
10. Be3 O-O
{ Taking on  e3  seems fine as well. By waiting for a moment, we avoid the option of  10...Bxe3  11.Rxe3  O-O  12.Nc3  Nxc3  13.Rxc3  , although this shouldn't be too big of a deal. }
11. Nbd2 Bxe3 12. Rxe3 Nc5
{ Black hints at taking on b3, but his main idea is to push ...d4. } 13. c3 d4
{ Black usually can count on a decent position when he executes this break. }
14. cxd4 Nxd4
{ Black is fine here. His pieces are active, and in the long-term he can look to use his Queenside pawns with ...c5-c4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9th Move Sidelines"]
[Black "9.Re1 (Short Variation) #2 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Re1
{ This move is not bad at all. Nigel Short has played it several times. The downside is that it's a fairly generic move; far from useless but also not really the most useful move in the position. }
9... Bc5
{ This seems like the most logical move to me. Black develops a piece while attacking f2. This 'attack' isn't really going anywhere, as White will in all likelihood play Be3 and swap Bishops. Nonetheless, this does relieve a bit of the pressure on Black's position. }
10. Be3 O-O
{ Taking on  e3  seems fine as well. By waiting for a moment, we avoid the option of  10...Bxe3  11.Rxe3  O-O  12.Nc3  Nxc3  13.Rxc3  , although this shouldn't be too big of a deal. }
11. c3 Bxe3 12. Rxe3 Qe7
{ ...Nc5 doesn't have as much point when White can just retreat his Bishop to c2. Additionally, ...d4 is harder to achieve when White has yet to place his Queen's Knight on d2. Therefore, Black contents himself with developing. He is intending ...Rad8 next, opposing the White Queen, and seeking a ...d4 break at some stage. }
13. Nbd2 Rad8 14. Qe2 Nxd2
{ This is not such a usual capture in this opening, but it does gain a tempo here. }
15. Qxd2 { 15.Nxd2?!  d4  is excellent for Black. } 15... Na5
{ Black can already claim to be slightly better. ...c7-c5 is coming, and either ...Nxb3 or perhaps more likely ...Nc4 are in the air. The light squares will then be Black's to play on. }
