Be6 9. Re1
{ This move is not bad at all. Nigel Short has played it several times. The downside is that it's a fairly generic move; far from useless but also not really the most useful move in the position. }
9... Bc5
{ This seems like the most logical move to me. Black develops a piece while attacking f2. This 'attack' isn't really going anywhere, as White will in all likelihood play Be3 and swap Bishops. Nonetheless, this does relieve a bit of the pressure on Black's position. }
10. Be3 O-O
{ Taking on  e3  seems fine as well. By waiting for a moment, we avoid the option of  10...Bxe3  11.Rxe3  O-O  12.Nc3  Nxc3  13.Rxc3  , although this shouldn't be too big of a deal. }
11. c3 Bxe3 12. Rxe3 Qe7
{ ...Nc5 doesn't have as much point when White can just retreat his Bishop to c2. Additionally, ...d4 is harder to achieve when White has yet to place his Queen's Knight on d2. Therefore, Black contents himself with developing. He is intending ...Rad8 next, opposing the White Queen, and seeking a ...d4 break at some stage. }
13. Nbd2 Rad8 14. Nd4 Nxd4 15. cxd4 c5
