[White "9th Move Sidelines"]
[Black "9.a4 (Ljubojevic Variation) #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. a4
{ This is the most common of the variations in this chapter. In a vacuum, it's hardly a bad move, but the follow-up that nearly everyone plays is quite questionable, to say the least. }
9... b4 10. a5
{ This is what 'everyone' plays here, splitting the a6 and b4-pawns Go-style, taking away a5 from Black's Knight and opening the a4 square for White's Bishop. The computer is really not a fan of it, however. }
10... Nc5
{ Black introduces the possibility of taking on b3 while also depriving the Bishop of the a4 square. }
11. Bg5
{ This is, again, the follow-up that almost everybody plays, and once again, it seems dubious. }
11... Qd7
{ Black removes his Queen from attack, places it on quite a natural square, and will now gain time against the errant Bishop on g5. }
12. Nbd2 h6 13. Bh4 g5 14. Bg3 Be7
{ Black will likely castle long and pursue dangerous play on the kingside, both in connection to harassing White's pieces ...h5-h4/...g4 and trying to undermine the support of the e5 pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9th Move Sidelines"]
[Black "9.a4 (Ljubojevic Variation) #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. a4
{ This is the most common of the variations in this chapter. In a vacuum, it's hardly a bad move, but the follow-up that nearly everyone plays is quite questionable, to say the least. }
9... b4 10. a5
{ This is what 'everyone' plays here, splitting the a6 and b4-pawns Go-style, taking away a5 from Black's Knight and opening the a4 square for White's Bishop. The computer is really not a fan of it, however. }
10... Nc5
{ Black introduces the possibility of taking on b3 while also depriving the Bishop of the a4 square. }
11. Nbd2
{ Preserving the Bishop with  11.Ba2  is just too slow. After  11...Be7  followed by an eventual ...d5-d4, Black gains space, and the e5 pawn may find itself in serious trouble after a future ...Qd5. Should  12.Nd4  be played, there is an interesting idea available in  12...Nxd4  13.Qxd4  Nb7  , when the mobile queenside majority comes to life following ...c5, and the a5-pawn is quite weak. }
11... Be7
{ White hasn't achieved much with his a4-a5 push. Black can castle, and consider taking on b3 and playing ...d4. }
