[White "9.Qe2 "]
[Black "9.Qe2 (Keres Variation) #1 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Qe2
{ This is a fairly natural move with a specific point in mind. White wants to put his Rook on d1, opposing Black's Queen, and then break with c2-c4 to disturb Black's solid position. }
9... Be7 { Black, for his part, is content to develop naturally. } 10. Rd1 O-O
11. c4 bxc4 12. Bxc4 Bc5
{ With White's Rook no longer on f1, Black hopes to ease some of the pressure on his position by threatening the f2 pawn, prompting an exchange of Bishops. }
13. Be3 Bxe3 14. Qxe3 Qb8
{ This is a key idea for Black to escape the entanglement along the d-file. This move unpins the d-pawn, thereby pseudo-threatening the Bishop on c4, and also attacks the b2 pawn. It also prepares to swing the Queen around to a decent square on b6. White only has one good move. }
15. Bxd5 { This loses. } 15... Bxd5 16. Rxd5 Qxb2
{ White's Rook is trapped on a1. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9.Qe2 "]
[Black "9.Qe2 (Keres Variation) #2 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Qe2
{ This is a fairly natural move with a specific point in mind. White wants to put his Rook on d1, opposing Black's Queen, and then break with c2-c4 to disturb Black's solid position. }
9... Be7 { Black, for his part, is content to develop naturally. } 10. Rd1 O-O
11. c4 bxc4 12. Bxc4 Bc5
{ With White's Rook no longer on f1, Black hopes to ease some of the pressure on his position by threatening the f2 pawn, prompting an exchange of Bishops. }
13. Be3 Bxe3 14. Qxe3 Qb8
{ This is a key idea for Black to escape the entanglement along the d-file. This move unpins the d-pawn, thereby pseudo-threatening the Bishop on c4, and also attacks the b2 pawn. It also prepares to swing the Queen around to a decent square on b6. White only has one good move. }
15. Bb3
{ This moves the Bishop out of attack and blocks the threat to the b2 pawn. }
15... Na5
{ This is a good move. Black both annoys the b3-Bishop and prepares to expand on the queenside with ...c7-c5. }
16. Bxd5
{ This time, taking this pawn does not lose immediately for White. It does, however, lead to a forced draw. }
16... Bxd5 17. Rxd5 Qxb2 18. Qd4
{ This is the only way to cover the Rook on a1. Now, if Black wants to continue the game, he can play several moves, but objectively the best is a repetition. }
18... Qc1+
{ 18...Qxd4  19.Rxd4  Nc5  leads to what may be a very marginally worse endgame, but nothing too scary. The surprising  18...Nc4!?  is also a valid move, with a similar type of endgame arising after  19.Qxb2  Nxb2  . }
19. Qd1 Qb2 20. Qd4 Qc1+ { with a draw. } *

