1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Be3
{ This is the third most common move, but it's an extremely natural one. White develops a piece and fights for control of the dark squares. }
9... Be7 10. Nbd2
{ This is a slightly inaccurate move order. White should instead begin with  10.c3  , allowing for  Bc2  if needed. }
10... Nc5
{ This not only annoys the b3 Bishop, but in some lines it also prepares ...Nd7 to attack the e5 pawn. }
11. c3
{ This is a natural move, but it's not so good here, due to a tactical trick.   Instead,  11.Bxc5  Bxc5  should maintain rough equality, but this is clearly not what White wanted.   11.Qe2?  d4!  is excellent for Black, with  ...d4-d3  upcoming.   Finally  11.Nd4  Nxd4  12.Bxd4  Qd7  is okay, but doesn't give White much, and he always has to look out for a future  ...c5  push. }
11... Nd3
{ Black wins a pawn due to the dual threats on b2 and e5.   A logical continuation is  12.Qb1  Ndxe5  13.Nxe5  Nxe5  14.Bd4  Ng6  15.Bxg7  , winning the pawn back, but after  15...Rg8  16.Bd4  c5  , Black has the initiative and a large advantage. }
