9... Be7 10. c3 Qd7
{ This is not the most common move, but I think it's a decent way to get an interesting game. Black prepares ...Rd8 while activating his Queen. I'm going to recommend delaying castling for a few moves, to avoid attacks from White down the b1-h7 diagonal. }
11. Nbd2 Nxd2
{ This is a somewhat uncommon move. The problem with allowing Nxe4 not that this is a bad approach at all is that it leads to exchanges and an endgame where Black has a worse pawn structure. Such endgames tend to be holdable, but they're not so much fun. }
12. Qxd2 Na5
{ A typical move for this line; Black prepares both ...c5 and ... Nc4 hitting the Queen and Bishop. }
13. Ng5
{ White goes after the e6 Bishop, but this is a little more one-dimensional compared to the more flexible 13.Nd4. }
13... Nc4 14. Bxc4 dxc4 15. Nxe6 Qxe6 16. f4 O-O
{ Black is fine here. In spite of White's healthy pawn majority, it isn't so easy to push f4-f5. First of all, Bd4 is met by ...c5. Secondly, with ...f6 on the horizon, it's far from a guarantee that White will at all have time to prepare an advance on the kingside before being challenged. Black's pawn on c4 allows him to fight for the d-file, i.e. with ...Ra/fd8-d3, and he may also consider doubling with ...Ra/fd8-d5. }
