1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Be3
{ This is the third most common move, but it's an extremely natural one. White develops a piece and fights for control of the dark squares. }
9... Be7 10. c3 Qd7
{ This is not the most common move, but I think it's a decent way to get an interesting game. Black prepares ...Rd8 while activating his Queen. I'm going to recommend delaying castling for a few moves, to avoid attacks from White down the b1-h7 diagonal. }
11. Nbd2 Nxd2
{ This is a somewhat uncommon move. The problem with allowing Nxe4 not that this is a bad approach at all is that it leads to exchanges and an endgame where Black has a worse pawn structure. Such endgames tend to be holdable, but they're not so much fun. }
12. Qxd2 Na5
{ A typical move for this line; Black prepares both ...c5 and ... Nc4 hitting the Queen and Bishop. }
13. Nd4
{ This is a dangerous move. White challenges the e6 Bishop while clearing the way for the f-pawn to advance. }
13... c5 { Black should play aggressively to avoid being run over with f4-f5. }
14. Nxe6 fxe6
{ Black is almost ready to take on b3 and castle, at which point he will be absolutely fine. To pose problems, therefore, White must move his Bishop, which will allow ...Nc4 and thus implies a sacrifice of a pawn. }
15. Bd1
{ This is the less natural, but the more dangerous of the two Bishop moves. }
15... Nc4 16. Qe2
{ This is the only move active enough to give White compensation. He intends to meet ...Nxe5 with a check on h5. Black does not have the option to grab on b2 due to the second rank being clear. }
16... Nxe5
{ 16...Nxe3  is given as an alternative recommendation in thenext line. } 17.
Qh5+ Nf7 18. a4
{ White aims to open the queenside, adding another avenue to his attack. }
18... Rc8
{ Black cedes the a-file, because the attempt to connect Rooks with  18...O-O  runs into  19.Bc2  . }
19. axb5 axb5 20. Ra6 { White puts pressure on the tender e6 pawn. } 20... Rc6
{ Black has to be careful here.  20...O-O  , for example, would be quite bad due to  21.Bc2  , when the second player lacks a good way to meet the mate threat on  h7  . Black should be quite cautious about castling in this position in general.  The text aims to quell the pressure on e6  (which can be amplified with a move like Bg4 or Qg4)  by fighting for the sixth rank. }
21. Ra8+ Rc8 22. Rxc8+ { 22.Ra6  Rc6  could lead to a draw by repetition. }
22... Qxc8
{ Black remains a pawn up, but White has the two Bishops and some attacking potential against our King in the centre. The position is dynamically balanced, but still quite complex. Black may look to expand in the centre with ...e5 at the right moment, as well as kick the Queen and close the b1-h7 diagonal with ...g6. Castling short may follow, but only when Black is sure that his King is safe from any quick attack White might stir up. }
