1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. c3
{ The text used to be White's main move but is now second to  9.Nbd2  popularity-wise. It should be noted that there are plenty of possible transpositions between the two.  White establishes a stronghold over the d4 square and creates a square for the light-squared bishop on c2, which effectively takes the sting out of ...Nc5. }
9... Bc5
{ is the most popular and ambitious continuation. The bishop is most active on c5 from where it controls key central squares and stares down f2.  The more solid   9...Be7  is analyzed in the next chapter. }
10. Bf4 g5 { An enterprising move that forces White to be accurate. } 11. Bc1
{ Going back home is paradoxically White's only good continuation. The first player successfully weakened our kingside, but that came at the cost of two full tempi. }
11... g4
{ Now that the g-pawn is already mobilized, we might as well push it forward to gain space and pick up the e5 pawn. }
12. Nd4 Nxe5 13. a4
{ White's only way of showing any compensation for the pawn is to undermine our queenside.   13.Nd2  Nd6  14.Re1  Qf6  15.Qe2  Bxd4  16.cxd4  Nec4⩱  gives Black the upper hand.   13.Bf4  is no improvement. Following  13...Qf6  14.Bxe5  Qxe5  15.a4  b4∓  Black had a clear advantage, going on to win in 0-1 53 Myers, J. - Stephson, D. Queensland 1994. }
13... Nf3+
{ Boom! The cavalry leaps into the fray, launching a vicious attack against White's king.   13...Qf6Ν  is another good option. }
14. Nxf3 gxf3 15. Qxf3 Rg8
{ All of Black's pieces are aimed at White's king, which barely has any defenders. }
16. axb5 Qh4
{ The queen comes flying into the attack with the huge threat of ...Bh3. I can't imagine anyone wanting to be in White's shoes.   The immediate threat is  17.--  Bh3  18.Bxd5  Rxg2  19.Kh1  Nxf2  20.Rxf2  when  Rxf2  is decisive. }
