1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. c3
{ The text used to be White's main move but is now second to  9.Nbd2  popularity-wise. It should be noted that there are plenty of possible transpositions between the two.  White establishes a stronghold over the d4 square and creates a square for the light-squared bishop on c2, which effectively takes the sting out of ...Nc5. }
9... Bc5
{ is the most popular and ambitious continuation. The bishop is most active on c5 from where it controls key central squares and stares down f2.  The more solid   9...Be7  is analyzed in the next chapter. }
10. Nbd2 O-O 11. Bc2 Nxf2
{ Boom goes the dynamite or better put the Dilworth attack! This enterprising move is named after Vernon Dilworth, who was the first to play it consistently in the 1940s. In exchange for two minor pieces, Black gets a rook, typically 1-2 pawns and most importantly a dangerous initiative. We're in for some very exciting, attacking chess! }
12. Rxf2 f6
{ is a key follow-up. There is no need to take on f2 right away given the rook isn't going anywhere. Instead, Black adds gasoline to the fire by blasting open the f-file! }
13. Nb3 { Moving pieces away from the kingside is inadvisable. } 13... Bxf2+
{ lands White in hot water. } 14. Kxf2 fxe5
{ With ...e4 and ... Bg4 on the way, White is in big trouble.   For example  15.Kg1  Bg4  16.h3  Bxf3  17.gxf3  e4∓  White's pieces are all on the queenside while his king is completely bare on g1. Black's attack will be practically decisive. }
