1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. c3
{ The text used to be White's main move but is now second to  9.Nbd2  popularity-wise. It should be noted that there are plenty of possible transpositions between the two.  White establishes a stronghold over the d4 square and creates a square for the light-squared bishop on c2, which effectively takes the sting out of ...Nc5. }
9... Bc5
{ is the most popular and ambitious continuation. The bishop is most active on c5 from where it controls key central squares and stares down f2.  The more solid   9...Be7  is analyzed in the next chapter. }
10. Nbd2 O-O 11. Bc2 Nxf2
{ Boom goes the dynamite or better put the Dilworth attack! This enterprising move is named after Vernon Dilworth, who was the first to play it consistently in the 1940s. In exchange for two minor pieces, Black gets a rook, typically 1-2 pawns and most importantly a dangerous initiative. We're in for some very exciting, attacking chess! }
12. Rxf2 f6
{ is a key follow-up. There is no need to take on f2 right away given the rook isn't going anywhere. Instead, Black adds gasoline to the fire by blasting open the f-file! }
13. Nf1
{ is rarely played as it gives up another pawn and allows Black to build up a strong center. The point behind's White move is to quickly develop the queenside in an attempt to limit Black's initiative. }
13... Bxf2+
{ 13...fxe5?  allows  14.Be3  when Black only has two pawns for the piece. }
14. Kxf2 fxe5 { ...e4 is coming so White's king must step back. } 15. Kg1 Qd6
16. Be3 { A logical continuation, aiming to redeploy the bishop to g3. } 16...
h6 { Black takes control over the g5 square, ruling out both Ng5 or Bg5. } 17.
Bf2
{ The bishop is well placed on f2 from where it can pop out to g3. White also stepped out of the ...d4 break with tempo. }
17... Rad8 18. Qe2
{ A clever move, which makes  18...Bg4  pointless on account of  19.Ne3  given that the f3 knight is defended by White's queen.   Conversely  18.Qe1  is well met by  18...Bg4  hitting the f3 knight and thus ruling out Ne3. }
18... d4
{ Gaining space with tempo. Black is threatening to win material with ...d3. }
19. Qe1
{ GM Nils Grandelius stopped here in the Chessable course The Grand Ruy Lopez, ending with I like the calm 19.Qe1, just stepping out of the fork, and then play N1d2-e4, with a very nice blockade. It will still not be easy to make progress as Black has everything protected, but with the pawns blocked we are running no risk and can increase pressure with moves like Bb3, Rd1 and Bg3.  We're not going to allow White to achieve any of this. }
19... Bf5 20. Bb3+ Kh8 21. N1d2
{ Following Grandelius' plan of blockading the e4 square. } 21... dxc3 22. bxc3
Bh7
{ A very strong retreating move, vacating the g6 square for ...Qg6 in order to fight for the e4 square. }
23. Ne4 Qg6 24. Nfd2 Ne7
{ heading to ...d5. White's knight on e4 looks good but maintaining it has condemned the d2 knight to passivity. Black has zero problems with all of his pieces well placed. }
