1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. c3
{ The text used to be White's main move but is now second to  9.Nbd2  popularity-wise. It should be noted that there are plenty of possible transpositions between the two.  White establishes a stronghold over the d4 square and creates a square for the light-squared bishop on c2, which effectively takes the sting out of ...Nc5. }
9... Bc5
{ is the most popular and ambitious continuation. The bishop is most active on c5 from where it controls key central squares and stares down f2.  The more solid   9...Be7  is analyzed in the next chapter. }
10. Nbd2 O-O 11. Bc2 Nxf2
{ Boom goes the dynamite or better put the Dilworth attack! This enterprising move is named after Vernon Dilworth, who was the first to play it consistently in the 1940s. In exchange for two minor pieces, Black gets a rook, typically 1-2 pawns and most importantly a dangerous initiative. We're in for some very exciting, attacking chess! }
12. Rxf2 f6
{ is a key follow-up. There is no need to take on f2 right away given the rook isn't going anywhere. Instead, Black adds gasoline to the fire by blasting open the f-file! }
13. exf6
{ is White's main approach. The first player refrains from giving up the e5 pawn, which comes at the cost of opening up the f-file and allowing us to rapidly develop the queen to f6. }
13... Bxf2+
{ Time to flush out White's king into the open!   13...Qxf6?  is too clever for Black's own good as it allows  14.Qf1±  when White can take on f2 with the queen, ensuring the king safely stays on g1. Smyslov convincingly took down Botvinnik in a top-level encounter in Moscow, 1943. }
14. Kxf2 Qxf6 15. Nf1
{ Instead of retreating the king to g1, White clears the way for Be3-c5/d4 to speed up queenside development.   15.Qf1  Ne5  16.Kg1  Bg4  is excellent for Black. }
15... Ne5 16. Be3 Rae8 17. Bc5
{ is by far White's most popular move, seeking to disrupt our coordination. }
17... Nxf3 18. gxf3 Rf7
{ Black has a dangerous attack and has had great results in a sample size of 100s of games. I see little point in taxing our memory with a ton of variations from hereon given how natural Black's play is. Instead, I've chosen to provide a few sample variations below:   a  19.Kg1  Bf5  20.Bxf5  Qxf5  21.Ng3  Qxf3  22.Qxf3  Rxf3  23.a4  h5  24.Nxh5  Re2  Black is in great shape in this endgame. The b2 pawn is hanging and . ..Rh3 is also in the air.   b  19.Ng3  Bg4  20.Kg1  Qxf3  21.Qxf3  Rxf3  is a a typical endgame in this line where Black is doing well. It's not at all one-sided! For example, White quickly got a worse position in the game ½-½ 51 Leko,P 2555-Jussupow,A 2655 Horgen 1994, which continued  22.Kg2  h5  23.Bg6?!  Re6  24.Bxh5  Rxg3+  25.Kxg3  Bxh5⩱  Leko managed to hold with White, but only Black can win this.   c  19.Kg2  Qg5+  20.Ng3   20.Kh1  runs into  20...d4!  clearing the way for ...Bd5 with a very dangerous attack.  20...d4!  Clearing the way for ...Bd5  21.Bxd4   21.cxd4??  Bd5-+  is already winning.  21...c5  22.Bf2  Rxf3!  is incredibly dangerous. White needs to defend like an engine to hold this. }
