1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Nc5
{ is the modern mainline. Black removes the knight from e4 to enable the ... d4 push. }
10. c3 Be7
{ 10...d4  is an enterprising alternative, which is covered in thenext chapter. }
11. Bc2 d4
{ The inclusion of ...Be7 and Bc2 make ...d4 arguably even more attractive than on the previous turn. We're intending to push ahead with ...d3 to limit White's light-squared bishop. }
12. Ne4
{ is rarely seen and for good reason. It essentially forces a drawish endgame. }
12... d3
{ White's bishop and knight are now hanging, leading to the following forced sequence of moves: }
13. Nxc5 dxc2 14. Qxd8+ Rxd8 15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. Be3 Rd5
{ We're not concerned about the c2 pawn dropping since e5 is just as weak. Many games were quickly drawn in this line, a few examples being:   17.Rfc1  Nxe5  18.Nxe5  Rxe5  19.Rxc2  Kf7  20.Kf1  Rd8  21.a4  Bg5  22.Bd4  Red5  23.axb5  axb5  24.Ra7  R8d7=  1/2-1/2 48 Warmerdam, M 2433-Stevic,H 2587 Skopje 2018     21.Rd2  Red5  22.Ke2  a5  23.g3  a4  24.Rad1  1/2-1/2 24 Istratescu,A 2553 -Milliet,S 2407 Chalons en Champagne 2021     20.c4  Rc8  21.Rd1  Rd8  22.Rxd8  Bxd8  23.Kf1  b4  1/2-1/2 24 Bok, B 2497 -Ernst, S 2596 Maastricht 2011 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9.Nbd2 Nc5 10.c3 Be7 | Repertoire 1"]
[Black "12.Nb3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Nc5
{ is the modern mainline. Black removes the knight from e4 to enable the ... d4 push. }
10. c3 Be7
{ 10...d4  is an enterprising alternative, which is covered in thenext chapter. }
11. Bc2 d4
{ The inclusion of ...Be7 and Bc2 make ...d4 arguably even more attractive than on the previous turn. We're intending to push ahead with ...d3 to limit White's light-squared bishop. }
12. Nb3 d3 13. Bb1
{ The bishop drops back but keeps tabs on the d3 pawn. White is now threatening to win it with Nxc5 followed by takes on d3. }
13... Nxb3 { is required to hold onto the d3 pawn. } 14. axb3 Bf5
{ The battle lines are drawn and revolve around the d3 pawn. White will attempt to prove it's essentially a weakness and dedicate efforts to capturing it. In the meantime, Black will make use of the extra space to organize counterplay. }
15. b4
{ is a logical move. White creates a window for the light-squared bishop on a2 and tries to fix Black's backward pawn on a6.   15.Bf4  O-O  16.h3  Qd7  17.b4  is covered via the 15.b4 move order. }
15... O-O
{ However, the b4 pawn is a perfect hook for ...a5, which White cannot stop. Black naturally secures the king before initiating active operations on the queenside. }
16. Re1 a5
{ Black comfortably equalized in 1/2-1/2 60 Lomasov,S 2525-Raja,R 2408 Arandjelovac 2021. }
*

