{ The battle lines are drawn and revolve around the d3 pawn. White will attempt to prove it's essentially a weakness and dedicate efforts to capturing it. In the meantime, Black will make use of the extra space to organize counterplay. }
15. Be3 O-O 16. Re1 { 16.Bd4  Qd5  17.Re1  Rfd8  transposes to the text. }
16... Qd5
{ is a good, active square for the queen. It eyes the b3 and e5 pawns while vacating the d8 square for the f8 rook. }
17. Bd4 Rfd8 18. h4 { is strongly met by the tactical shot } 18... d2
{ which solves all of Black's problems. The idea is to distract White's queen from the defense of the b3 pawn while exchanging a pair of minor pieces.   18...Nxd4!?  also equalizes. }
19. Re2
{ White keeps the b3 pawn protected and intends to pick up the d2 pawn with the rook. The first player cannot, however, hold on to all the pawns. The one on h4 drops after the following forced sequence:   19.Bxf5  dxe1=Q+  20.Qxe1  Qxb3=  is also fully equal. }
19... Bxb1 20. Rxb1 Nxd4 21. Nxd4 Bxh4
{ with a comfortable game. White's knight on d4 is not stable and the e5 pawn is potentially a target.     Black is threatening to hold onto the d2 pawn with ...Bg5 so White should play  22.Nf3  Be7  23.Rxd2  Qe6  intending a future ...c5. For example  24.b4  h6  25.Ra1  Rxd2  26.Qxd2  c5=  is excellent. }
