1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Nc5
{ is the modern mainline. Black removes the knight from e4 to enable the ... d4 push. }
10. c3 d4 { The immediate pawn break is Black's most ambitious continuation. }
11. Ng5
{ This unexpected move was first played by Karpov vs Kortschnoj in the epic 1978 World Championship in Baguio. The credit goes to Zaitsev, who was Karpov's second. }
11... Qxg5
{ Black should bite the bullet and grab the knight, not fearing 12. Qf3.   11...dxc3  is inferior for various reasons:  12.Nxe6  fxe6  13.bxc3  Qd3  14.Nf3  Qxd1  15.Bxd1  Be7  16.Be3⩲  gave White the upper hand in 1/2-1/2 44 Karpov,A 2725-Kortschnoj,V 2665 Baguio City 1978.     14.Bc2  is even more problematic as discussed in thepositional and tactical themes chapter. }
12. Qf3
{ hitting both the c6 knight and the f7 pawn is the point behind 11. Ng5.   The materialistic  12...Bd7  is ill-advised on account of  13.Bxf7+  Ke7  14.Bd5  Nxe5  15.Qe2→  Black's king is in a world of trouble.   Finally  12...Kd7?  fails to  13.Bd5  Nxe5  14.Bxe6+  Nxe6  15.Qxa8+-  . }
12... O-O-O
{ White can now take on c6 right away or throw in Bxe6+ first. We'll analyze both options in detail in the next set of trainable lines. }
