Be6 9. Nbd2 Nc5
{ is the modern mainline. Black removes the knight from e4 to enable the ... d4 push. }
10. c3 d4 { The immediate pawn break is Black's most ambitious continuation. }
11. Ng5
{ This unexpected move was first played by Karpov vs Kortschnoj in the epic 1978 World Championship in Baguio. The credit goes to Zaitsev, who was Karpov's second. }
11... Qxg5
{ Black should bite the bullet and grab the knight, not fearing 12. Qf3. } 12.
Qf3 { hitting both the c6 knight and the f7 pawn is the point behind 11. Ng5. }
12... O-O-O { White can now take on c6 right away or throw in Bxe6+ first. }
13. Bxe6+ { is the only way to test Black. } 13... fxe6 14. Qxc6 Qxe5 15. b4
{ is White's best try. } 15... Qd5
{ Black does best in getting the queens off the board. We'll end up down a piece in the ensuing endgame but have two strong passed pawns in return.   15...dxc3?!  is not a good idea on account of  16.bxc5  when  16...cxd2  17.Qxa6+  Kd7  18.Bxd2±  is clearly better for White. Our king on d7 is in no man's land. }
16. Qxd5 exd5 17. bxc5 dxc3 18. Nb3 d4
{ The c and d-pawns are a force to be reckoned with. White needs to tread carefully to maintain the balance. }
19. Ba3 c2
{ Push em baby as Yasser would say!   19...g6  is Black's most popular move, which has been worked out to a forced draw. The text is far less popular, meaning it could surprise your opponents, and gives White more chances to go wrong. }
20. Bb4 Rd5
{ This novel move is the machine's top choice. The idea is to play ...a5 and then grab the c5 pawn combined with pushing the central pawns.   It's too late for  20...g6  on account of  21.a4+-  . }
21. Rac1 { is a blunder. } 21... d3 { Black's pawns are far too powerful. } *

