Be6 9. Nbd2 Nc5 10. c3 d4
{ The immediate pawn break is Black's most ambitious continuation. } 11. Bxe6
{ is by far White's main move, currently more than three times as popular as the alternatives. }
11... Nxe6 12. cxd4 Ncxd4 13. a4
{ Undermining the queenside is White's most common option. } 13... Bb4 14. axb5
Nxb5 { is the only viable recapture. } 15. Qb3
{ White brings out the queen with a tempo on our bishop. What could be more natural? }
15... Bxd2 16. Rxa6
{ can catch one by surprise but is not a move to lose any sleep over. } 16...
Rb8
{ 16...Rxa6  runs into  17.Qxb5+  Qd7  18.Qxa6  Bxc1  19.Rxc1  O-O  Black is still objectively fine but there's no need to go for this pawn down position. }
17. Rxe6+ { is White's point. Nothing to fear though! } 17... fxe6 18. Qxe6+
Qe7 19. Qc6+ Qd7 20. Qxd7+ Kxd7 21. Bxd2 c5
{ White has two pawns for the exchange but no advantage whatsoever. We will post up our king on e6, which will firmly control the e-pawn, and bring the h8 rook to d8 or c8.   A sample continuation is  21...c5  22.Be3  Rhc8  23.g3  Ke6  24.Rc1  Nd4  25.Nxd4+  cxd4  26.Rxc8  Rxc8  27.Bxd4  g5=  should be quickly drawn.   21...Ra8!?  also holds but requires Black to be far more precise. }
