{ Black should be careful here. In many ways, the most logical move is  11...f5  , but after  12.exf6  , he lacks the recapture with the Knight due to the loose Bishop on  e6  . The text therefore develops the Queen, clears the back rank and covers the Bishop on  e6  . }
12. Bxe4
{ This is not a very good pawn grab, but whenever a pawn sacrifice is offered at all, I'd like the author of the course to tell me something about what happens if they take it. }
12... dxe4 13. Qxe4 Bf5 14. Qe3 { 14.Qe2?!  Bd3  is even worse for White. }
14... f6
{ Black has a big lead and development and extremely active play. Ideas like ...Rad8/...Rae8, ...Bd3, ...Qd5, ...Ne5 and so on all come into play and Black has fantastic compensation. }
