[White "9.c3 Be7 | Repertoire 2"]
[Black "9.c3 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. c3 Be7 10. Re1 O-O 11. Nd4
{ This is the critical move, but it is probably not very good. Black does have to be willing to enter some sharp variations and even sacrifice a piece, but it all works out very well for him theoretically. }
11... Nxe5
{ This pawn grab is not normally possible, but tactically, it works out here.   The problem with  11...Nxd4?!  12.cxd4  is that White has yet to commit his Knight to  d2  , meaning f2-f3 will chase the e4-Knight back to an awkward square, as there is no option to exchange it. }
12. f3
{ This move, skewering the Knights along the e-file, is generally the tactical refutation of ...Nxe5 in these positions. Otherwise, White just remains a pawn down. }
12... Bh4 13. fxe4
{ While it may seem that White is getting two pieces for a Rook, Black has a massive initiative, thanks in part to the first player's complete lack of queenside development. }
13... Bg4
{ This attacks the Queen, forcing it to an awkward square. Black is going to continue to make threats until he's extracted enough concessions to be happy taking on e1. }
14. Qd2 { Moving the Queen anywhere else would lose material. } 14... c5
{ Black makes another threat, and this one is particularly difficult to deal with. White's position is tactically hanging by a thread. I won't make you memorize sequences against all of White's legal moves here, but I will give some examples of possible tactics in the notes. }
15. Bxd5
{ This counterattacking move is the computer's first choice.   Instead,  15.Nc2  c4  traps the Bishop;  15.Ne2  loses to  15...Bxe1  16.Qxe1  Nd3  17.Qd2  Bxe2  18.Qxe2  Nxc1  and  15.Nf5  Bxf5  16.exf5  Bxe1  17.Qxe1  Nd3  18.Qd2  c4  19.Bc2  Re8  , with a winning attack, as White's queenside is dormant. }
15... cxd4 16. Bxa8 Nc4
{ 16...Qxa8  is also good, but the text is the most accurate. The Queen is forced away from the defense of the Rook. }
17. Qd3 Bxe1 { Black has equalized the material and his initiative continues. }
