[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9.c3 Be7 | Repertoire 2"]
[Black "9.c3 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. c3 Be7 10. Re1 O-O 11. Nd4
{ This is the critical move, but it is probably not very good. Black does have to be willing to enter some sharp variations and even sacrifice a piece, but it all works out very well for him theoretically. }
11... Nxe5
{ This pawn grab is not normally possible, but tactically, it works out here.   The problem with  11...Nxd4?!  12.cxd4  is that White has yet to commit his Knight to  d2  , meaning f2-f3 will chase the e4-Knight back to an awkward square, as there is no option to exchange it. }
12. f3
{ This move, skewering the Knights along the e-file, is generally the tactical refutation of ...Nxe5 in these positions. Otherwise, White just remains a pawn down. }
12... Bh4 13. Re2
{ White moves his Rook. The skewer along the e-file is still in place, but we have another tactical shot planned. }
13... Nf2
{ This time we're making a genuine offer of two pieces for a Rook, but not only have we picked up a pawn, we have great play in spite of the material balance. }
14. Rxf2 Bxf2+ 15. Kxf2 Re8
{ Material is even according to conventional wisdom, but generally you'd take the side with the Bishop pair, i.e. White here. That being said, the first player's queenside pieces are not in motion and he will likely also have to spend a tempo on Kg1 at some point. Meanwhile, Black's pieces will activate very smoothly, and he also has ...c5 to throw into the mix. }
16. Bf4 { White develops with tempo. } 16... Qf6
{ Black brings his Queen into the action, also with tempo. Naturally, White would not be so excited to take on e5 and surrender his Bishop pair. }
17. Qd2
{ White covers his Bishop, but this also restricts the movement of the Knight on b1. }
17... c5
{ Black expands with tempo. With moves like ...Rad8, ...Bf5 intending ...Nd3+, ...c4 and ...d4 in the picture, Black has tremendous compensation for a very slight material deficit  (a Rook and pawn tend to balance out two minor pieces on the whole, but White's Bishop pair gives him a half-pawn edge, according to modern wisdom)  . }
*

