1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. c3 Be7 10. Re1 O-O 11. Nd4 Nxe5 12. f3 Bh4 13. g3 c5 14. gxh4 Qxh4
{ Black ignores the Knight on d4 and goes for a direct attack. He can still take the Knight later, of course. }
15. fxe4 { 15.Rf1  cxd4  16.fxe4  Bh3  transposes. } 15... cxd4
{ Black is only a piece for two pawns down at the moment, ...Bg4 followed by ...Nf3+ is an extremely strong threat. }
16. Rf1 { Covering the f3 square and thus dissuading ...Bg4. } 16... Bh3
{ We are not only threatening to take on f1 and win the material back while the attack continues, but ...Rad8-d6-g6+ is also a totally plausible idea. Black is winning. }
