[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9.c3 Be7 | Repertoire 2"]
[Black "9.c3 #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. c3 Be7 10. Re1 O-O 11. Nd4 Nxe5 12. f3 Bh4 13. g3 c5 14. Nxe6 fxe6 15.
fxe4
{ This is the less risky of the two pieces to take, as it doesn't directly open White's King. However, Black has enormous compensation for the piece regardless. }
15... Bg5
{ Black simply moves his Bishop out of threat. There is quite an ominous check on f3 on the horizon, and ...Bxc1, Qxc1, ...c4, Bc2, ...d4 is also a very strong idea. }
16. Re2
{ White moves his Rook out of the range of our Knight, and the check on f3 would now fire a blank. However, we can now execute the other idea that I mentioned in the previous note. }
16... Bxc1 17. Qxc1
{ This exchange has deflected the Queen from controlling the d4 square. } 17...
c4 18. Bc2 d4
{ The propsect of ...d4-d3 pretty much forces White to capture on d4, allowing Black's Queen into the attack. }
19. cxd4 Qxd4+ 20. Kg2 Nd3
{ Black remains a piece down, but he has a tremendous attack, with ...Rf2+ being a strong threat, and taking on d3 is not a total solution to White's problems, as then a very strong passed pawn on d3 would be created. Note as well White's lack of queenside development, weak King and the fact that his Queen is tied down to the b2-pawn. In addition, the move ...b5-b4 might be useful under the right circumstances, to prevent White from developing his Knight to c3. }
