1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. c3 Be7 10. Re1 O-O 11. Nd4 Nxe5 12. f3 Bh4 13. g3 c5 14. Nxe6 fxe6 15.
fxe4 Bg5 16. Bxg5 Qxg5
{ Black has more than enough play for his sacrifice piece. Firstly, there's the issue of the looming check on f3, but White's problems are not limited to that. Moving the King to g2 to get out of the range of the Knight can be met with ...Ng4, introducing both ...Rf2+ and ...Ne3+ as possibilities. Note also that completing queenside development remains difficult for the first player, as Nd2 can be met with ...Qxd2, with a fork on f3 coming up after the Queen is captured. }
