1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2
{ This is White's main move. He challenges the central Knight on e4 while developing a piece. }
9... Be7
{ The modern main line is  9...Nc5  10.c3  Be7  11.Bc2  d4  , which can lead to sharp positions revolving around Black's advanced d-pawn or one of a few endgames. The text leaves the Knight on  e4  for the time being, with one idea being to support it with  ...f7-f5  . }
10. Nxe4
{ 10.c3  is the main move by far. The text invites an endgame which is more than fine for Black. }
10... dxe4 11. Bxe6 fxe6 12. Ng5
{ Making use of the trick  12...Bxg5  13.Qh5+  , winning the piece back.   Instead, there's no reason to play  12.Qxd8+?  , as this reaches a similar endgame, but Black is able to activate his Rook after  12...Rxd8  , when  13.Ng5  Nd4  is better for him. }
12... Qxd1 13. Rxd1 Bxg5 14. Bxg5 O-O 15. Re1
{ A logical move - White goes after the weak e4-pawn.   15.Rd7  can be met in a variety of ways, including  15...Rac8  and  15...Rf7  . This occupation of the 7th rank is easily neutralized. }
15... h6
{ 15...Rf5  16.Bh4  Rxe5  is what is normally played here, but this is somewhat awkward. The Rook can't stay on  e5  forever, so eventually the e4-pawn will be lost. That then begs the question why Black spent time on  ...Rf5xe5  if he does not concretely benefit from it.  The text is an attempt to push the Bishop away from covering the d2 square. }
16. Bh4 { 16.Be3  Rad8  is fine for Black, as the e-file is now blocked. }
16... g5 17. Bg3 Rad8
{ Black is slightly better. He threatens to invade on d2, and  17.Rad1  can be met with  17...Nb4!  , creating some awkward threats. }
*

