1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 { This is the main line, preparing Bc2. } 10... O-O
{ Black continues to leave his Knight in the centre. } 11. Nd4
{ The tactical point is that  11...Nxe5?  12.Nxe6  fxe6  13.Nxe4  dxe4  14.Bxe6+  is good for White, but strategically, this move is not challenging. }
11... Nxd4 12. cxd4 Nxd2 13. Bxd2 c5
{ If White had time to inhibit this break with a move such as Rc1, he could argue that he is better. As it stands, however, Black is perfectly fine. }
14. dxc5 Bxc5
{ Black has executed his key pawn break, and can now continue by activating his major pieces. }
