1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Re1 Nc5 12. Nd4
{ This is the more dangerous option. } 12... Nxd4 13. cxd4 Nd3
{ 13...Nxb3  is the wrong Bishop to capture, as  14.Nxb3  increases White's control over the key c5 square. }
14. Re3 Nxc1 15. Rxc1 a5
{ As Mikhalevski explains, this move gains queenside space while keeping the option of breaking with ...c5 open. }
16. Rec3 Rc8 17. Nf3 a4 18. Bc2 g6 { Blunting the c2 Bishop's diagonal. } 19.
Bd3 b4
{ It's not so easy for either side to prove anything. Black may someday be able to push through ...c5, but immediately, this is being forestalled. Meanwhile, Black's Kingside is quite solid, so a checkmating attack is still far away for White. Black may look to throw in ...b3 or ...a3 at a good moment. }
