1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Qe2 Nc5 12. Nd4
{ This is what White normally tries in this position, stopping ...d4. } 12...
Qd7
{ I wasn't too happy with  12...Nxd4  13.cxd4  Nxb3  14.Nxb3  , when the Knight is excellently placed to cover the important c5 square. The text simply covers the Knight on c6 and clears d8 for a Rook. }
13. Nxe6 { Grabbing the Bishop doesn't lead to much for White. } 13... Qxe6 14.
Re1 { White covers the e5 pawn while also defending the Queen on e2. } 14...
Rfd8
{ This supports the d4 break, which can occur either on the next move, e.g.  15.Bc2  d4  , or after Black captures on b3. }
