1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Bc2 { Now, it's time to look at the main line. }
11... f5
{ Black supports his Knight on e4. ...Nc5 is legal, but having already kept it on e4, it makes sense to continue to leave it there. }
12. Nd4 Nxd4 13. cxd4 Qd7
{ Black wants to break with ...c5. If he does it immediately;  13...c5  14.dxc5  Bxc5  15.Nb3  is somewhat annoying. Therefore, Black would like to insert  13...Nxd2  14.Bxd2  first. However, it also makes sense to make a generally useful move, waiting for provocation with f2-f3 before taking on d2. }
14. f3 Nxd2 15. Bxd2 c5
{ Black is totally fine. f3 has forced Black to clarify the situation involving his e4-Knight, but it has also created a weakness along the a7-g1 diagonal. }
*

