1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. exf6 Nxf6 13. Re1
{ This move, which I had initially dismissed as being harmless, is actually quite tricky to meet. Joshua Doknjas recommends it in Opening Repertoire: The Ruy Lopez. }
13... Bg4
{ introduces an annoying pin, which, among other things, may facilitate the freeing ...d4 break. David Anton also recommends this move for Black in his Chessable course.   I had initially given  13...Qd7  intending to meet the direct  14.Ng5  with  14...Bf5   However  13...Qd7  14.a4!  is more challenging, when the queenside comes under some pressure. }
14. h3 Bh5 15. Nf1
{ According to Doknjas, this is a 'simple and playable' move, 'but shouldn't be too challenging'. The main idea is to swing the knight around to g3, attempting to break the annoying pin. }
15... Bc5
{ Black puts pressure on the f2-pawn.   One point is that  16.Ng3  can now be met with  16...Bxf3  when White is best advised to capture with the pawn as  17.Qxf3??  Ne4-+  is winning for Black. }
16. Be3
{ This is a sensible move, quelling the threats by exchanging off the dangerous c5-bishop. However, Black should now be able to equalize without too much trouble. }
16... d4 17. cxd4 Nxd4 18. Bxd4 Bxf3 19. Qxf3 Bxd4
{ With ...c5 potentially to come, I see no reason at all to suspect that Black might be worse. }
*

