1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. exf6 Nxf6 13. Re1
{ This move, which I had initially dismissed as being harmless, is actually quite tricky to meet. Joshua Doknjas recommends it in Opening Repertoire: The Ruy Lopez. }
13... Bg4
{ introduces an annoying pin, which, among other things, may facilitate the freeing ...d4 break. David Anton also recommends this move for Black in his Chessable course.   I had initially given  13...Qd7  intending to meet the direct  14.Ng5  with  14...Bf5   However  13...Qd7  14.a4!  is more challenging, when the queenside comes under some pressure. }
14. h3 Bh5 15. a4
{ This is Doknjas' recommendation, attacking the somewhat vulnerable queenside construction. }
15... b4 16. Nf1 Bc5 17. Be3
{ 17.Ng3  is risky, as after  17...Bxf3  18.gxf3  is forced. } 17... Bxe3
{ One of the extremely deep points of White's fifteenth move is that  17...d4?!  doesn't work as well here. After  18.cxd4  Nxd4  White can play  19.g4!  In the version without a2-a4 and ... b5-b4 thrown in, this would be quite bad due to  19...Nxf3+  20.Qxf3  Nxg4??  However, here, White wins with  21.Qe4!  , when  21...Nf6  runs into  22.Qc4+!  , which wouldn't have been possible with a pawn on b5. }
18. Rxe3
{ 18.Nxe3  allows Black to generate nice play with  18...bxc3  19.bxc3  Ne5  , playing against the pinned knight on f3. }
18... d4 19. Rd3
{ In the book Opening Repertoire: The Ruy Lopez, Doknjas recommends pinning the pawn, but Black shouldn't really have any problems here. }
19... Qd6
{ Black prepares ...Rad8 and in some lines ...Qf4 is an idea.   19...Bxf3  is also okay. }
20. cxd4 Bxf3 { Black needs to throw this in to regain his pawn. } 21. Qxf3
Nxd4 22. Qd1 c5
{ We can solidly defend our knight on d4, and White isn't really in time to make anything out of the pin, as the queen can hop off the d-file at the next convenient moment. }
