Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. exf6 Nxf6 13. Nb3 Bg4
{ Black activates his Bishop, pinning the Knight on f3 and introducing ideas of ...Ne4 followed by ...Bxf3, doubling the pawns around White's King. }
14. Qd3
{ This is very logical - White steps out of the pin and sets up a battery along the b1-h7 diagonal. }
14... Ne4
{ This might be Black's best option objectively, but it does involve some forcing variations.  14...Qd7  and  14...Qd6  are alternatives, although we do run the risk of ending up ever so slightly worse. }
15. Nbd4 { This is White's main move. } 15... Nxd4 16. Nxd4 Bd6
{ This position is quite complicated. White's Kingside, particularly the h2 point, is very vulnerable. However, Black's pieces are also in very precarious spots i.e. f2-f3, the Knight being pinned to the h7 pawn, ideas of Nxb5 followed by Qxd5+, etc.. }
17. Nc6 Qh4 18. Qxd5+ Kh8 19. f4
{ Blocking the d6 Bishop's diagonal, but Black has a good reaction to this. }
19... Be2
{ Now that the e1 square is inaccesible to White's Rook, this move traps it. He gets two pieces and a pawn for his Rook, but our active pieces against the weak White King give us the better chances. }
20. Bxe4 Bxf1 21. Kxf1 Rae8
{ All of Black's pieces are extremely active; taking on f2 and h2 are both ideas, and the King on f1 is quite precarious. }
