1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. Nb3 Qd7 13. Nbd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 c5 15.
Ne2
{ This is a rare but playable option for White. Rather than exchanging on e6, White instead drops his Knight back, from where it can re-emerge on f4. }
15... Rad8
{ Black centralizes his Rook. This move is particularly productive here, as the second player intends ...d5-d4 to generate counterplay. }
16. f3
{ Kicking the Knight back. As we'll see, in this variation f2-f3 is common, and g5 tends to be the e4-Knight's only square. It's not so badly placed here, however, as it can find itself on e6, blockading the e5-pawn, or may return to e4 should White choose to advance his f-pawn a second time. }
16... Ng5 17. Be3
{ This develops a piece, but the specific point is to make it more difficult for us to achieve the ...d5-d4 push. }
17... d4
{ This is the most forcing move. It turns out that, due to a tactical nuance, Black is able to get away with this move. Something less direct such as  17...Kh8  is fine as well, however. }
18. cxd4 Bc4
{ This is the idea. Black intends to take on  e2  and win his pawn back on  d4  .  19.dxc5  can be met with  19...Qc7  , which wins at least one pawn back and creates an awkward threat against White's Queen. }
19. b3 Bxe2 20. Qxe2 cxd4 21. Rad1 Ne6
{ The d4 pawn is safe, and Black has a satisfactory position. His ideas include centralizing the Queen with ...Qd5, ...Nc5 to fight for the d3 square should White play, e. g. Bc1 at some point and consolidating moves like ...Kh8 and ...g6. }
