1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. Nb3 Qd7 13. Nbd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 c5 15.
Ne2
{ This is a rare but playable option for White. Rather than exchanging on e6, White instead drops his Knight back, from where it can re-emerge on f4. }
15... Rad8
{ Black centralizes his Rook. This move is particularly productive here, as the second player intends ...d5-d4 to generate counterplay. }
16. Nf4
{ White re-routs his Knight to a square where it annoys the e6 Bishop and pressures the d5 pawn. Once again, Black should push in the centre. }
16... d4
{ This works tactically, but there are a couple of points that should be illustrated. }
17. Nxe6 Qxe6 18. cxd4
{ Once again, the problem arises that  18...cxd4  19.Bb3  wins material for White, as does  18...Rxd4  19.Qxd4  cxd4  20.Bb3  . Fortunately, there is a good solution to this. }
18... Qc6
{ Black moves his Queen off of the a2-g8 diagonal, while maintaining the d-file pin and keeping control over the d5 square. }
19. Bb3+ { Otherwise Black can regain his pawn. } 19... c4
{ Moving the King would have of course allowed White to play d4-d5. } 20. Bc2
Nc5
{ This is one solution to the problem of winning the pawn back. The idea is to play ...Ne6 and then take back on d4. The pin is very difficult to escape, and Black can continue with ...Bc5 if needed. Also note that Be3, covering the d4 pawn, can generally be met by ... f5-f4. }
