1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. Nb3 Qd7 13. Nbd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 c5 15.
Nxe6 Qxe6 16. f3 Ng5 17. Bxg5
{ 17.a4  is the main move, but White can also head for the Bishops of Opposite Colour position immediately. }
17... Bxg5 18. f4
{ White supports his passed e-pawn with tempo. Note that exchanging on g5 first prevented Black from hopping back into the e4 square with his Knight. }
18... Be7 19. Qf3 c4
{ This is a common theme which we'll see many times in this variation. Black is intending to play ...Bc5, followed by ...d4 if allowed. }
20. Rad1 Bc5+ 21. Kh1 Rad8
{ Black is fine, with ...d4 on the horizon. This can be prepared by ...Rd7 and ...Rfd8 if needed. }
