1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. Nb3 Qd7 13. Nbd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 c5 15.
Nxe6 Qxe6 16. f3 Ng5 17. Bf4
{ A rare move recommended by both GMs Gajweski and Grandelius here on Chessable. White prevents ...f5-f4 and waits for an opportune moment to take on g5.   For example, after  17...Qc6  18.Bxg5  White has already got an improved version of the 17. Bxg5 line as Black's queen is better placed on e6 rather than c6 in this structure.  Moreover, Qd2 is now an idea to hit the knight. }
17... Rad8 18. Kh1 Qb6
{ 18...c4  is premature, allowing  19.Qd4  with control over the key a7-g1 diagonal. This is why we go ...Qb6 first. }
19. Bxg5
{ White now takes on g5 arguing that Black's queen would rather be on e6. }
19... Bxg5 20. f4 Be7 21. g4
{ Having the Black queen on b6 instead of e6 gives White this interesting possibility. Worry not, Black is fine after the following precise sequence of moves. }
21... d4
{ Black must create counterplay in the center!   21...fxg4?!  would only open up an avenue towards our king. After  22.Qxg4  White has the initiative with Rg1 on the agenda. }
22. Bxf5 { 22.gxf5  is well met by either  22...d3  or  22...dxc3  . } 22...
dxc3 23. Qb3+ Kh8 24. Qxc3 Qc6+
{ Black forces the queens off the board, going for a balanced endgame. } 25.
Qf3 Qxf3+ 26. Rxf3 g6 27. Be6 Rd4
{ The pressure on the f4 pawn and the presence of opposite colored bishops give Black full compensation for the missing pawn.   The point of Black's last move is that  28.f5  runs into  28...Re4!  29.f6  Bd8=  when the e5 pawn falls.   More testing is  28.Raf1  which Black should meet with  28...c4  29.b3  Bb4  30.bxc4  bxc4  31.h3  a5=  White still can't make headway with  32.f5  on account of  32...Re4  when the e5 pawn drops. }
