1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. Nb3 Qd7 13. Nbd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 c5 15.
Nxe6 Qxe6 16. f3 Ng5 17. a4
{ Immediately undermining Black's queenside is White's main continuation. }
17... Rad8 18. axb5 axb5
{ I've chosen to give this position its own chapter, because it's pretty much the heart of this variation with 9...Be7 and 10...O-O. It's quite a complex position, where White can choose from several viable moves, and Black has to be prepared to play somewhat accurately to ensure the game remains equal.   In general, the second player's play is based around ...c5-c4, intending ...Bc5 and ...d4 if permitted, as well as blockading the passed e5 pawn, often with a Knight. ...f5-f4 tends to be a nice move to throw in, both splitting the f3 and e5-pawns, as well as taking e3 away from White's Bishop. }
