1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. Nb3 Qd7 13. Nbd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 c5 15.
Nxe6 Qxe6 16. f3 Ng5 17. a4 Rad8 18. axb5 axb5 19. Qe2
{ White covers e5 and threatens b5. } 19... c4
{ This is a standard move for Black in this structure  (with ...Bc5+ and ...d4 being a key idea)  and it also meets White's threat to take on b5. }
20. Be3 Qc6
{ Note that  20...Qxe5  21.f4  wins a piece.  The text clears the e6 square for the Knight to use to blockade White's e-pawn. }
21. Qf2 f4
{ Black throws in this move before bringing his Knight to e6 in order to claim some kingside space and prevent f3-f4, defending the e-pawn. The immediate  21...Ne6  is also possible. }
22. Bb6 Ne6
{ There's no reason to delay this move, as the Rook on d8 is untouchable. } 23.
Ra7 { 23.Bxd8??  Bc5-+  is Black's point. } 23... Rd7
{ Black once again wasn't obligated to answer the threat of Bxd8, but neutralizing the pressure along the 7th rank is a good idea. }
24. Rxd7 Qxd7
{ Black is fine. The Knight on e6 serves as a good blockading unit, and he has counterplay with the ...b4 and ...d4 breaks. It may be a good idea to throw in ...g6 at some point to neutralize the c2-Bishop's diagonal. }
