1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. Nb3 Qd7 13. Nbd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 c5 15.
Nxe6 Qxe6 16. f3 Ng5 17. a4 Rad8 18. axb5 axb5 19. Kh1
{ White moves his King from the a7-g1 diagonal. This is useful prophylaxis against the ...c4, ...Bc5+, ...d4 plan. }
19... f4
{ This is a useful move; stopping f3-f4  (so ...Qxe5 is now on the table)  and also taking the e3 square away from the c1-Bishop. }
20. Re1 { White covers his e-pawn.   20.Qe2  c4  is similar. } 20... c4
{ Black continues thematically. The goal is, once again, to push ...d4, be it as a temporary pawn sacrifice, or with the support of ...Bc5 and/or ...Qb6. }
21. Qd4
{ White attempts to take control over the dark squares before Black occupies them. }
21... Qc6
{ Followed by ejecting the Queen with either ...Bc5 or ...Ne6. Black stands well. }
