1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. Nb3 Qd7 13. Nbd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 c5 15.
Nxe6 Qxe6 16. f3 Ng5 17. a4 Rad8 18. axb5 axb5 19. Kh1
{ White moves his King from the a7-g1 diagonal. This is useful prophylaxis against the ...c4, ...Bc5+, ...d4 plan. }
19... f4
{ This is a useful move; stopping f3-f4  (so ...Qxe5 is now on the table)  and also taking the e3 square away from the c1-Bishop. }
20. Ra7 Rf7
{ In this case, this is a better way to neutralize the seventh rank pressure than  20...Rd7  . One of the points is that after  21.Rxd7  Qxd7  , White no longer has to worry about the attack on  e5  . The Rook on  f7  defends the Bishop on  e7  , meaning taking on  e5  is once again in the picture, as the  Re1  skewer has been avoided. }
21. Qe2 Qb6
{ This is a multi-purpose move. Black kicks back the Rook, defends the b5 pawn and clears the e6 square for his Knight. }
22. Ra1 c4
{ Black is fine. He has the usual ideas of the ...b4 and ...d4 breaks, and his Knight can drop back to the e6 square. }
