1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. Nb3 Qd7 13. Nbd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 c5 15.
Nxe6 Qxe6 16. f3 Ng5 17. a4 Rad8 18. axb5 axb5 19. Kh1
{ White moves his King from the a7-g1 diagonal. This is useful prophylaxis against the ...c4, ...Bc5+, ...d4 plan. }
19... f4 20. b4
{ With this move, White sacrifices a pawn to open lines for his two Bishops. }
20... Qxe5
{ 20...c4  21.Qd4  favours White, as we lack the ability to play  ...Bc5  at some point to kick the Queen away.  20...cxb4  21.cxb4  Qxe5  is a playable alternative, but opening the long diagonal for a Bishop to eventually come to  b2  doesn't seem ideal. }
21. Re1 Qf6
{ It's possible to play  21...Qxc3  , as this comes with tempo on the Rook, but it opens the long diagonal and loses time. White has good compensation after  22.Rb1  Qf6  - defending the  e7  Bishop and retreating out of harm's way -  23.Bb2  , but the game continues on with  23...d4  . }
22. bxc5 Bxc5 23. Qd3 Qh6
{ Of the good moves available to Black, this is probably the one whose idea is most apparent. Black defends h7 and has the idea of ...Bf2-g3.   23...Kh8  is given as analternative recommendation. }
24. Qxb5
{ There is also  24.Ba3  Bxa3  25.Rxa3  Qc6  , when Black is fine. The text regains the pawn but allows Black to start a quick attack. }
24... Bf2 25. Re2
{ This is better than  25.Rf1??  , which takes away a flight square and does not provide defense along the second rank. Black mates by force after  25...Bg3  26.h3  Nxh3  . }
25... Bg3 26. h3 Nxh3 27. gxh3 Qxh3+ 28. Kg1 Rde8
{ This is the only way to continue the attack, but it is effective. We have the idea of lifting the Rook via e5, with the e2-Rook tied down to the defense of the h2 square. }
29. Qxe8
{ 29.Ba3  Re5!  30.Be4!!  - only move -  30...Rd8!  31.Bd6!!  - only move -  31...Bf2+!!  32.Kxf2  dxe4!  33.Qxe5  Qxf3+  34.Ke1  Qh1+  35.Kd2  e3+  36.Kc2  Qxa1  and even here, the game remains unclear. }
29... Rxe8 30. Rxe8+ Kf7 31. Re2
{ White is material up, but Black has a drawing mechanism. } 31... Bh2+ 32.
Rxh2 Qg3+ { White cannot avoid a draw, for example: } 33. Rg2
{ 33.Kh1  Qe1+  34.Kg2  Qg3+  repeats.   33.Kf1??  Qxh2  . } 33... Qe1+ 34. Kh2
Qh4+ 35. Kg1 Qe1+ { with a perpetual. } *

