1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. Nb3 Qd7 13. Nbd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 c5 15.
Nxe6 Qxe6 16. f3 Ng5 17. a4 Rad8 18. axb5 axb5 19. Kh1
{ White moves his King from the a7-g1 diagonal. This is useful prophylaxis against the ...c4, ...Bc5+, ...d4 plan. }
19... f4 20. b4
{ With this move, White sacrifices a pawn to open lines for his two Bishops. }
20... Qxe5
{ 20...c4  21.Qd4  favours White, as we lack the ability to play  ...Bc5  at some point to kick the Queen away.  20...cxb4  21.cxb4  Qxe5  is a playable alternative, but opening the long diagonal for a Bishop to eventually come to  b2  doesn't seem ideal. }
21. Re1 Qf6
{ It's possible to play  21...Qxc3  , as this comes with tempo on the Rook, but it opens the long diagonal and loses time. White has good compensation after  22.Rb1  Qf6  - defending the  e7  Bishop and retreating out of harm's way -  23.Bb2  , but the game continues on with  23...d4  . }
22. bxc5 Bxc5 23. Qd3 Kh8
{ This subtle move in fact leads to massive complications. The King is stepping out of any Bb3 ideas or future Qxd5 captures with check. }
24. Rb1
{ 24.Bd2  can be met either by  24...d4  or in a similar manner to the text, with  24...Bf2  . }
24... Bf2
{ Unfortunately, this is where play becomes highly specific. Black is about to whip up a quick attack against the opposing King with ...Bg3. This leads, as things so often do, to a forced draw. However, there are some details along the way that you would need to get right if you happened to reach this position with Black. }
25. Re2
{ This is more challenging than  25.Rf1  , which takes away a flight square from the King. The Rook from  e2  can also act as a defender along the second rank. After  25.Rf1  Bg3  , the threat of  ...Qh6  forces  26.hxg3  Qh6+  27.Kg1  fxg3  and now  28.Qxh7+!  Nxh7  29.Bxh6  gxh6  , and Black is fine. }
25... Bg3 26. Ba3 Qh6 27. h3 Nxh3 28. gxh3 Qxh3+ 29. Kg1 b4
{ This is absolutely necessary, and actually quite brilliant. The point is that Black would like to play  29...Rf6  , but  30.Qxb5  not only threatens a check on  e8  , but after  30...Qh5  , there is  31.Qb8  . }
30. Bxb4
{ 30.cxb4  Rf6  is similar. Instead,  30.Rxb4  keeps the b-file options open, but leaves the back rank weak, and therefore  30...Rfe8  is strong. }
30... Rf6 31. Qxd5
{ Exploiting the weak back rank. Black only has one way to avoid losing here. }
31... Bf2+ 32. Kxf2 { 32.Rxf2??  Rxd5  and there's no longer a mate on  e8  . }
32... Qh2+ 33. Kf1 { 33.Ke1??  Qg1+  34.Kd2  Rxd5+ } 33... Qh1+
{ Now two pieces down, Black makes a draw. } *

