Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. Nb3 Qd7 13. Nfd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 c5 15.
Nxe6 Qxe6 16. f3 Ng5 17. a4 Rad8 18. axb5 axb5 19. Ra7
{ This is White's main move here. } 19... Rd7
{ Neutralizing the seventh rank pressure is by far the main line for Black here, but the rare  19...c4!?  is also interesting. }
20. Rxd7 Qxd7 21. h4
{ This is an attempt to kick the kick and expand on the Kingside. } 21... Ne6
22. g4
{ Black has a few ways to meet this. He probably shouldn't take on g4 and open the position further, but both defending the pawn and advancing it seem like good options. }
22... f4 23. h5 c4 24. Kg2 Bc5
{ White has opened the b1-h7 diagonal, but otherwise has not yet succeeded at generating an attack. Once again, ...d5-d4 is an idea for Black, and his Knight can go to g5 if need be, e.g. if White makes a threat to h7. }
