{ This is White's main move here. } 19... Rd7
{ Neutralizing the seventh rank pressure is by far the main line for Black here, but the rare  19...c4!?  is also interesting. }
20. Rxd7 Qxd7 21. Bxg5
{ Heading for the Bishops of Opposite Colour position, in order to play f2-f4 and support the e5 pawn without allowing the Knight to jump back to e4. This also prevents Black from setting up a blockade with his Knight on e6. }
21... Bxg5 22. f4 Be7 23. Qf3 Rd8 24. Rd1 g6
{ A computer will show a tiny advantage for White at first, but this tends to fizzle out if you continue down the line. This is a typical position for this variation; Black may continue with ...c4 and ...Bc5  (+)  . }
