Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. Nb3 Qd7 13. Nfd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 c5 15.
Nxe6 Qxe6 16. f3 Ng5 17. a4 Rad8 18. axb5 axb5 19. Ra7
{ This is White's main move here. } 19... Rd7
{ Neutralizing the seventh rank pressure is by far the main line for Black here, but the rare 19...c4!? is also interesting. }
20. Rxd7 Qxd7 21. f4
{ This is arguably the critical attempt. The g5-Knight is allowed to return to the centre, but the first player has some attacking possibilities. }
21... Ne4
{ 21...Ne6?  is insufficiently active in this case. White can achieve a big edge with  22.g4!  g6  23.gxf5  gxf5  24.Qh5!  Ng7  25.Qf3  . }
22. g4
{ This is a very aggressive attempt to undermine Black's strong central construction. }
22... Kh8
{ Moving the King to safety makes sense.   Note that  22...fxg4??  23.Bxe4  wins a piece for White. }
23. gxf5 Qxf5 24. Qe2 g5
{ This isn't the only playable move, but it's the strongest. Black puts the principle of attacking the base of the pawn chain into practice. }
25. fxg5 Qxe5 26. Rxf8+ Bxf8 27. Qg4 Bd6
{ White can't achieve anything with Queen checks, and the threat to h2 ensures that the first player can't get too ambitious. }
