Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. Nb3 Qd7 13. Nfd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 c5 15.
Nxe6 Qxe6 16. f3 Ng5 17. a4 Rad8 18. axb5 axb5 19. Ra7
{ This is White's main move here. } 19... Rd7
{ Neutralizing the seventh rank pressure is by far the main line for Black here, but the rare  19...c4!?  is also interesting. }
20. Rxd7 Qxd7 21. f4
{ This is arguably the critical attempt. The g5-Knight is allowed to return to the centre, but the first player has some attacking possibilities. }
21... Ne4
{ 21...Ne6?  is insufficiently active in this case. White can achieve a big edge with  22.g4!  g6  23.gxf5  gxf5  24.Qh5!  Ng7  25.Qf3  . }
22. Bxe4
{ This is the main try. Black can only capture back one way, and then White will run his f-pawn forward. }
22... fxe4 23. f5 d4
{ Black must seek active counterplay, and so he puts his own pawn majority to use. }
24. f6 Bd8
{ 24...gxf6?  25.Bh6  is good for White, who has the plan of Qe1-g3+. } 25. Be3
{ White uses the pin to win the d4 pawn. } 25... gxf6
{ This pawn is safe to capture now. Were White to play  26.Bh6  here, Black's extra tempo of  ...Bd8  would help him significantly, as the Queen now defends the seventh rank.  This move was not covered in the book Kaufman's New Repertoire for Black and White by GM Larry Kaufman. }
26. cxd4 cxd4 27. Bxd4 Qe6 28. Qe2 Bb6
{ A good move, simplifying into a Queen and Rook pseudo-endgame, which is slightly safer than the middlegame. }
29. Bxb6 Qxb6+ 30. Kh1 f5
{ Our King is slightly airy, but shouldn't cause us too many problems if we're careful. The e5-pawn is somewhat weak, and can be a potential target after ...Qc5/...Qd4/...Qe6. }
