[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Spanish Sidelines: 5.d4 and Rare Lines"]
[Black "5.Bxc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. Bxc6
{ This is probably the least challenging of White's three versions of the Exchange Variation. The most common would be to take on c6 on move 4. The second most common is to wait for 5.O-O Be7 - we would of course play 5...Nxe4 - and then play 6.Bxc6. Here, with the Bishop still on f8, he does not need to lose a tempo with ...Be7 and then a later ...Bc5 or ...Bd6. }
5... dxc6 6. d3 Bd6
{ Black can develop his Bishop to this square immediately, from where it solidifies the e5 point. }
7. Nbd2 Be6
{ We could continue, but as this is quite a rare line and a non-critical one, I'm happy to stop here. The general plan is ...Nd7, ...f6, ...Qe7, followed by castling on either side.   8.Ng5  can be met by  8...Bg4  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Spanish Sidelines: 5.d4 and Rare Lines"]
[Black "5.Nc3 #1 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. Nc3
{ Traditionally, Nc3 isn't supposed to be a challenging more for White in the Spanish, since it inhibits the d2-d4 push. However, this is a bit of a generality; sometimes it's indeed a good move. Here, it's not exactly critical, but it's playable. The main idea tends to be to play a disruptive Nd5 at some point. }
5... Be7
{ Approaches with ...Bc5 are also quite adequate. Note that Black should play ...Be7 before ...b5.   5...b5  6.Bb3  Be7  gives White the extra option of  7.a4  . }
6. O-O b5 7. Bb3 d6
{ We have a standard Spanish type of position, but with Nc3 played instead of Re1. This prevents White from playing c2-c3 right away, but he has other ideas. }
8. a4 b4
{ When meeting a4 with ...b4 gains a tempo on a Knight on c3, it's almost always a good idea. }
9. Nd5 Na5
{ Black should not be worried about letting White take on e7, as he can eliminate the Bishop pair by taking on b3 at a moment of his choosing. }
10. Ba2 { White preserves his Bishop. } 10... Nxd5 11. Bxd5 c6 12. Ba2 c5
{ Stopping d2-d4 and gaining queenside space. We do give the d5 square to White, but the intention is to neutralize this with ...Be6. }
13. Bd5 Rb8 14. d3 O-O 15. Be3 Be6
{ The game is equal, as White has no further pieces with which to fiight for the d5 square. }
*

