1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. Nc3
{ Traditionally, Nc3 isn't supposed to be a challenging more for White in the Spanish, since it inhibits the d2-d4 push. However, this is a bit of a generality; sometimes it's indeed a good move. Here, it's not exactly critical, but it's playable. The main idea tends to be to play a disruptive Nd5 at some point. }
5... Be7
{ Approaches with ...Bc5 are also quite adequate. Note that Black should play ...Be7 before ...b5.   5...b5  6.Bb3  Be7  gives White the extra option of  7.a4  . }
6. O-O b5 7. Bb3 d6
{ We have a standard Spanish type of position, but with Nc3 played instead of Re1. This prevents White from playing c2-c3 right away, but he has other ideas. }
8. a3
{ This is an attempt to transpose into a trendy line of the d3 variation. 8...O-O 9.d3 would get us there. That's not the end of the world, but we can avoid it. }
8... Bg4
{ This threatens to exploit the pin with ...Nd4. Black doesn't often play ... Bg4 in the Spanish, but in this case, he has no intention of letting it end up on the passive g6 square. }
9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Nd4 11. Qd1 O-O
{ Taking on b3 is also possible, but the computer prefers avoiding it for the time being.   After  11...Nxb3  12.cxb3  , White is set to break with either d4 or f4. Black is fine, but maybe White can provide some small annoyance to his opponent. }
12. Ba2 c6 { Black has a plan in mind. } 13. d3 Ne6
{ This Knight re-reouting places it on a nice central square, from where it dissuades f2-f4. }
14. Re1 Qc7
{ The plan is ...Rad8 and ...d5. Black is fine here, in spite of White's Bishop pair. }
