{ We have a standard Spanish type of position, but with Nc3 played instead of Re1. This prevents White from playing c2-c3 right away but he has other ideas. }
8. Nd5 Na5
{ Black should not be worried about letting White take on e7, as he can eliminate the Bishop pair by taking on b3 at a moment of his choosing. }
9. Nxe7 Qxe7 10. d3 O-O
{ Black is fine here. One common plan is ...Nxb3, ...Nd7, ...Bb7 followed by ...f5, opening both the f-file for the Rook, and the long diagonal for the Bishop. Note that this comes into play because White has gone for d2-d3 rather than d2-d4, indicating that he is not immediately going to break in the centre. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Spanish Sidelines: 5.d4 and Rare Lines"]
[Black "5.Nc3 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. Nc3
{ Traditionally, Nc3 isn't supposed to be a challenging more for White in the Spanish, since it inhibits the d2-d4 push. However, this is a bit of a generality; sometimes it's indeed a good move. Here, it's not exactly critical, but it's playable. The main idea tends to be to play a disruptive Nd5 at some point. }
5... Be7
{ Approaches with ...Bc5 are also quite adequate. Note that Black should play ...Be7 before ...b5.   5...b5  6.Bb3  Be7  gives White the extra option of  7.a4  . }
6. d3
{ This is a tricky move order. Black isn't exactly in any danger, but he does risk transposing into a line he may not want to meet. }
6... d6
{ Instead,  6...b5  7.Bb3  d6  gives White the choice between  8.a4  and  8.a3  , when play can transpose into one of the main lines of the modern  5.O-O  Be7  6.d3  variation.  The approach with a quick ...Bg4 doesn't work as well here, as with d2-d3 in, White is able to play Be3 quickly; covering the d4 square. }
7. Bxc6+
{ This is the attempt to make things a bit tricky. Otherwise, Black is quite comfortable. }
7... bxc6 8. d4
{ Otherwise, Black can consider ...c5, stopping this altogether. } 8... exd4 9.
Nxd4
{ White has more space, in the style of the Steinitz Variation, but has lost a tempo with d3-d4 and has given up the Bishop pair. }
9... Bd7
{ Developing and defending the  c6  pawn.  9...c5  would be inaccurate due to  10.Nc6  . }
10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 Re8
{ There are plenty of possibilities for both sides in these types of positions. In general, Black can hold the balance with ideas like ...c5 followed by ...Bc6 or ...Be6, ...a5-a4, and ...Qb8. Oftentimes, it's a decent idea to play ...h7-h6, which prepares ...Bf8 securing this piece against Nf5 jumps by stopping the Bg5 pin. }
*

