1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d4
{ I can personally attest that this line is tricky to meet when you don't know very much about it. However, once you've learned a few key details, it becomes significantly less scary. }
5... exd4 6. e5
{ This immediate push is inaccurate. White should castle before playing this. }
6... Ne4 7. Nxd4
{ This is a bad move which gets White into all sorts of trouble. Instead,  7.O-O  could transpose into one of the main lines analyzed in this chapter after  7...Be7  , but  7...Nc5!  is even stronger, catching the Bishop. }
7... Nxf2
{ This Fried Liver-esque shot gives Black a serious advantage, even a winning one according to the computer. }
8. Kxf2 Qh4+ 9. Ke3
{ Otherwise, Black can regain his piece with great interest by taking on d4. }
9... b5 10. Bb3 Bc5
{ I won't go into any more detail, because this is a very rare line in practice and very good for Black. If you need any more convincing that Black's position is great, try taking the White side against a computer. The general plan is ...O-O, ...Bb7 and Rook to the e-file in some order, if allowed. }
