1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d4
{ I can personally attest that this line is tricky to meet when you don't know very much about it. However, once you've learned a few key details, it becomes significantly less scary. }
5... exd4 6. O-O Be7 7. e5 { This is the most direct, but play fizzles out. }
7... Ne4 8. Re1
{ This is not so good, due, once again, to the ability to gain a tempo against the Bishop on a4. }
8... Nc5 9. Bxc6 { White has to ditch his Bishop to get his pawn back. } 9...
dxc6 10. Nxd4 Ne6 11. Nf5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Bf8
{ This passive-seeming move is actually quite strong. The Bishop pair is a long-term asset. White has no way to increase the pressure, and Black will quickly emerge and take over the initiative. }
13. Nc3 h5
{ This is a nice idea. The point is to keep the King in the centre, and activate the h8 Rook by playing ...h4 and ...Rh5. If you've studied the Berlin, you may well have come across this idea. Black has a superior version of the Berlin here, as White lacks the initiative he would normally have, and Black maintains castling rights. }
14. h3 h4 15. Ne3 Rh5 { The e5 pawn is weak. } *

