1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d4
{ I can personally attest that this line is tricky to meet when you don't know very much about it. However, once you've learned a few key details, it becomes significantly less scary. }
5... exd4 6. O-O Be7 7. Re1 b5 8. e5
{ This is a tricky, but ultimately not dangerous, move. } 8... Nxe5
{ Black uses the fact that White left his Bishop hanging on a4 to eliminate a central pawn. }
9. Rxe5 d6
{ This isn't strictly necessary, but it's nice to throw in another useful move with tempo. }
10. Re1
{ 10.Rg5?  bxa4  11.Rxg7  isn't a very good pawn grab, as the Rook is stuck on  g7  .  11...Nh5  traps it, although the computer prefers a preliminary  11...c5  .   10.Rxe7+?  Qxe7  11.Bb3  c5  gives Black a Rook and two pawns for the two minor pieces, and the powerful pawn mass on the queenside gives Black an advantage. }
10... bxa4 11. Nxd4 Bd7 { Developing a piece and stopping Nc6. } 12. Qe2
{ This is a tricky try to keep our King in the centre. After a few good moves, this problem dissipates, however. }
12... c5 13. Bd2
{ White leaves his Knight hanging on d4, but is intending the tactic Ba5. }
13... O-O
{ Just castling out of any trouble. The loose Bishop on e7 is not a concern, as the Knight on d4 is also hanging. }
14. Qxe7 Qxe7 15. Rxe7 cxd4
{ Black has a big advantage. In spite of his questionable structure, he is a pawn up. More importantly, however, White lacks queenside development, and there are ideas of ...Be6 trying to make it difficult for the Rook to escape, ...Ra/fb8 and ...Bf5 targeting c2. }
