[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Spanish Sidelines: 5.d4 and Rare Lines"]
[Black "5.d4 #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d4
{ I can personally attest that this line is tricky to meet when you don't know very much about it. However, once you've learned a few key details, it becomes significantly less scary. }
5... exd4 6. O-O Be7 7. Re1 b5 8. Bb3 d6 9. Bd5
{ This is a reasonable attempt to win the pawn back without getting his Bishop trapped, but he has to give up this Bishop in the process. }
9... Nxd5 10. exd5 Ne5 11. Nxd4 O-O
{ Black has two Bishops and a well placed Knight on e5. The first player may have a space advantage due to his d5-pawn, but this pawn is also liable to become weak in the future. }
12. a4 Bd7
{ Developing a piece and covering b5. We don't want to play ...b4 until Nc3 is played, at which point, it will come with tempo. }
13. Nc3 b4 14. Nce2 Qb8
{ Black intends ...Qb7 to put pressure on the d5 pawn. We have some advantage here, as the d-pawn is weak, we have two Bishops, and a strong Knight on e5 which can only be ejected with the weakening f2-f4. ...Bf6 and a Rook to the e-file is a likely follow-up to this Queen maneuvre. }
