[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Spanish Sidelines: 5.Qe2"]
[Black "6.O-O with 8.d4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. Qe2
{ This is the Worrall Variation, which has been part of my repertoire at various points in time. White covers the e4 pawn, thus avoiding the Open Variation, while also clearing the d1 square for a Rook to use in the future. }
5... Be7
{ I've chosen to recommend a Marshall-adjacent approach, which gains in strength with White's Queen on e2. Naturally, lines with ...Bc5 are also totally okay. }
6. O-O
{ This and  6.c3  are quite liable to transpose into each other, although both have their own independent options. }
6... b5 7. Bb3 O-O
{ As in the Marshall, Black delays ...d6, so he can push in the centre with ...d5. }
8. d4 { This is a questionable gambit approach. } 8... Nxd4 9. Nxd4 exd4 10. e5
Ne8 11. c3
{ If Black were forced to take on c3 here, then this whole line may well be more popular. However, there is a stronger move.   11.Qe4  doesn't achieve much, as after  11...Rb8  ,  12.Qxd4??  would run into  12...c5  13.Qd1  c4  . }
11... c5
{ Good move - Black returns his pawn in order to establish a mobile queenside pawn majority. }
12. cxd4 c4 13. Bc2 d5 14. f4 f5
{ Black's poisition is slightly more pleasant here in my opinion. The point is that, having played ...f7-f5, White's progress on the Kingside is now much more difficult. Meanwhile, on the other side of the board, it's much harder to slow down Black's play, as the corresponding b2-b4 is quite hard to make work. }
*

