[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. Qe2
{ This is the Worrall Variation, which has been part of my repertoire at various points in time. White covers the e4 pawn, thus avoiding the Open Variation, while also clearing the d1 square for a Rook to use in the future. }
5... Be7
{ I've chosen to recommend a Marshall-adjacent approach, which gains in strength with White's Queen on e2. Naturally, lines with ...Bc5 are also totally okay. }
6. O-O
{ This and  6.c3  are quite liable to transpose into each other, although both have their own independent options. }
6... b5 7. Bb3 O-O
{ As in the Marshall, Black delays ...d6, so he can push in the centre with ...d5. }
8. a4
{ This is a standard theme in the Spanish in general, but not so common here. }
8... b4 { Pushing past and keeping the a-file closed. } 9. a5
{ This is a thematic move, stopping  ...Na5  , allowing for  Ba4  , and splitting the  a6  and b4-pawns. After a move like  9.d3  , Black gets fine play with  9...Na5  . }
9... Rb8
{ This is an interesting move order. The point is essentially that after the normal  9...d6  ,  10.c3  would make things somewhat tricky. These positions are still fine for Black, but they require entering some forcing variations to fully equalize. Therefore, by starting with ...Rb8, we eliminate the option of the immediate c2-c3, as the Bishop on  b3  would be hanging after we take on  b4  . The downside is that the  a6  pawn is now less well defended, but if Black is careful, he can avoid hanging it unprofitably. }
10. d3
{ This is a pretty normal approach. Note, however, that White's Queen is no longer in contact with the pawn on a6, which is a bit of a relief for us.   After the immediate  10.Bc4  , Black can continue with  10...Bb7  , intending to break with  ...d5  sooner rather than later. Note that taking on  a6  isn't so great for White, because of  11.Bxa6  Bxa6  12.Qxa6  Nxe4  . }
10... d6 11. Bc4
{ This is another thematic move; putting pressure on the a6-pawn and taking the b5 square away from our Rook. }
11... Be6
{ The hanging pawn on a6 is a bit illusory, because we can play ...Ra8 and immediately regain our pawn by capturing on a5. Note that taking on e6 would open the f-file for us but, importantly, it also costs White a tempo, since he played Bb3-c4xe6. }
12. Bxe6
{ 12.Nbd2  Bxc4  is fine for us. We can continue with useful moves like ...Qd7 and ...h6, with ideas such as ...Rb5 attacking a5 and ...d5 breaking in the centre on our radar. }
12... fxe6
{ We have decent play, with ...Nh5-f4, ...Qe8-g6 and ...d5 all being ideas. With White's Light Squared Bishop off the board, ...Rb5 is also tempting in some positions, going after the a5-pawn. }
