[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Spanish Sidelines: 5.Qe2"]
[Black "Main Line #1 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. Qe2
{ This is the Worrall Variation, which has been part of my repertoire at various points in time. White covers the e4 pawn, thus avoiding the Open Variation, while also clearing the d1 square for a Rook to use in the future. }
5... Be7
{ I've chosen to recommend a Marshall-adjacent approach, which gains in strength with White's Queen on e2. Naturally, lines with ...Bc5 are also totally okay. }
6. O-O
{ This and  6.c3  are quite liable to transpose into each other, although both have their own independent options. }
6... b5 7. Bb3 O-O
{ As in the Marshall, Black delays ...d6, so he can push in the centre with ...d5. }
8. c3
{ White prepares d2-d4. If he's allowed to get that in, he may have chances for an advantage. We should beat him to it. }
8... d5
{ This Marshall-style Gambit is very strong. It's so strong, in fact, that White is generally advised not to accept it. }
9. exd5 { Accepting the gambit pawn is risky, as White's Queen is exposed. }
9... Nxd5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5
{ I played the alternative  10...Nf4  here in a tournament game several years ago. There's a connection between that move and the film '2001: A Space Odessey', but that's a story for another time. }
11. Qxe5 Nf6
{ If you know your chess history, you're aware that this was Frank Marshall's original idea in the Marshall proper rather than the modern ...c6 approach. White's exposed Queen means that Mr. Marshall's idea can be strongly applied to this situation. }
12. d4 Bd6 13. Qe2 Re8
{ Black continues to attack the Queen, gaining tempi for development. } 14. Qd1
Bb7
{ Just for the record, the computer ever so slightly prefers  14...Bg4  15.f3  Bh5  . I understand the point; to include f2-f3 as a weakness. However, this somehow feels more natural, and I do really like the two Bishops raking towards the Kingside like this. Black has excellent compensation here. }
*

