1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. Qe2
{ This is the Worrall Variation, which has been part of my repertoire at various points in time. White covers the e4 pawn, thus avoiding the Open Variation, while also clearing the d1 square for a Rook to use in the future. }
5... Be7
{ I've chosen to recommend a Marshall-adjacent approach, which gains in strength with White's Queen on e2. Naturally, lines with ...Bc5 are also totally okay. }
6. c3
{ This is White's other main move order. It can very well transpose into  6.O-O  , but does not have to. }
6... b5 7. Bc2
{ This is one additional option that White has. The Bishop on c2 is not subject to attacks via ...Na5 or ...a5-a4, but is also argaubly less active. }
7... O-O
{ 7...d5  is also good, when  8.d4  Bg4  9.exd5  Bxf3  10.Qxf3  Qxd5  11.Qxd5  Nxd5  12.dxe5  Nxe5  reaches an equal endgame. The text keeps more play in the position. }
8. O-O d5 { Now, it's definitely time to strike in the centre. } 9. d3 Re8
{ The computer prefers this slightly to ...Be6, which we play in the Worrall main line. These approaches are similar, as we're likely to play ...h6 and ...Be6 at some later point. The idea is that ...Re8 is a bit more flexible, and with the Bishop on c2 rather than b3, we don't have to worry about threats along the a2-f7 diagonal for the most part. }
