1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. Qe2
{ This is the Worrall Variation, which has been part of my repertoire at various points in time. White covers the e4 pawn, thus avoiding the Open Variation, while also clearing the d1 square for a Rook to use in the future. }
5... Be7
{ I've chosen to recommend a Marshall-adjacent approach, which gains in strength with White's Queen on e2. Naturally, lines with ...Bc5 are also totally okay. }
6. c3
{ This is White's other main move order. It can very well transpose into  6.O-O  , but does not have to. }
6... b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. d3 O-O 9. Nbd2
{ 9.O-O  would transpose into the main line, but White is not obligated to castle so quickly.  White is effectively trying to save a bit of time by getting Nf1-g3 in before castling. Therefore, we should proceed directly, to avoid giving our opponent the time to complete his plan. }
9... a5
{ My computer is a large fan of expanding on the queenside here. As a general rule, playing on the wing makes the most sense when the centre cannot be profitably opened. As White has yet to castle, exd5 is much less likely. This is my 'principled' justification for why ...a5 is strong here. }
10. a4 b4 11. O-O Rb8
{ Black can proceed with either ...Ba6 or ...Be6, ...Re8 and at some point ...bxc3 to activate the Rook on b8. }
