[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Spanish Sidelines: 5.d3"]
[Black "6.c3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 d6
{ Black has many good options at this junction. The text is a favorite of mine as it's very practical and easy to learn. I'll be recommending Black fianchetto the dark-squared bishop on g7, from where it covers the e5 pawn and can become very active once we break with ...d5. }
6. c3
{ White creates a square for the bishop on c2, thus neutralizing the positional 'threat' of ... b5 followed by ...Na5. }
6... g6 7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1 O-O 9. h3
{ A useful waiting move, keeping the position of the queenside minor pieces flexible. Usually, when Black goes for the central break ...d5 White tends to develop the bishop to e3 to exert more control over the center. However, if Black opts for kingside play with ...f5, White's bishop on e3 can find itself exposed to ...f5-f4. }
9... h6 { Turns out we also have useful waiting moves at our disposal! } 10. a3
{ Another classy waiting move, not only preparing d4 but also taking control over the b4 square which can be useful in the case of d4 ...exd4 cxd4.   10.Be3  is premature as Black can go for  10...Nd7  preparing ...f5. }
10... Re8
{ Enough waiting games, Black overprotects the e5 pawn in preparation for ...d5. }
11. Be3 d5 12. Nbd2 b5
{ It's time to get rid of the White's active bishop and gain space on the queenside. }
13. Bc2 a5
{ Black has equal chances in this tense middlegame position.   Play may continue with  14.b4  when  14...Be6  15.Nb3  Nd7!  comes just in time to cover the c5 square.   14.Qc1  hits h6 and positions the queen on the c-file, which will be soon be opened up with d3-d4.  14...Kh7  15.d4  dxe4!  16.Nxe4  Bf5  17.Ng3  Bxc2  18.Qxc2  was all recommended by Nils Grandelius in the Chessable course The Grand Ruy Lopez where the Swedish GM suggested White can continue with Rad1 and possibly h4-h5 later on. Black has a good game after  18...a4  fixing the queenside. On a good day, Black can look to exploit the weak light-squares in White's camp with Na5-c4/b3 .  19.Rad1  exd4  20.cxd4  Qd6  21.Rc1  Re6=  neutralizes White's pressure down the c-file. ...Nd5 or ...b4 are likely coming next with equal chances. }
*

