1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6
{ The Exchange Spanish, where White gives up the two bishops to slightly damage our queenside pawn structure. Ideally, White would like to trade down to an endgame where the superior pawn structure plays a major role. Conversely, Black should in general avoid piece exchanges and strive for active play, particularly making use of the two bishops.  Nowadays, the Exchange variation is rarely played at the top level nowadays given that Black has several lines that promise easy equality. }
4... dxc6 5. Nc3
{ This natural knight development fails to ask any questions whatsoever. By placing the knight on c4, White no longer has the option of playing c2-c3. }
5... f6
{ Simple and effective, reinforcing the e5 pawn. There's no need for ...Bg4 or ...Bd6, when White has some chances for an advantage with the d4 break. }
6. d4 exd4 7. Qxd4 { Swapping off the queens gives White absolutely nothing. }
7... Qxd4 8. Nxd4 Bd7 { followed by ...O-O-O with an easy game. } *

