[Black "5.O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6
{ The Exchange Spanish, where White gives up the two bishops to slightly damage our queenside pawn structure. Ideally, White would like to trade down to an endgame where the superior pawn structure plays a major role. Conversely, Black should in general avoid piece exchanges and strive for active play, particularly making use of the two bishops.  Nowadays, the Exchange variation is rarely played at the top level nowadays given that Black has several lines that promise easy equality. }
4... dxc6 5. O-O
{ This flexible option is White's main move. With the king on g1, the first player is now threatening to take on e5. }
5... Qf6
{ Black has several good options at this junction. This queen sortie is my preferred option as it gives Black more chances to play for a full point than  5...Bd6  or  5...Bg4  . }
6. d3
{ is too slow. White's bishop may very well be coming to g5 but our queen will be perfectly well placed on d6. }
6... Ne7 7. Bg5 Qd6 8. Nbd2 Ng6 9. a4 a5
{ was a fully satisfactory opening outcome for Black in 1-0 45 Lu,S 2630 -Wang,H 2710 Tianjin 2018. The second player lost the game, but not as a result of the opening. A logical continuation is to play ...f6 and ...c5, increasing the scope of the unopposed light-squared bishop on c8 while restricting White's dark-squared bishop. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Spanish Sidelines: Exchange Variation"]
[Black "5.O-O #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6
{ The Exchange Spanish, where White gives up the two bishops to slightly damage our queenside pawn structure. Ideally, White would like to trade down to an endgame where the superior pawn structure plays a major role. Conversely, Black should in general avoid piece exchanges and strive for active play, particularly making use of the two bishops.  Nowadays, the Exchange variation is rarely played at the top level nowadays given that Black has several lines that promise easy equality. }
4... dxc6 5. O-O
{ This flexible option is White's main move. With the king on g1, the first player is now threatening to take on e5. }
5... Qf6
{ Black has several good options at this junction. This queen sortie is my preferred option as it gives Black more chances to play for a full point than  5...Bd6  or  5...Bg4  . }
6. d4 { Expanding in the center is the only testing continuation. } 6... exd4
7. Bg5
{ 7.Qxd4  has been seen but the resulting endgame is once again very comfortable for Black.  7...Qxd4  8.Nxd4  Bd7= }
7... Qd6
{ It may seem as if White has gained time on our queen. On closer inspection, these tempi are irrelevant given that we're only two or three moves away from castling long. }
8. Nxd4 Be7
{ Neutralizes the bishop on g5, which is White's most active piece. Once the bishop moves away from the h4-d8 diagonal, we'll easily castle long. }
9. Bxe7 Nxe7
{ Now that White's bishop is gone from g5, there's no stopping ...Bd7 followed by ... O-O-O. }
10. Nc3 Bd7 11. Nb3 O-O-O
{ Black has no problems whatsoever. Given enough time, we can even consider anchoring the knight on e5 and following up with ...g5. }
*

