9. Nxd4 { Was capturing the d4 pawn a good idea? } 9... Nxd4 10. Qxd4 c5 11.
Qd1 c4 { traps the bishop. This is the age old Noah's Ark Trap. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "0-1 Jeffrey Xiong (2708) vs. Baskaran Adhiban (2639) FIDE Grand Swiss 2019"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following is a top level game between American super-GM Jeffrey Xiong and the strong Indian GM Baskaran Adhiban from the 2019 FIDE Grand Swiss. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. c3 Bc5 10. Qd3
{ is an interesting alternative to the main move  10.Nbd2  White prepares either Be3 or Nbd2 anyway. }
10... O-O 11. Be3 { 11.Nbd2  is covered in thetheory section. } 11... Bxe3 12.
Qxe3 f5 { 12...Na5  or  12...f6  are good alternatives. } 13. exf6
{ Instead, simply developing with  13.Nbd2  can be answered by  13...Qe7  clearing the way for ... Rad8 with a good game. }
13... Qxf6 14. Nbd2 { Effectively eliminates the e4 knight. } 14... Nxd2 15.
Qxd2 Kh8
{ 15...Rad8!  would have been slightly more accurate. The rook certainly belongs on d8, not only protecting the d5 pawn but also supporting ...d5-d4 in certain variations. Meanwhile, it's not clear ...Kh8 is at all necessary. A sample line runs  16.a4  d4!  17.axb5  axb5  18.Bxe6+  Qxe6  19.cxd4  Nxd4  20.Nxd4  Qb6  followed by ...c5 when Black will recoup the piece with an equal game. }
16. Rfe1 Rad8 17. Nd4
{ A natural, albeit inaccurate move. The knight may look active on d4 but it's actually doing very little. Moreover, ...Na5/...Ne5 followed by ...c5 will now come with tempo.   17.Re3  Bg8  18.Rd1  d4!  was a timely break in ½-½  50 Kamsky,G 2710-Anand,V 2715 Las Palmas 1995. Black had no problems whatsoever. }
17... Bg8 18. Bc2
{ White gets out of the way of ...Na5 but Black's knight can still find its way to c4 via e5. }
18... Ne5
{ Black is threatening both ...c5 and ...Nc4. It's clear White has gone wrong and the first player must now start thinking about equalizing. }
19. b4
{ Rules out ...c5 but surrenders control over the c4 square.   White could have equalized by tactical means with  19.Rxe5!  Qxe5  20.Nc6  Qf6  21.Nxd8  Rxd8  22.Qd4=  with a completely level game. }
19... Nc4 20. Qe2 a5
{ A typical continuation once the knight has made its way to c4. Black wants to open the a-file to target the a2 pawn. }
21. Qf3
{ 21.a3  was necessary. Xiong may have been afraid of the piece sacrifice  21...Nxa3!  as after  22.Rxa3  axb4  23.Raa1  bxc3  Black looks to have a very menacing squad of queenside pawns. However, White can still maintain the balance with precise play:  24.Nxb5  c6  25.Ra6  Bf7  White has sufficient resources to hold here but it's no fun at all. It's unsurprising Xiong rejected this option. }
21... Qb6
{ The queen swings over to the queenside with two very concrete threats. The obvious ...Rxf3 and ... axb4. White succumbed to the pressure and immediately blundered with }
22. Qg3
{ 22.bxa5!  was absolutely necessary. After  22...Nxa5  23.Qg3  Play can continue  23...c5  24.Nxb5!  just about maintains the balance. Not at all easy to see!  24...Qxb5  25.Re7=  Bf7  Of course not   25...Rf7?  which runs into a double-attack after  26.Rxf7  Bxf7  27.Qh4+-  26.Qh3  As Mikhalevski pointed out in his excellent chesspublishing.com lecture, Black has nothing better than a draw after  26...g6   26...Bg8  27.Qg3=  27.Bxg6!!  Bxg6  28.Qh6!  White's concrete threats never give Black enough time to make use of the two extra pieces.  28...Rg8  29.Rxh7+!  Bxh7  30.Qf6+  Rg7  31.Qxd8+  Black cannot escape perpetual check on the d8, f6 and h4 squares. Again, this is all very hard to spot from afar! }
22... axb4 23. Nf5 Qf6 24. cxb4 d4
{ Black's passed d-pawn will now decide the game. The immediate threat is ...Nb2 followed by ...d3. }
25. Ne7 Be6
{ Black brings the bishop out, seeking to exchange it for White's c2 bishop. Once that happens, the d-pawn will be unstoppable. }
26. Nc6 Rd6 27. Na5 Bf5 28. Bxf5 Qxf5
{ With the light-squared bishops exchanged, the path for the d-pawn has been cleared. }
29. Nb3 d3 30. Rad1 d2
{ @@StartBlockQuote@@Push em baby! - Yasser Seirawan@@EndBlockQuote@@ } 31. Re7
{ 31.Rf1  Qc2-+  is also decisive. White's queenside now falls. } 31... Rg6 32.
Nd4 { Desperation. This fails tactically following... } 32... Qf6 33. Re6 Qxd4
34. Rxg6 Qe4
{ with the double-threat of Qe1 checkmating and ...Qxg6, when Black will be up a piece. White resigned. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "0-1 Yasser Seirawan (2610) vs. Uriel Zak (2335) Lugano 1989"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. c3
{ A multi-purpose move, opening up a window for the light-squared bishop to retreat to c2 from where it can pressure the b1 knight. Additionally, c2-c3 supports a later Nd4 and keeps the queenside minors flexible. }
9... Bc5
{ This is the most active position for Black's dark-squared bishop. From this location, it exerts control over the critical d4 square and eyes the f2 pawn. The downsides of this move are that Black's kingside is slightly more exposed, in particular the g5 square when compared to 9...Be7. Moreover, the often desirable ...c5 advance will now take longer to get in. Finally, the king's bishop is also more exposed to being exchanged off on c5. }
10. Nbd2 O-O 11. Bc2 Bf5
{ A rather solid option, simply reinforcing the e4 knight.   11...Nxf2  was our main recommendation in the theoretical section. }
12. Nb3 Bxf2+
{ An interesting sacrifice, which must have come as a shock to Seirawan with the White pieces. Objectively, this move is quite dubious albeit hard to refute over the board. }
13. Rxf2 { White has no option but to accept the sacrifice. } 13... Nxf2 14.
Kxf2 Bxc2 15. Qxc2 f6
{ Black seeks to open the f-file to get to White's king. } 16. exf6
{ A big mistake. Taking on f6 only helps Black activate his pieces!   16.e6!  keeping lines closed was the way to go! A sample variation runs  16...Re8  17.Nc5  Qd6  18.b4±  when it's not easy for Black to continue the attack. }
16... Qxf6 17. Kg1 Ne5
{ In comes another attacker, Black immediately dials up the pressure! } 18. Qd1
{ White covers the f3 knight and hits the d5 pawn. White is more than welcome to take it though!   18.Nbd4  would have helped stabilize the position. White reinforces the f3 knight and prepares Bg5.  18...h6  19.b4!  It's paramount to prevent ...c5.   19.Be3?  is careless. After  19...c5  20.Ne2  Nxf3+  White's kingside collapses.  19...a5  20.Bb2  Nc4=  followed by ... Rae8 with all to play for. }
18... Rae8
{ Black brings the last piece into the game and is now ready to pounce on White's king. }
19. Qxd5+ Kh8 20. Bd2 Nxf3+ 21. gxf3
{ Forced.   21.Qxf3??  loses on the spot to  21...Qb6+-+  . } 21... Re2
{ It's clear things have gone horribly wrong for White. The king on g1 is very exposed and Black's rook on e2 is super active. }
22. Be1 Rxb2 23. Nd4 Qf4 24. Bg3
{ The final mistake which gives Black free reign over the 2nd rank.   24.Bf2  Qd2  25.Rf1  would have kept White in the game. }
24... Qd2 25. f4 c5
{ White's knight is pinned and will fall next as the d5 queen must keep contact with the g2 square. White soon lost. }
26. f5 cxd4 27. cxd4 Qd3 28. f6 gxf6 29. Rf1 Rg8 30. Rxf6 Rxg3+ 31. hxg3 Qe3+
{ Faced with mate in two, White threw in the towel. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "0-1 Anatoly Karpov (2690) vs. Viktor Kortschnoj (2650) Merano 1981"]
[Result "*"]

{ It's now time to go through the action-packed game 6 of the 1981 World Championship match between Karpov and Kortschnoj. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. c3 Bc5 10. Nbd2 O-O 11. Bc2 Bf5 12. Nb3 Bg6
{ A far more solid and reliable option than Zak's  12...Bxf2!?  that we saw in the previous game. A world Championship match is certainly no place for such shenanigans! }
13. Nfd4 Bxd4 14. cxd4 a5
{ Black wastes no time marching the a-pawn down the board to create weaknesses in White's queenside. Importantly, Black gives the first player no time to play Be3 and anchor the b3 knight on c5. }
15. Be3 a4 16. Nc1
{ 16.Nd2  is more testing as it costs White less time to get the knight back into the game than  16.Nc1  . }
16... a3 17. b3 f6
{ Black's standard pawn break, chipping away at White's strong e5 pawn and opening up lines on the kingside. }
18. exf6
{ 18.Nd3  Qe7  19.f4  would have kept the central structure intact. In turn, Black's knight would have been firmly entrenched on e4. }
18... Qxf6 19. Ne2 Nb4 20. Bb1 Qe7
{ Black steps out of the f-file and supports a later ...c5 break.   20...Rae8  was another good option. }
21. Qe1
{ 21.Re1  intending to get f3 in is well met by  21...Rae8  22.Nf4  Qf6  23.Nxg6  hxg6  with chances for both sides. }
21... Rfe8 22. Nf4 Bf7
{ Black naturally preserves the light-squared bishop and reinforces the d5 pawn. }
23. Qc1
{ White is hoping to prevent ...c5 but Black can get it in anyhow.   23.f3  Nd6  24.Bf2  was a better option. }
23... c5 { Kortschnoj sacrifices a piece to activate his pieces. } 24. dxc5 Qf6
25. Bxe4 Rxe4 26. Ne2
{ is a questionable decision given it allows Black to push ahead with ...d4.   26.Qd2  would have prevented ...d4. }
26... d4 27. Ng3 Ree8 28. Qd2
{ White hopes to be able to round up the d4 pawn and prove it's a weakness. Kortschnoj ended up proving him wrong as we shall see. }
28... Nc6 29. Bg5 { 29.Bf4  with the idea Bd6 was superior. } 29... Qe5 30.
Rac1 d3
{ The pawn continues marching forward, gaining more space and further tying up White's pieces. The d3 pawn and the presence of opposite colored bishops will make it very hard for White to keep his position together.   The pawn is taboo as  31.Qxd3??  blunders  31...Qxg5 }
31. Rfd1 Bg6 32. Be3 Re6 33. Bf4 Qf6 34. Re1 Rae8 35. Rxe6 Rxe6 36. Rb1
{ It's hard to recommend a move for White here but Rb1 certainly achieves nothing. }
36... h5 { In comes the h-pawn which will further knock back White's pieces. }
37. h3 h4
{ 37...Nd4  with the idea ...Ne2+ would have been practically decisive. After  38.Bg5  Qf8  39.Be3  Qxc5  Black restores material equality and maintains an overwhelming position. }
38. Bg5 Qd4 39. Be3 Qd5
{ A mistake that could have allowed White back into the game. } 40. Nf1
{ 40.Ne2!  exploiting the pin to reroute the knight to f4 would have put a big dent on Black's attack. }
40... Be4 { The g2 pawn now falls and with it White's kingside. } 41. Bf4
{ 41.f3  would have simply been taken with  41...Bxf3  42.gxf3  Ne5  43.Nh2  Nxf3+  44.Nxf3  Qxf3-+  when the e3 bishop is hanging and ... Rg6+ is coming. White is busted. }
41... Bxg2
{ White resigned. This was Kortschnoj first win against Karpov in the 1981 World Championship in Merano, Italy. A memorable attacking game in the Open Spanish even if Kortschnoj did end up losing the match +6-2=10.   Note that  42.Ne3  Qf3  43.Nxg2  Re2-+  is lights out. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "0-1 Marie Sebag (2496) vs. Mariya Muzychuk (2542) Reykjavik 2015"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. c3 Be7 10. Nbd2 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. Nb3 Qd7 13. Nbd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 c5 15.
Nxe6 Qxe6 16. f3 Ng5 17. a4 Rad8 18. Bxg5 Bxg5 19. f4 Be7 20. axb5 axb5 21. Kh1
d4 22. cxd4 c4
{ This was all covered in thetheoretical section. At a high level, these positions have quite a high drawing tendency, due to the relatively simplified position and opposite colour bishops. That's not to say that the players in this game are not at a high level they are both Grandmasters, and the player with the Black pieces was the women's world champion at the time of this game, but just that it's still possible to make a mistake, especially in positions with mutual passed pawns. }
23. b3
{ 23.Qd2  Rd7  24.Qa5  Qc6  25.Rad1  Rd5  followed either by ...Rfd8 or ...Bd8-b6 is not particularly impressive for White, as demonstrated in two games of the correspondence player Pascal Roques. }
23... Bc5
{ Winning the pawn back straight away. White really doesn't have any advantage to speak of once his opponent restores material equality. }
24. bxc4 Rxd4 25. Qb1
{ 25.Qf3  was played in two very high level games, where the first players achieved nothing.  25...bxc4  26.Rfd1  g6  27.Rxd4  Bxd4  28.Ra8   28.Rd1  Rd8  29.Qb7  Bb6  30.Rxd8+  Bxd8  31.Ba4  Qb6  32.Qxb6  Bxb6  1/2-1/2 in Anand-So, Wijk aan Zee 2018.  Rxa8  29.Qxa8+  Kg7  30.Qb7+  Qf7  31.Qxf7+  1/2-1/2 in Adams-Giri, Shenzhen 2017. }
25... bxc4 26. Ra5 Qc6 27. Bd1 Qc7 28. Qb5 Bb6 29. Ra6 Rb8 30. Bf3 c3
{ The position is still pretty much level, but the c-pawn is beginning to look fairly imposing. }
31. Rc1
{ 31.e6  would make it somewhat difficult for Black to pretend to be playing for a win. e6-e7 is a serious threat, as the queen is overloaded on c7. There's also a threat to f5 to keep in mind.  31...Qc5   31...c2??  32.e7  wins for White.  32.Qxc5  Bxc5  33.Rc6= }
31... Kh8 32. Ra8
{ I suspect that White had imagined that nothing very dangerous would happen after the rook exchange, due to the threat of Qe8#. Unfortunately for her, there is indeed an effective multi-purpose move.   32.g3  It's a good idea to make sure f4 is defended. We'll see White losing this pawn in the game. }
32... Rxa8 33. Bxa8 Rd8
{ It could also be the backwards nature of this move that made it difficult to spot. Black achieves three things; stops mate, threatens the bishop and clears the way for ...Be3, winning the f4-pawn. }
34. Bf3 Be3 35. Rc2 Bxf4
{ Once f4 falls, e5 begins looking fairly vulnerable. } 36. e6 Rb8 37. Qd5 Rb1+
38. Bd1 h6
{ This is a pretty quiet-looking move but it wins the game almost instantly. The point is to set up ...Qd6 while being able to meet a potentially disrputive Qa8+ with ...Kh7. }
39. Qd3 Qd6 { The bishop on d1 is doomed, so White resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "0-1 Anatoly Karpov vs. Valery Chekhov Moscow 1972"]
[Result "*"]

{ I had to do a double take upon seeing this game in my database. Black  (a player I don't really know anything about)  pretty soundly defeats Karpov in 39 moves. That's incredibly impressive on its own, but Chekhov was also 16 at the time! Okay, this isn't Karpov at his absolute peak, but he did qualify for a World Championship Match not too long after this game was played. Chekhov also beat Spassky in this same line in the same year! }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. c3 Be7 10. Nbd2 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. Nb3 Qd7 13. Nfd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 c5 15.
Nxe6 Qxe6 16. f3 Ng5 17. Re1
{ This move didn't really catch on, with fewer than a couple handfuls of games in the ChessBase Online Database in 2022. This variation was still in its infancy at the time, so there wasn't any particular established theory to go off of. A dubious symbol would be a bit harsh, but Black isn't under any particular pressure after this move.   17.a4  and  17.Bxg5  are considered the principal moves nowadays. }
17... Rad8 18. Qe2
{ White's play doesn't leave an overly terrifying impression, so Chekov rightly decides to pursue the initiative. }
18... c4
{ We've seen this move time and again in this variation. It does have to be timed correctly, but is quite effective in many different situations. }
19. Kh1
{ Again, it's unfair to call this a bad move, but Black is being allowed to get all his ideas in. }
19... f4
{ Another thematic move; Black both prevents f3-f4 from White and prepares ...Bc5 by cutting off the c1-bishop's view of the knight. }
20. b3 Bc5
{ The computer slightly prefers  20...Qc6  but I can hardly call Chekhov's choice a bad move. }
21. Bd2
{ White continues drifting into a worse position.   21.a4  is possible, although this should have been played a little while ago.  21...d4!  22.bxc4  bxc4  23.cxd4  Bxd4  24.Rb1  Bc3!  wins the e5-pawn, but White at least has the bishop pair on an open board to compensate. }
21... Rde8 { 21...Qh6  immediately is also good. } 22. a4
{ It's probably a bit too late to be able to exploit the a-file.   22.Rad1  is the computer's preference. }
22... Qh6
{ This is a queen slide worth keeping in mind. It showed up in the theoretical section and in certain cases can prove very effective. After ...Re6, Black will be threatening ...Qxh2+ with mate in two, while ...Qh4 and ...Bf2 is another attacking idea. }
23. axb5 axb5 24. b4
{ 24.bxc4  is a better way to generate counterplay. For example:  24...bxc4  25.Ra5  skewering the bishop and the d5-pawn, thereby prompting one of Black's attackers to come support the bishop. }
24... Bb6 25. Ra6
{ Karpov continues ambitiously, but at this point it was better to defend meekly.   25.Qf1  Re6  26.h3  poses the question of how exactly Black wants to progress. He's doubtless much better, but White seems to be holding off any immediate attack. }
25... Re6
{ Suddenly White is in desperate trouble, with ...Qxh2+ being an immediate threat. }
26. Rxb6 { The best defense. } 26... Rxb6 27. Qf2 Ra6 28. g3
{ Attempting to make use of the c1-h6 diagonal, but this backfires. } 28...
fxg3 29. Qxg3 Ne4 { Remember that every pin can also be a discovery. } 30. Bxh6
Nxg3+ 31. hxg3 gxh6 { This endgame is pretty hopeless for White. } 32. f4 Ra3
33. e6 Rxc3 34. Bd1 Rxg3 35. e7 Re8 36. f5 Rg5 37. f6 Kf7 38. Rf1 d4 39. Bf3
Rf5 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "0-1 Emil Sutovsky (2654) vs. Ivan Sokolov (2696) Hoogeven 2005"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Ivan Sokolov is an expert on the Ruy Lopez in general, although he did write a book specifically on systems other than 3... a6. }
4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5 Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O
11. Bc2 f5
{ It is nice to know that our recommended repertoire has been played on a high level for a reasonably long time. }
12. Nb3 Qd7 13. Nbd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 c5 15. Nxe6 Qxe6 16. f3 Ng5 17. a4 g6
{ 17...Rad8  is the main line, and was our choice in the theoretical section. Both moves are playable. }
18. Be3
{ I suspect that Sutovsky may have prepared this move. If Black takes on e5, a forcing sequence ensues, in which it seems that the second player is just about okay. Sokolov, however, sees no reason to go down that continuation. }
18... Qc6
{ This is the safe move, which not only avoids immediate complications, but also retains long-term winning chances. The plan is a 'changez le blockeur' technique, where the knight hops back to e6. In general, knights are the best piece to use for blockading passed pawns.   18...Qxe5!?  takes up the challenge.  19.Re1  Qd6  20.axb5  axb5  21.Rxa8  Rxa8  22.Bf4!  Qd7  23.Rxe7  Qxe7  24.Qxd5+  Kg7  25.Be5+  ...Qe1# was a pretty significant threat.  Kh6  26.Qxa8  Qxe5  27.Qf8+  Kh5  28.g4+  fxg4  29.fxg4+  Kh4  30.Qf2+  Kh3  Black actually seems to be totally okay here, but you have to be very sure of yourself to do something like this.   18...Rfd8?  19.Qd2  is one point of White's eighteenth move; we'd really like to be able to play ...Ne6 here. }
19. Bxg5
{ It's sensible to get rid of this knight. I would say this arguably reduces White's winning chances, but it's nice to be able to play f3-f4 with tempo without worrying about ...Ne4. Black also no longer has an entirely convenient blockader of the e5-pawn  (apart from maybe the king in an endgame)  . }
19... Bxg5 20. f4 Be7 21. Qf3 c4
{ This thematic advance clears c5 for a piece while beginning to push the queenside majority forward. }
22. Rfd1 Rad8 23. b4
{ White tries to block the queenside by preventing ...b5-b4.   23.Kh1  Kg7!  It's also possible to push ...b4 straight away.  24.h3  b4!  25.cxb4  Qb6!  26.Rxd5?!  Rxd5  27.Qxd5  The point of ...Kg7 was to avoid this being check.  Qxb4  and Black may even be better here. }
23... a5
{ Black should indeed be looking for a pawn break, but this turns out to be the wrong one.   23...Qb6+  24.Qf2  d4!  25.axb5  axb5  26.Rxd4   26.Kf1!?  I can see why Black may not have wanted to enter this position. It's a bit precarious with the d-pawn pinned, but White can't actually achieve anything definite.  26...Rxd4  27.Qxd4  Qxd4+  28.cxd4  Rd8  regains the pawn with a comfortable position. }
24. bxa5
{ 24.axb5  Qb6+   24...Qxb5??  25.Rxa5  is just a clean extra pawn.  25.Qf2  Qxf2+  26.Kxf2  axb4  27.cxb4  The computer is surprisingly optimistic about this for White. I suspect Black should be able to hold, but it's not actually that pleasant. }
24... b4 { Now Black is rolling. } 25. cxb4 Bxb4 26. Kh1 Qc5
{ Freeing the d-pawn to advance. This position might only be objectively equal but it feels like things are starting to go Black's way. }
27. a6 Rf7
{ This is not a bad move, but why not push the d-pawn?   27...d4  Well, easy for me to say. I'd want to play ...d4 regardless of what else is going on, but the computer actually backs me up this time. }
28. Rac1 Qa5 29. h4
{ 29.g4!  fxg4  30.Qxg4  and suddenly Black is facing a very strong attack, with f4-f5 coming up. }
29... Kh8
{ Not awful, but the wrong king move.   29...Kg7!!  Black would like to play ...d4, but Qc6 is annoying.  30.h5  d4  31.Qc6?!  Bd2!  Both c1 and f4 are threatened. The point of ...Kg7 was to avoid Qxc4  (followed by Bb3)  pinning the rook. Note that if the king were on h8 instead, the same rook would indeed be hanging.   29...d4?  30.Qc6! }
30. e6
{ 30.h5  is better, as the pawn ends up weak on e6.  d4?!  31.Qc6!  as we discussed earlier. }
30... Re7 31. Qe3 Qxa6 32. Qe5+
{ 32.Bb3!!   32.Bd3!!  both moves make use of the fact that ...cxd3 can be met  by Qd4+ regaining the piece. White seems to be able to hold the balance here. }
32... Kg8 33. Rb1
{ I'm not entirely sure what White missed here. Taking on d5 leads to a slightly worse but very drawable endgame, whereas the text loses.   33.Rxd5  Rxd5  34.Qxd5  Qxe6  35.Qxe6+  Rxe6⩱ }
33... Qa5
{ This is not the best continuation, but I can see why Black may not have wanted to take on  e6 immediately.   33...Rxe6  34.Rxd5  Rxe5  35.Rxd8+  Kf7  36.fxe5  Qa5-+  The computer says that Black is actually completely winning here, with White's king so exposed  (...Qxe5 and ...Bd6, for example, is quite scary)  . }
34. Qf6 Rf8 35. Qe5 Rd8 36. h5 Bc3 37. Qe2 Qc7 38. Qf3 d4 39. Rb5 Rxe6 40. Rb7
Qc6 41. Qxc3 dxc3 42. Rxd8+ Re8 43. Rdd7 Qf6 44. Kg1 gxh5 45. a5 Qg6 46. Re7
Rxe7 47. Rxe7 Qd6 48. Re2 Qc5+ 49. Kh2 Qxa5 50. Kg3 Qd5 51. Kh4 Qd3 52. Bxd3
cxd3 53. Re3 d2 54. Rd3 c2 55. Rxd2 c1=Q 56. Rd8+ Kf7 57. Kg5 h6+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "0-1 Robert Hovhannisyan (2591) vs. Manuel Petrosyan Yerevan (2570) 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. Nb3 Qd7 13. Nbd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 c5 15.
Nxe6 Qxe6 16. f3 Ng5 17. a4 Rad8 18. axb5 axb5 19. Ra7 g6
{ 19...Rd7  is our recommendation in thetheoretical section. } 20. Be3 Rd7
{ Grabbing the pawn on e5 is possible, but risky. The text is safer. } 21. Rxd7
Qxd7
{ Black should be fine here. Next he can drop his knight back to e6 and White doesn't have any particular pressure. }
22. Qd2
{ 22.b4  is often possible.  22...Qc6  just covering c5 is fine.   22...c4  is an option too.  23.f4  Ne6  24.g4  with unclear play typical for this variation.  23.bxc5  Bxc5  24.Bxc5  Qxc5+  25.Qd4  Qc4  26.Rb1  Ne6=   22.Bxg5  is another typical continuation, e.g.  22...Bxg5  23.f4  Be7  24.h3  and now Black can proceed thematically:  24...c4  25.Kh2  Bc5  26.Qf3  d4  27.cxd4  Qxd4= }
22... Ne6 23. b4 c4 24. Rd1 Rd8
{ 24...d4!?  If Black wants to simplify to clear equality, this is an option.  25.Bxd4  Nxd4  26.Qxd4  Qxd4+  27.Rxd4  Ra8=  ...Ra3xc3 is coming, and Black is fine. }
25. Bb6
{ White is beginning to drift into a worse position.   25.g4!?  fxg4  26.f4  is an interesting idea, leading to unclear play.  26...Ng7  This prevents f4-f5, although Black might be better off allowing it.  27.Be4  Kh8  28.Bxd5  and the game continues. }
25... Bg5 26. Qe1 Ra8
{ White doesn't have a ton of obvious play while Black improves his pieces. }
27. h4
{ This is an okay move, but weakening the king's position almost always carries some element of risk.   27.Ra1?  To illustrate White's issues, this natural move only exacerbates the problems.  27...Rxa1  28.Qxa1  Kg7  The computer gives Black a winning advantage here. The first player has to watch out for things like ...d4, ...Bf4xe5 and potentially ...Bd2xc3. }
27... Qc6 28. Bf2 Bh6 29. h5
{ 29.Ra1  should be preferred here, as otherwise Black gets to infiltrate. It's not always so easy to understand computer evaluations, such as why Ra1 was so bad in the previous note and much better in this version.  29...Rxa1  30.Qxa1  Black is still better here, but there's nothing clear.  30...Bf4   30...Kg7  31.g3  White intends f4, covering the potential weakness on e5 and closing the diagonal of the bishop on h6.  31.Qe1  Qc7?  is an attempt to win e5, but it backfires.  32.g3!  and taking on e5 is bad due to f4, winning a piece. }
29... Ra2 30. Bb1 Rb2 31. Be3
{ White tries to ease the pressure. It's hard to suggest a productive move here. }
31... Bxe3+ 32. Qxe3 Qb7
{ Black finds a brilliant way to transfer his queen towards the weakened kingside. }
33. Kf1 Qe7 34. Qc1 Qh4 { A clever move. } 35. Qxb2 Qh1+ 36. Kf2
{ 36.Ke2  Qxg2+  would win the queen. } 36... Qxd1
{ Black still has to convert this, of course, but at this stage he's got a winning advantage. }
37. h6 d4 38. cxd4 Kf7 39. Qa1 Qd2+ 40. Kf1 Qxd4 41. Qa6 Qd1+ 42. Kf2 Qd2+ 43.
Kf1 Qc1+ 44. Kf2 Qb2+ 45. Kg3 Qxe5+ 46. Kf2 Qb2+ 47. Kg3 Qxb1 48. Qb7+ Kf6 49.
Qxh7 Qe1+ 50. Kh2 Qh4+ 51. Kg1 Qd4+ 52. Kh2 Qd6+ 53. Kg1 Qf8 54. Qa7 Qxh6 55.
Qa1+ Kf7 56. Qa7+ Kg8 57. Qb8+ Qf8 58. Qxb5 Qc8 59. Qa4 c3 60. Qc2 Qc4 61. g4
Qxb4 62. gxf5 Qc5+ 63. Kh2 Qe5+ 64. f4 Qxf4+ 65. Kh1 Qf3+
{ A game pretty much perfectly played by Black. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "0-1 Jorden Van Foreest (2702) vs. Shakhriyar Mamedyarov (2767) Tata Steel Chess Masters 2022"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following is a top-level game in the Ljubojevic variation 9.a4 between super-GMs Jorden Van Foreest and Shakhriyar Mamedyarov from the 2022 Tata Steel Chess Masters. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. a4 b4 10. Be3 Be7
{ 10...Nc5  11.Nbd2  Be7  was our recommendation in thetheoretical section of the course. Mamedyarov's approach of starting with 10...Be7 to prepare ...O-O is also very logical. }
11. a5 O-O 12. Qd3 Nc5 13. Bxc5
{ is practically forced.   Moving the queen not only allows  13.Qe2  Nxb3  damaging White's structure but after  14.cxb3  Black can push forward with  14...d4  when White is already dead lost.  15.Bf4  g5  16.Bd2  g4  All of White's pieces get successively pushed back.  17.Ne1  d3  18.Qd1  Nxe5-+ }
13... Bxc5 14. c3
{ White's knight would love to pop out to the c3 square in order to pressure the d5 pawn. The b4 pawn is in its way so White challenges it with c2-c3. }
14... Ne7
{ Black naturally avoids taking on c3, which would only help White complete his development. The knight is well placed on e7, covering the d5 square and importantly it's no longer in the way of the c-pawn. This will enable Black to expand with ...c5 later on. }
15. Nbd2 { Only now that the knight is on d2 does Black take on c3. } 15...
bxc3 16. bxc3
{ White should have taken the chance to drop back the bishop with tempo with  16.Bc2!  threatening mate on h7.  16...Ng6   16...Bf5?!  is inaccurate as after  17.Qxc3  Ba7  18.Bxf5  Nxf5  19.b4±  Black has been left with weak pawns on c7 and d5.  17.bxc3  Compared to the game, the bishop is already on c2 and out of the way of ...c5-c4. }
16... Ba7 17. Nd4
{ It's too late to go  17.Bc2  now because of  17...Bf5  when White no longer has the option of Qxc3 as in the 16. Bc2 line. }
17... Bd7 18. N2f3 c5 { Black naturally expands in the center with tempo. } 19.
e6
{ 19.Ne2??  is impossible on account of  19...c4-+   19.Bc2  was once again the better choice. A sample line goes  19...g6  20.Ne2  Bf5  21.Qd2  when White is still very much in the game. }
19... Be8
{ White's idea behind  19.e6  can be seen after  19...fxe6??  allowing  20.Ng5  hitting h7 and e6.  20...g6  21.Ndxe6+-  is lights out. }
20. Ng5
{ Mamedyarov later commented this approach was 'too risky'.   Not to sound like a broken record but  20.Bc2  was once again the way to go.  20...f5  21.Ne2  with a complicated game. }
20... f5 { blocks out White's queen, neutralizing the threat of Qxh7#. } 21.
Nf7
{ A miscalculation that leads to White's demise.   21.Qh3  h6  and only now  22.Nf7  was the way to go. Following  22...Bxf7  23.exf7+  Rxf7  24.Ne6  Qd6  25.Rae1  White is slightly worse but still in the game. }
21... Rxf7
{ And not  21...c4  22.Qd2  Bxf7  23.exf7+  Rxf7  24.Ba4  with very decent compensation. }
22. exf7+ Bxf7
{ White is currently up an exchange but will now lose another minor piece. The d4 knight is hanging and ...c4 with a fork is also a threat. White can't parry both. }
23. Nxf5 c4 24. Bxc4 Nxf5
{ Mamedyarov naturally avoids  24...dxc4??  which hangs the knight on e7 after  25.Qxd8+  Rxd8  26.Nxe7+  Kf8  27.Nc6  Rd7  28.Nxa7  Rxa7  29.Rab1+-  White is winning with the extra exchange and pawn. }
25. Bxa6 Nd6
{ Black has two minor pieces for a rook and two pawns. The problem is White's bishop on a6 is completely dominated by the d6 knight and the a5 pawn is also very weak. And of course Black's dark-squared bishop is a monster. }
26. Qf3 Bc5
{ Black opens up the rook with tempo. The a5 pawn is about to drop. } 27. Bd3
Rxa5 28. Rxa5 Qxa5 29. h4
{ Black has a big advantage as the two minors are far stronger than White's rook. }
29... h5 30. g3 Ne8
{ The knight on d6 wasn't doing much so Black reroutes it to f6, from where it can jump to g4 to pressure f2. }
31. c4 dxc4 32. Bh7+ Kf8
{ 32...Kxh7  would have allowed  33.Qxf7  33...Nf6  34.Qxc4  when White can hold, quite comfortably. }
33. Bg6 Nf6 34. Bxf7 Kxf7 35. Rc1
{ Jorden loses the thread and Mamedyarov swiftly punishes him.   35.Qb7+  was the way to go.  35...Kg6  36.Qb1+  Kh6  37.Qc1+  Kg6  38.Qxc4  picking up the pawn when White's fine. }
35... Qc7 36. Kg2 { 36.Rxc4??  fails to  36...Bxf2+  37.Kxf2  Qxc4-+ } 36...
Bd4 37. Qa8 c3 { Black's passed pawn now decides the game. } 38. Qa2+ Kg6 39.
Qc2+ Kh6 40. Qd3 Qb7+ 41. f3 Qb2+ 42. Rc2 Qb1 43. Qf5 Be3 44. Kh3 Qd1
{ ...Bd2 is coming with a checkmate threat on h1. White can barely move and thus threw in the towel. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "0-1 Surya Shekhar Ganguly (2582) vs. Peter Heine Nielsen (2628) Tripoli 2004"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following is a model game in the 9. Be3 variation between Indian GM Surya Ganguly and GM Peter Heine Nielsen from the 2004 FIDE World Championship Knockout tournament in Tripoli. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Be3
{ is arguably a tad premature. It's by no means clear the bishop is always better placed on e3.   9.c3  keeping the queenside pieces flexible is the mainline. }
9... Be7 10. c3 O-O
{ The more flexible  10...Qd7  was our recommendation in the theoretical section of the course. }
11. Nbd2 Qd7 12. Bc2
{ 12.Nxe4  dxe4  13.Bxe6  Qxe6  14.Nd4  Nxd4  or 14...Qd7  15.cxd4  fails to give White anything. }
12... f5
{ As alluded to on move 9, e3 is usually not the best square for White's dark-squared bishop. Here, it's clear the bishop is misplaced. The threat of ...f4, trapping the bishop, forces White to go for }
13. exf6 { which only helps Black activate his pieces. } 13... Nxf6 14. Qb1
{ White is planning Ng5 to pressure Black's kingside. However, it turns out Black can simply ignore this threat as we shall see.   14.Re1  or  14.a4  were alternatives worth considering. }
14... Kh8 15. Ng5
{ White is clearly angling for the h7 pawn and Black simply says 'Go ahead and take it!'. }
15... Ng4
{ A very strong move, going after the e3 bishop and daring White to take on h7. This move emphasizes how misplaced the e3 bishop turned out to be. }
16. Nxh7
{ The critical move but not a good one!   16.Ndf3  is well answered by  16...Bxg5  17.Nxg5  Qd6  The threat of mate on h2 forces White to compromise his kingside with  18.g3  when  18...Nxe3  19.fxe3  Qe5  leaves White's position riddled with weaknesses. }
16... Rf5
{ This is the entire point! White's knight on h7 is trapped!   17.Bxf5??  only sets White up for a fork after  17...Bxf5-+  Black's two minors are far stronger than White's rook in this middlegame. }
17. Qd1 Nxe3 18. fxe3
{ White is hoping to get in Bxf5 followed by Ng5, intending to regain the knight after ...Bxg5 Qh5+. However, }
18... g6
{ firmly emprisons the knight. 18 moves into the game and White is already bust. }
19. a4
{ White tries to create some distraction on the queenside but to no avail. }
19... b4 20. cxb4 Nxb4 { 20...Rxf1+!  21.Qxf1  Kxh7  was even better. } 21.
Bxf5 Bxf5 22. Nf3 Kxh7
{ Needless to say, Black's two bishops are far more powerful than White's extra rook. The latter can hardly find an open file to operate in! }
23. Rc1 c5 24. h3 Qe6
{ Black gradually improves all his pieces and sets his eyes on the e3 weakness. }
25. Qd2 Rc8 26. h4 Kg8
{ A useful prophylactic move, stepping out of any Ng5+ nonsense. } 27. Ng5 Qe5
28. b3 Bd6 29. Rf4 d4
{ White resigned in this hopeless position. It's rather poetic that White's position quickly collapsed on the dark squares once Black chopped off the e3 bishop. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "0-1 David Navara (2697) vs. Shakhriyar Mamedyarov (2767) Baku 2021"]
[Result "*"]

{ This is a quite recent game. It's rapid chess, but it does show Mamedyarov outplaying Navara, a fellow extremely strong Grandmaster, from a typical Open Spanish position. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Qe2 Nc5
{ This is a decent choice, especially if Black particularly wants to avoid a draw. Until recently, I was under the impression that the move is just dubious, but it's actually not bad at all, even if 9...Be7 is sturdier theoretically.   9...Be7  is our recommedation in the course, which has the potential to lead to drawish positions after  10.Rd1  O-O  11.c4 }
10. Rd1 Nxb3 11. cxb3
{ It's hard to say which capture is better. The text, probably a bit less obvious, does have the benefit of opening the c-file. The c5-square and c6-knight are both potentially vulnerable. }
11... Be7 12. Nc3 O-O 13. Bf4
{ This is a natural enough developing move, but the bishop isn't always ideal on this square. }
13... Qd7 14. Rd2
{ Preparing to double on the d-file, but despite the vulnerable-looking d5-pawn, this turns out not to be a very effective plan. }
14... Nd8
{ Since White has sort of telegraphed his intention to double on the d-file, Mamedyrov prepares ...c6 to solidly defend the d5-pawn.   14...d4  is also reasonable.  15.Rad1  Bc5  followed by ...Rae8 and ...f6, with a good game. }
15. Rad1
{ This doesn't actually achieve very much when Black has ...c6 in reply. }
15... c6 16. h3
{ This seems best, stopping ... Bg4. The pin is fairly annoying, and a quick ...Ne6 and ...f6 would be excellent for the second player. }
16... Bf5 { Activating the bishop and clearing the way for ...Ne6. } 17. Nd4
{ This is natural, but the computer is not particularly fond of it. } 17... Bg6
18. Qg4 Ne6 19. Be3
{ 19.Nxe6?!  fxe6  would only help Black, who now has the half-open f-file plus the ability to play a quick ...c5 with now defended. }
19... Rad8 20. Nf5
{ This does eliminate Black's bishop pair, but at the cost of time.   20.Nxe6  is actually quite reasonable here.  20...fxe6  21.b4  With the bishop now on e3 rather than f4, White not only has better control over key squares such as c5, but the text is possible covered laterally by the queen. With Black unable to force forward his pawn mass, it's not so easy to claim such a large advantage. }
20... Bxf5 21. Qxf5 f6
{ Thematic. Black not only rids his opponent of his one trump the advanced e-pawn and opens the f-file, but he gains further time against the queen in the process. }
22. exf6 Bxf6 23. Qg4 Qf7
{ With well placed pieces, open lines and a queenside majority that could be put to good use in the future, Black stands much better. }
24. Ne2 h5 25. Qg3
{ 25.Qf5!  is better, e.g.  25...c5?!   25...a5  is a better move.  26.Nf4!   26.Rxd5??  Nd4-+  Nxf4  27.Bxf4  and the lateral pressure on Black's queenside pawns is somewhat annoying. }
25... c5
{ Black is much better here, with ... d4 coming. In an already difficult position, Navara blunders. }
26. Rxd5 Nd4 { Threatening both the rook on d5 and a fork on e2. } 27. R5xd4
cxd4 28. Nxd4 Rd5 { 28...Qa7!  wins more directly. } 29. Rd2 Be5 30. Qh4 Qg6
31. g3 Bf6 32. Qf4 Bxd4 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "½-½ Robert Booij (2362) vs. Hans Hofstetter (2387) W-ch40 prel07 email 2016"]
[Result "*"]

{ This correspondence game shows one of the weirder lines in the repertoire fizzling out into a fairly stable position for both sides. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. Be3 Be7 10. c3 Qd7 11. Nbd2 Nxd2 12. Qxd2 Na5 13. Nd4 c5 14. Nxe6 fxe6
15. Bc2 Nc4 16. Qe2 Nxb2 17. Bc1
{ This is one of a number of moves evaluated at 0.00 by Stockfish 15. The idea is to chase the knight back to c4, then push a2-a4. A logical idea, but the retrograde move shouldn't be too threatening, theoretically speaking.   17.Qh5+  Kd8  was covered in the theoretical section.   17.a4!?  Nxa4  18.c4!?  seems worth mentioning. Opening the d-file with . ..dxc4 should definitely be avoided here, especially considering we want to meet Qh5+ with ...g6.  18...O-O !?  Normally this would be extremely risky, but it seems to work out here.   18...g6  is the alternative, stopping Qh5+ altogether. For instance:  19.Rxa4!?  bxa4  20.Bh6  Bf8  21.Qd1  Kf7  22.Bxa4  Qb7  23.Qf3+  Kg8  24.Bg5  Be7  25.Bh6=  19.Qh5  Rf5=  Black has enough pawns in the bank that sacrificing an exchange to stop the attack is no problem at all. }
17... Nc4 18. a4 b4
{ This is not exactly forced, but keeping the a-file closed makes good sense. }
19. Qh5+ Kd8
{ The typical reaction to Qh5+ in these sharp lines. The king should eventually find relative safety on the queenside. }
20. Bd3 { Threatening Bxc4 followed by Rd1. } 20... Kc7
{ Hopping off the d-file and connecting the rooks. } 21. Bxc4 dxc4 22. Rd1 Qe8
{ 22...Qc6?  23.Bg5!  wins for White as he gains access to the d6-square, e.g.:  23...Bxg5  24.Rd6  Qb7  25.Qxg5  and Black's position is collapsing. }
23. Qg4
{ White will quickly win his pawn back. It seems as though he may be able to claim an edge as a result, due to Black's exposed king. In OTB practice, it's possible that the second player could face some difficulties, but in this game the pressure is swiftly neutralized. }
23... Rd8 24. Re1
{ Keeping pieces on the board.   24.Rxd8  Qxd8  25.Be3  Qd5  26.Qxg7  Re8  is fine for Black.  27.Qxh7  b3∞  with a messy position. }
24... Qc6 25. Qxc4 a5
{ The evaluation is probably already slightly in Black's favour. He has a passed b-pawn, control over the d-file, and the rook on a1 is a bit tied down to the defense of a4. Black's king is a bit airy, but there doesn't appear to be any good way for getting at it. }
26. Be3 Rb8 { 26...Rd5  is another good move. } 27. Rec1
{ White plans cxb4, trying to make use of the c-file. } 27... Rhd8
{ This indirectly defends against the threat to the c5-pawn, as we'll see in a moment. }
28. cxb4 axb4
{ White has also obtained a passed a-pawn, but it's a very long way away from queening. }
29. Rab1
{ In fact, White immediately removes his rook from its position behind the passed a-pawn, as the b4-pawn is much more menacing at the moment.   29.Bxc5??  Bxc5  30.Qxc5  Rd1+-+  is a standard tactic, winning for Black here. }
29... Qd5 { 29...Qxa4??  30.Bxc5  is quite a bad idea for Black. } 30. Qe2
{ In a game between two unassisted humans, one could easily imagine any result occurring. However, in a correspondence game, it proves very difficult for either side to do much. Black has connected passed pawns, but it's extremely difficult to get the c-pawn past the c4-square. Meanwhile, White can try to use this pawn as a target by tripling on the c-file as he indeed does in the game, but it's hard to capture it profitably if Black is careful. }
30... Rb7
{ This is a pretty mysterious move. I suspect most unassisted humans would play either   30...b3  or  30...Qxe5  although threse three moves and several others are all 0.00 according to the computer. }
31. h3 g6 32. Rc4 Kb8 33. Rbc1 Rc8 34. h4 Qd7 35. Qc2
{ 35.Bxc5  doesn't particularly help, e.g.  35...Rxc5  36.Rxc5  Bxc5  37.Rxc5  b3  38.Qb2  Qxa4 }
35... Ka8 36. Rb1
{ 36.Bxc5?  b3   36...Rbc7  37.Rd1   37.Qe4+  Qd5  Qc6  38.Bxb4  Qxc4  39.Qxc4  Rxc4  40.Bxe7  Rc1  41.Rxc1  Rxc1+  42.Kh2  Ra1  43.Kg3  Rxa4  I don't think Black is winning here, but I could be wrong.  37.Qb2  Qd5  38.Rd4  Qc6  39.Rd6  Bxd6  40.exd6  Qd5  41.Ba3  Rxc1+  42.Qxc1  Kb8∓ }
36... Qd8 37. g3 Bf8 38. Bg5 Qa5 39. Kh2 Qa6 40. Be3
{ Neither side could find much to play for and a draw was agreed. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "0-1 Vitolinsh, Alvis (2415) vs. Mikhalchishin, Adrian (2480) Uzhgorod 1988"]
[Result "*"]

{ I found this game in Glenn Flear's 2000 book Open Ruy Lopez. It is also annotated by Carsten Hansen in his Miniatures in the Main Line Ruy Lopez. Both authors skip over some critical moments in the game, although in Flear's case he was writing 22 years ago, whereas I have Stockfish 15 running in the background. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. Re1
{ Alvis Vitolinsh was famous for being a creative attacking player. Therefore, I'm not entirely sure what drew him to this line. He played it multiple times, and I don't think he was aiming for a draw. I suppose he just wanted to avoid the main lines. It's hardly a bad move, anyway. }
6... Nc5 7. Bxc6 dxc6 8. Nxe5 Be7 9. d4 Ne6 10. Be3 O-O 11. c4 f6
{ We saw  11...Bd6  in the previous game. } 12. Nf3 f5
{ If you ask the computer about this move, it won't give dead equality. However, it seems like a decent way to generate some play in a position that can be a bit dry. It is fairly committal though. Pawns don't move backwards! }
13. Nc3 f4 14. Bd2 Bf6 15. d5
{ 15.Ne4  is Stockfish's top choice, but I can't understand why White should be better after  15...Bxd4  16.Nxd4  Qxd4  17.Bb4  Qxd1  18.Raxd1  Rf5  Yes, White has control over the d-file and it's not easy for Black to complete development, but Black has an extra pawn. Play should fizzle out to a draw in some opposite coloured bishop endgame, as I don't know what exactly the first player can achieve while Black sorts out his queenside.   15.Ne2  is also possible, as  15...Nxd4?  is bad:  16.Nexd4  Bxd4  17.Nxd4  Qxd4  18.Bb4!  Qxd1  19.Raxd1  The rook on f8 is sort of trapped, as abandoning the 8th rank would be disastrous.  19...Bg4!?  20.f3  c5!  21.Bxc5  Rf5  22.fxg4  Rxc5  23.Re7+-  with Rdd7 next and Black is in big trouble. }
15... Nc5
{ 15...cxd5?!  16.Nxd5  Bxb2  is a dubious pawn grab which does not mesh well with ...f5-f4.  17.Rb1  Ba3  18.Qb3±  It was a bit surprising to me at first just how strong White's compensation is here. Despite being a pawn down, facing the bishop pair, and ostensibly having a worse pawn structure, Stockfish 15 gives the first player an edge firmly in the +/- range. The d-file pressure after Rbd1 is annoying, Bc3 puts the bishop on an extremely strong diagonal, and ...c6 is difficult to play without falling afoul of Nb6. Analyzing this position is a bit beyond the point of including this game, but it's worth looking at further if you're interested. }
16. Ne5
{ This is a mistake which gives Black a powerful initiative.   16.dxc6?!  bxc6  doesn't really help White. ...Nd3 is a threat and ...Bg4/...Bf5 is on the horizon. White should probably attempt to bail out with an intricate tactical sequence:  17.Bxf4!  Qxd1  18.Rexd1!  It's important that ...Bxc3 does not hit the rook, and also that ...Nd3 which would win in response to Nxd1 is prevented.  18...Bxc3  19.Be3!  Only move.  19...Bxb2  20.Bxc5  Bxa1  21.Bxf8  Bf6  22.Bc5  Be6⩱  Black is better, but remaining in the middlegame was even more hazardous for White.   16.Qc2  should keep things within the range of equality, but Black is for choice. }
16... Bxe5 17. Rxe5 Nd3 18. Re2
{ 18.Re4  Bf5  19.Rxf4  Nxf4  20.Bxf4  is a lesser evil, objectively speaking. }
18... Bf5
{ 18...f3!  is best, but Black needs to have the right follow-up ready.  19.Re3   19.gxf3  Qh4-+  is fantastic for Black.   19.Re4  Bf5-+   19.Re1  Nxf2  20.Kxf2!  Qh4+  21.Kg1  f2+-+  Nxf2!  20.Kxf2  Qh4+  21.Kg1  f2+  22.Kh1   22.Kf1  Qxh2-+  Qd4-+  Queening immediately is also very good for Black. The text is a patient and extremely clever move. The threat is stronger than the execution. Now Black is now threatening to take on d2 due to back rank issues, but not ...f1=Q+, Qxf1, ...Rxf1+, Rxf1, ...Qxd2, as Re8# would be mate! ...Bg4 is also a pressing concern. This isn't really very relevant to the topic, but it's a bit interesting.   18...Nxb2?  19.Qb3  Nd3?!  20.Ne4  and White begins to take over. }
19. Be1
{ This covers both b2  against ...Nxb2 and f2 against ...f3, Re3, ...Nxf2. }
19... Qf6
{ 19...Re8  20.f3  Qd6∓  is the computer's recommendation.   19...f3  20.Re3  is somewhat less strong for Black now that there's no ...Nxf2. Nevertheless, he's better after:  20...Nxb2  21.Qb3  Nd3  22.Rxf3  Qf6∓ }
20. Qd2
{ 20.dxc6  bxc6   20...Qxc6  21.Nd5  Qxc4  22.Ne7+  Kh8  23.Nxf5  Rxf5  24.Re7  is okay for White.  21.Ne4  pretty much neutralizes Black's pressure.  21...Qd4  22.Bc3  Qxc4  23.Nd2  Qf7  24.Nf3  and White more or less consolidates. }
20... f3 21. Re3
{ There's no ...Nxf2 this time, but with ...Bf5 and ...Qf6 now in, the knight can safely drop back to e5, with a lethal attack.   21.gxf3??  Qg6+  22.Kh1  Bh3  with mate upcoming. }
21... Ne5 22. Qd4 Rae8 23. g3 Bc8 { Intending ...Qf5-h3. } 24. Bd2 Qf5 25. Qh4
Ng6 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "½-½ James Henri (2373) vs. Brian Anderson (2434) ICCF email 2016"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. Re1 Nc5 7. Bxc6 dxc6 8.
Nxe5 Be7 9. d4 Ne6 10. Be3 O-O 11. c4
{ This is a more active approach than the setup with the pawn on c3      from the previous game. }
11... Bd6
{ After running a computer for quite some time, it came to the      conclusion that this move is best. It puts the bishop on potentially      quite a nice diagonal and threatens ...c5.   11...f6  12.Nf3  Ng5!?  is an unusual-looking but sound alternative      approach. Black wants to swap off a pair of knights to clear some      space for his c8-bishop, while the half-open f-file could potentially      do him some good too.   11...Re8  12.Nc3  Nf8  is another decent option, with the idea to      develop the Queen's Bishop and bring the knight to g6. }
12. f4
{ This is logical - White gains space and supports his central knight,      thus dissuading ...c6-c5.   12.Nc3  c5!  sees Black execute his ideal break, and should be on      the sunnier side of equality after his pawns are undoubled.   12.Nf3  serves the function of dissuading ...c5, but seems fairly      compliant.  12...Re8  Black should have comfortable equality here.   12.c5  is an extreme reaction which sets off a tactical sequence.  12...Nxc5  Once again attempting to deflect the d4-pawn.  13.Nxf7  White responds with a desperado to avoid losing a pawn.  13...Rxf7  14.dxc5  Be7  15.Nc3  Qxd1  16.Raxd1  Bf5  White can argue that he's benefited     from this skirmish, as he now has a pawn majority on the kingside.      However, the strength of Black's bishops should make it hard for the      first player to do much of anything in this position. }
12... Qh4
{ Black responds actively; it's a bit awkward to defend the f4-pawn.      Also, the very useful d8-square is now clear for the rook. This move      has yet to be played in over the board games albeit only two that I      could find even reached this position, but has been tested twice in      correspondence chess.   12...Re8  is hardly bad either. }
13. g3
{ This is the best move; covering the f-pawn with a gain of tempo.      However, the weakening of the kingside is not to be disregarded.   13.Nf3  The queen doesn't have to retreat, and instead can go to a      surprisingly annoying square.  13...Qg4  and if  14.h3  then  14...Qg3  and White has serious trouble covering the f-pawn.   13.Qd2  Rd8  is active and pleasant for Black.   13.f5  Nd8  leaves White's f-pawn overextended, e.g.  14.g4  h5  and      now White should bail out for a draw with  15.Bf2  Qg5  16.Be3  Qh4 }
13... Qh3 14. Nd3
{ This is certainly not the first move that comes to mind, but it is      best. Naturally, this being a correspondence game, White does indeed      find the best option.   14.Nc3  is natural, but allows Black to execute a surprising but      strong tactical idea.  14...c5  This is thematic, but isn't normally      so good when d4-d5 is a possible reply.  15.d5  Ng5!  Black exploits      the weakened kingside; if the knight isn't taken, then ...f6 and      ...Bg4 if the e5-knight retreats is likely to follow.  16.fxg5  Bxe5  Objectively the computer gives this position as equal albeit ever so      slightly in Black's favour, but practically speaking it looks much      more pleasant to play for the second player. }
14... Rd8
{ Obviously I can't really criticize move choices too much in a modern      correspondence game, and this move is completely fine. Nonetheless,      for a practical over the board game, I would recommend being a little      more ambitious.   14...h5  This is quite ambitious, but also quite logical; ...h4 is      quite a serious attacking idea. It's clear that the second player      already has the initiative here. Black ends up playing this in just a      few moves in the game. }
15. Nf2 Qf5 16. Nc3 h5
{ Now Black opts for a kingside push. However, I think it, at least for     the time being, may be purely prophylactic against g3-g4. }
17. Qf3 Bb4
{ This is a slightly odd-looking move, but it does clear the d-file,      attacking the d4-pawn. Black also demonstrates that he isn't opposed      to given up this bishop for a knight, which makes some sense as it was     a bit restricted on d6. Not only that, but something like ...Bxc3,      ...Nf8, ...Qg6, ...Bf5 is definitely forseeable, when Black has      wonderful light square control.   17...Bd7  is possible, as is   17...b5 }
18. Rad1
{ 18.a3  Bxc3  19.bxc3  Bd7  This is quite an unusual position, but Black     seems slightly better.   18.h3  Black would be in some trouble here if not for:  18...Ng5 }
18... Bd7
{ The bishop doesn't look so fantastic on d7, but it currently isn't      able to get to a better square so easily.   18...Nf8  seems possible, perhaps intending ...Qg6 and ...Bf5.  19.h3  White can try to exploit the retrograde knight move by      forcing through g3-g4 ...Ng5 is no longer on the table. A      complicated game is ahead. }
19. d5
{ White decides to start concrete action.   19.h3  Ng5!   19.Kg2  Bxc3  20.bxc3  Nf8  21.h3  Qg6  and Black should be a bit better. }
19... Bxc3 20. bxc3 Nf8 21. Bd4 Re8 22. Re5 Rxe5 23. Bxe5 Rc8 24. Bd4 Re8
{ Black should definitely have an advantage here, but I suppose White      was confident he wouldn't lose this position. }
25. Qd3 f6
{ 25...Qxd3  26.Nxd3  Re2  seems more human, but  27.Re1  Rxa2  28.Re7  gives White counterplay. }
26. Qxf5 Bxf5 27. dxc6 bxc6
{ The structure is not exactly symmetrical, but similar on both sides.      However, an issue for White is that ...Re2 is coming up next.      Additionally, c4 and a2 are possible targets for Black's bishop. }
28. Nd3 { 28.Kf1  Be6 } 28... Re2 29. Nb4 Be4
{ Black intends ...Rg2+. The plan is to force the king to f1, so he can     pick up both a2 and h2.   29...a5  According to computers, this gives Black better winning      chances.  30.Nxc6  Bg4  31.Rb1  h4  32.Nxa5  Rxa2  33.Nc6  Bf3  34.Ne7+  Kf7  35.Re1  h3  36.Bf2  Ne6  37.Nd5  Be2  38.c5  Bf3  39.Nb4  Rb2  Despite the      extra pawn, White is quite badly tied up. }
30. Nxa6 Rg2+ 31. Kf1 Rxa2 32. Nxc7 Rxh2 33. Bf2 Rh1+ 34. Bg1 h4 35. gxh4 Ng6
36. Ne6 Nxh4 37. Rd7 Nf5 38. Rc7 Rh3 39. Bd4 Bd3+ 40. Kg2 Rg3+ 41. Kf2 Bxc4 42.
Nxg7 Rxg7
{ A draw was agreed here as White will take on c6 and then take on f6,      when I can't see how Black should really be able to win. The problem      is that Black is going to lose both of his pawns, at which point, even     if White's two pawns disappeared, it isn't a theoretical win within      fifty moves. In an OTB game, you continue as Black, why not? In      correspondence, however you agree a draw. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "0-1 Alina Bivol (2392) vs. Alisa Galliamova (2421) Ufa 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. Re1 Nc5 7. Bxc6 dxc6 8.
Nxe5 Be7 9. d4 Ne6
{ This is where we left off in the theoretical section. Black is      totally fine here, as the bishop pair compensates for White's space      advantage and slightly better structure. Again, note that, unlike in      the Exchange Spanish, White has no pawn majority. }
10. c3
{ 10.Be3  This is another way to cover the d4-pawn, and it's probably      slightly stronger. }
10... O-O 11. Be3
{ 11.Nd2  is played sometimes, but Black is already better after  11...c5  The problem for White is that the knight on d2 blocks the      queen's support of d4-d5, meaning that Black successfully undoubles      their pawns. }
11... f6
{ Kicking the knight back is a decent idea. The squares weakened by      this move are not currently significant and the e7-bishop was unlikely     to use f6.   11...Bf6  12.f4  If White gets to stabilize his knight in the      centre like this, he's probably playing for an advantage.   11...Re8  This somehow feels wrong, but if quickly followed up by      ...f6, there's absolutely no reason Black can't play this.   11...c5  12.d5  favours White. }
12. Nd3
{ This decision makes sense, as on f3, the knight is a bit restricted      by the f6-pawn. }
12... Re8
{ This is a solid and flexible move. Black places her rook on an open      albeit currently obstructed file, while clearing the f8-square for      potential use by other pieces. The ...f5 plan is no longer really      available, but that wasn't very promising in this case anyway. Note      that White has hardly done anything terribly wrong, but already even      though the position is pretty much equal Black is ever so slightly      for choice here. LeelaChess Zero, for example, gives Black a winning      percentage of just above 51%. That's not very dramatic, obviously, but     it's quite a step up from the second player compared to the initial      position.   12...Rf7  This has also been played by some strong players, but it      definitely feels less natural to me.   12...a5  Black plays this on the next turn in the game, but it's      very possible here as well. }
13. Nd2 a5
{ This is the sort of move that strong players play in positions where      nothing direct is happening. Black gains space on the queenside.      There's no need to rush into any concrete action, nor is there even a      particular need to develop the c8-bishop immediately although,      naturally, that's possible.   13...Nf8  and   13...Bf8  are also sensible. Both moves step out of the way of other     pieces.  14.Ne4  b6  15.Qc2  a5  16.Rad1  Ba6  These moves for both sides      are somewhat arbitrary, but I just wanted to show this possible method     of developing the Queen's Bishop. }
14. Qf3
{ This brings the queen to an active square, clears d1 for a rook      although Rad1 isn't immediately a great idea; see the next move and      stops ...b7-b6. However, it does give Black possibilities of ...Qd5,      offering a favourable queen trade. }
14... a4
{ Black further expands on the queenside. ...a4-a3 doesn't necessarily      have to be played on the next move, but it is a nice idea to have on      the table, undermining the b2-d4 pawn chain. If White plays a2-a3      herself, the b3-square and b2-pawn become potentially quite weak.   14...Qd5  is a very decent move, although keeping this in reserve      turned out well in the game.  15.Ne4  is a decent possibility here,      which ends up not being available later on.   14...Bf8  is also sensible, although why not continue pushing the      a-pawn? }
15. Rad1
{ This natural move allows Black to profitably swap the queens.   15.h3  This is a neutral move, not necessarily best, but the point      is to illustrate why 15.Rad1 is not a good move.  15...Qd5  16.Ne4  White can avoid the queen trade without a passive retreat. }
15... Qd5
{ The problem now is that, with a2 hanging, it is awkward to avoid      swapping queens. }
16. c4
{ 16.Ne4  Qxa2   16.Qxd5  cxd5  This is clearly not a desirable transaction for      White. Black undoubles his pawns, and has the bishop pair and a space      advantage.   16.Qg3  is considered best by the computer. It sets a trap, as the     a2-pawn cannot actually be captured here. Nonetheless, g3 is far from      a perfect square for the queen.  16...b6  I mentioned this method of      developing the c8-bishop earlier. Note that ...Qd5, taking control      over the long diagonal, facilitated this move.   16...Qxa2  17.c4  The queen cannot escape a2.  17.c4  Qf5  18.Nf1  Ba6  19.b3  Rad8  Black is fully developed, and has a      good position. }
16... Qxf3 17. Nxf3
{ This endgame is quite favourable for Black. She has plenty of time to     arrange her pieces actively and begin to exploit the two bishops. }
17... Nf8
{ This clears the way for the c8-bishop to develop. It's pretty easy to     imagine the knight quickly rejoining the action once this has      happened.It also steps away from the d4-d5 push, which enables the      first player to get some activity, and perhaps exchange off one of      Black's bishops.   17...Rd8  is also possible, simply activating the rook, while      limiting White's active options neither d5 nor Bf4 are possible.   17...Bd7  Developing the last minor piece makes sense in      principle, but d7 doesn't really seem like a good destination. This      piece should ideally end up on e6, f5 or g4, if not a6.  18.d5  cxd5  19.cxd5  Nf8  20.Bc5  Black is still slightly better here, but White is      coming closer to equalizing by exchanging one of the bishops.   17...b6  This is logical, but also allows White some play.  18.d5  cxd5  19.cxd5  Nf8  Bc5 has been prevented, but there is another      annoying bishop move.  20.Bf4  The c7-pawn is awkward to defend, so      Black should counterattack.  20...Bb7  21.Bxc7  Bxd5  22.Bxb6  Bxa2  23.Bc5!  Once again, exchanging bishops is a key idea when playing against      the bishop pair.  23...Bxc5  24.Nxc5  Black's bishop ensures an edge,      but I imagine it's going to be pretty hard to win this position. }
18. Bf4
{ The threat to the c7-pawn would feasibly be awkward if not for a      strong counter-threat.   18.d5  This is not as annoying when it does not come with tempo,      but nonetheless it may be White's best try. It's a bit      counterintuitive that undoubling Black's c-pawns and opening the      position for the bishops is a good idea, but at the same time White's      pieces are currently more active.  18...cxd5  19.cxd5  Rd8  The d-pawn      is difficult to defend, and a definite weakness should White proceed      'normally'.  20.Rc1  Rxd5  21.Rxc7  Bd6  22.Nf4   22.Rc3  is 'automatic' but too passive.  22...Bg4  Black is much         better.  Rf5  On principle it seems nice to keep the bishop pair.  23.Rc4  Rb5  24.Re2  Bd7  Black is better due to the strong bishops. }
18... Be6
{ Swapping c7 for c4 would very much not be a good deal for white, who      would be left with an isolated d-pawn. }
19. Rc1
{ 19.b3  Ugly as it looks, this might be best.  19...b5  Now, White      has to be very careful to keep his position together.  20.d5   20.cxb5  axb3  21.axb3  Bxb3  22.Rc1   22.Rb1  Bc2  cxb5  23.Rxc7  Ne6  24.Rd7  Rad8  25.Rb7  Bc4  Black is much          better.  bxc4  21.dxe6  cxd3  22.Rxd3  Bb4  23.Bd2  Bxd2  24.Rxd2  axb3  25.axb3  Nxe6  Black's extra pawn is doubled, but the plan is to advance the      frontmost c-pawn, swapping it for White's b-pawn when possible. }
19... Bf5
{ Black makes another threat, and next can redevelop the knight to e6.      Everything is flowing very nicely here. }
20. Red1 Ne6
{ Note that this comes with tempo as well, meaning that there is no      time for d4-d5. }
21. Be3 Rad8
{ Black's position is very aesthetically pleasing. Not only that, she      has the bishop pair, active pieces and pressure against d4. The latter     can be amplified by ...Be4 or ...Bg4, as well as doubling on the      d-file. ...g7-g5, gaining kingside space and restricting White's minor     pieces, is also a good idea. }
22. Nf4 g5 23. Nxe6 Bxe6 24. h3 b6
{ The subtle weakening of the c6-square gives White an opportunity to      execute their central break. It doesn't really come close to      equalizing, but it does at least change the nature of the play, which      currently is distinctly in Black's favour.   24...Bf7  is a subtle move recommended by the computer, stepping      out of the way of the d5 push and potentially preparing to swing over      to g6 or h5. }
25. Nd2
{ 25.d5  cxd5  26.Nd4  Bd7   26...Bf7  shows the point of White's idea.  27.Nc6  Rd7  28.Nxe7+  Rexe7  29.c5  Black remains a pawn up, but she would be          hard-pressed to win this position with bishops of opposite          colours.  27.cxd5  Bd6  Black is better, but maybe not as much better as      previously, when White had pretty much no counterplay. }
25... f5
{ With the g-pawn no longer requiring defense from the f-pawn, Black      takes the opportunity to continue advancing her kingside pawns. The      computer isn't such a huge fan of playing this move immediately, but      from a human perspective, it looks perfectly sensible to me. Firstly,      White has to meet the threat of ...f4, trapping the bishop.   25...h6  is a computer suggestion, overprotecting the g5-pawn, so      that after ...f5, the knight returning to f3 does not create a threat.   25...h5  is also very possible. }
26. f4
{ 26.Nf3  This 'retracting' move is difficult to play, but it's best.     White gains a tempo against g5 and the knight is heading for the      e5-square. }
26... gxf4 { Black now gets to cash in with a nicely calculated sequence. } 27.
Bxf4 { 27.Bf2  is relatively best, but Black is winning. } 27... Rxd4 28. Bxc7
Bb4
{ This is far from the only winning move, but it looks the clearest to      me. }
29. Nf3 Rxd1+ 30. Rxd1 Bc5+ { The check ensures that the b6-pawn is covered. }
31. Kh1 Bxc4 32. Ne5 Bxa2 33. Nd7 Re7
{ White can take on c5 and create a bishops of opposite colour      situation, but it'll be very hard to defend b2 and g2 once Black puts      a bishop on d5 and rook on e2.   33...Bb3  34.Rd3  Re1+  35.Kh2  Bg1+  36.Kg3  b5  This is probably the      cleanest, keeping both bishops and the two extra pawns. }
34. Bf4
{ 34.Bxb6  Rxd7!  35.Rxd7  Bxb6   34.Nxc5  bxc5  35.Bd6  Re2  36.Bxc5  Bd5 }
34... Bf2 35. Rd6 Re6 36. Rd3 b5 37. Be5 Bh4 38. Rd4 Be7 39. g4 Bd5+ 40. Kh2
Rxe5
{ A nice little tactic to end the game.   41.Nxe5  Bd6  will leave Black with two extremely powerful bishops alongside the queenside majority against White's overburdened rook. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "0-1 Rainer Polzin (2491) vs. Zahar Efimenko (2654) Bundesliga 2009"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game features the system with Qe2. I'm not going to devote multiple fully annotated games to it, but I will add some game fragments to the notes. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O
{ 5.Qe2  Be7  6.O-O  b5  is how we reach the game in our repertoire. } 5... Be7
{ Naturally, if you want to follow the course, you should play   5...Nxe4 } 6.
Qe2
{ 6.Re1  We're going to take a quick detour to look at a game I FD played with Black that reached a position similar to ones that occur in the Qe2 variation.  6...b5  7.Bb3  O-O  8.h3  Played as a means of avoiding the Marshall Attack proper.  8...Bb7  9.c3  9.d3 is stronger.  9...d5  10.d3  Qd7!?  Swapping on e4 is best, but I wanted to keep queens on.  11.Qe2  h6  12.Nbd2  Rfe8  This is very similar to a position reached in the game.  13.Nf1?!  The typical knight circuit isn't direct enough here.   13.a4  puts a bit of pressure on Black, although it should still be about equal.  13...Bf8  14.Ng3  Na5  15.Bc2  c5⩱  Black is comfortable here, with ...c5-c4 a likely break. Of course, there's going to be some attacking chances for White once a knight lands on f5, but the well-placed bishop on f8 provides sufficient resources to defend. I eventually won this game. }
6... b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. c3 d5 9. d3
{ 9.exd5  Nxd5  10.Nxe5  is not particularly advisable for White.  10...Nf4!?  is what I played here once.   10...Nxe5!  11.Qxe5  Nf6  is the recommendation in the theoretical section.  11.Qe4  Nxe5  12.Qxf4  and here I played 12....Bd6, putting a bit too much faith in threats along the b8-h2 diagonal. The game was soon drawn.   12.Qxa8??  Qd3  13.Bd1  Bh3  14.Qxa6  Bxg2  15.Re1  Qf3  and White resigned in Roesch-Schlage, Hamburg 1910. The last few moves of this game were featured in the film 2001: A Space Odyssey in a scene where Frank plays a game of chess against HAL. Anyway, it's a pretty nice miniature, and taking on a8 is very bad.  12...Nd3!  is simple and strong.  13.Qf3  Ra7  14.Bc2  Nxc1  15.Rxc1  c5⩱  with fantastic compensation, thanks to the bishop pair and pieces set to occupy open lines. Meanwhile, White's queenside is still sleeping. }
9... Bb7
{ We recommend  9...Be6  in the theoretical section, but the alternative bishop development can hardly be bad.  A game that sticks in my memory is the following:   9...Re8  10.Nbd2  Bf8  11.a3?!  h6  12.Ba2  Be6  13.Rd1  Qd7  14.exd5?!  Nxd5  15.Ne4  Nf4   15...f5  is also very logical.  16.Bxf4  exf4   16...Bxa2  leads to a tactical skirmish:  17.Bxh6!  Bb3  18.Rdc1  f5  19.Ned2  Bd5  20.Bg5  e4  etc.  17.Bxe6   17.b4  Rxe6  18.Qc2  Rae8  19.b4  Ne5  20.Nxe5  Rxe5  21.Nd2?  Re2  22.Qb1  Qc6  23.Qc1  Qb6  24.d4  g5!  and White was soon getting crushed in Polgar-Adams, Las Palmas 1994. }
10. Nbd2 Re8 11. Re1 Qd7
{ While ...Re8/../Qd7/...Rad8 looks like a logical set-up, it may be beneficial not to play the latter two moves so quickly. In particular, removing the rook from a8 may increase the strength of a2-a4.   11...Bf8  first may arguably be more accurate. }
12. exd5
{ 12.Nf1  h6  13.Ng3  Rad8   13...Bf8  is a bit more accurate.  14.Nf5?!   14.a4  Bf8  15.Bc2  Na5   15...Qe6  16.h3  Nb8!?  17.Nh2  Nbd7  is a reorganization that the computer likes.  16.N3h4  dxe4   16...c5  is natural and good.  17.dxe4  Nc4  18.Qf3?!  Qc6  19.Qg3  Kh7  20.b3?  Nd2!  21.Qe3  Bc5?!   21...Ndxe4!  22.Ng3  g6  and White can't win a piece on e4 due to back rank mate at the end of the line!  22.Qg3??  g6  and 0-1 in Camilleri-Read, correspondence 1994. Pre-computer correspondence! }
12... Nxd5 13. Ne4 h6
{ 13...f5?  14.c4±  is the way to exploit the a2-g8 diagonal.  14...bxc4  15.dxc4  fxe4??  16.cxd5  exf3??  17.dxc6+  Kh8  18.cxd7  fxe2  19.dxe8=Q+   13...f6  is one good option. It looks frightening to open the a2-g8 diagonal, but this isn't too much of a concern in reality.  14.a3!?  prepares to drop back to a2, but for us simply moving away from the diagonal is good enough.   14.Bd2  Na5  chases the bishop away.  15.Bc2  c5=  14...Kh8=   13...Bf8  14.a3  f5=  The point is that  15.c4?  bxc4  16.dxc4?  Nd4-+  wins because the e-file is now clear.   16...fxe4  17.cxd5  Na5  also works, but not as effectively. }
14. Bd2 { 14.a4⩲  is more challenging. } 14... Rad8 15. Rad1
{ 15.a4⩲  is most annoying, especially now that the rook has left a8. } 15...
Qg4
{ This is a nice maneuver, swinging the queen over to the kingside.   15...Qe6  also serves a similar purpose. }
16. h3
{ 16.Qf1  is a slightly better move, ducking off the e-file, avoiding ...Nf4 and not creating a kingside weakness. It's obviously quite passive-looking, but according to Stockfish 15 at least, White maintains a tiny advantage even here. Practically speaking Black's positions seems easier to play, though. }
16... Qg6 17. a3
{ 17.Ng3  is the computer's suggestion. The threat to the e5-pawn preempts a quick ...f7-f5.  17...Nf4   17...Bf8  18.Nh4  Qf6  19.Qg4  and it's no longer clear who has a kingside initiative.  18.Bxf4  exf4  19.Ne4  Bg5= }
17... Kh8
{ 17...f5  can also be played right away.  18.c4!  is an important resource, which we've seen before. }
18. Qf1
{ This is too passive and now Black begins to take over the game.   18.Ng3  should again be played. }
18... f5 19. Ng3 Bf6 20. h4
{ This creates a weakness without sufficient benefit to compensate for it.  Playing solidly with   20.Bc2  is better, although clearly White is worse here. }
20... f4 21. Ne4 Bc8 { Rerouting to g4 is quite a good idea here. } 22. Bc2
{ 22.Rc1  avoiding the ...Bg4 pin is better. } 22... Bg4 23. Qe2 Nde7
{ Swinging the knight around to f5 is very logical, and it would be a perfectly good move if not for a countershot.   23...Qh5-+  picks up the h4-pawn. }
24. d4 exd4 25. Bxf4 Nf5 26. Bxc7 Rc8 27. Bb6
{ 27.Qd3!!  is not easy to find, but necessary.  27...Rxc7  28.h5  Bxh5   28...Qxh5  29.Ng3!  points out that the f5-knight is now pinned to mate on h7.  29...Rxe1+  30.Rxe1  Qg6  31.Nxf5  Bxf5  32.Qxf5  Qxf5  33.Re8+!  Kh7  34.Bxf5+  g6  35.Re6=   28...Qf7  29.Nd6  Rxe1+  30.Rxe1  Qxh5  31.Nxf5=   28...Qh7??  29.Nxf6  Rxe1+  30.Rxe1  gxf6  31.Re8+  Kg7  32.Qe4+-  29.Nxf6  Rxe1+  30.Rxe1  gxf6  31.Qxf5  Qxf5  32.Bxf5  Bxf3  33.Re8+  Kg7  34.gxf3  and White is only a little worse. }
27... dxc3
{ 27...Ne5!  is even stronger.  28.Nxe5  Bxe5  29.f3  Qxb6  wins a piece due to the threat of ...d3+. }
28. Qd3 Ne5 29. Nxe5 Bxe5 30. f3 Qxb6+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "0-1 Akopian, Vladimir (2712) vs. Ivanchuk, Vassily (2703) Jarmula 2009"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 d6 6. c3 g6 7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1
O-O 9. Nbd2 Re8 10. Nf1 h6
{ 10...b5  11.Bc2  a5  This is Stockfish 15's recommendation on a very high depth, but not the only move. }
11. Ng3 b5
{ 11...d5  is an alternative. A big idea is to delay ...b5 to avoid an annoying a2-a4. }
12. Bc2 d5
{ 12...a5  is a move that Stockfish 15 likes in this and similar positions. The idea is to prepare to meet a2-a4 with ..b5-b4.  13.a4  b4= }
13. Qe2
{ This is a typical move in these types of positions, ensuring the queens stay on. Here, however, with ...g6 and ...Bg7 having been played, White has far fewer chances for a kingside attack than in, for example, an analogous position in the Italian Game.   13.a4  with some slight queenside pressure.  13...dxe4  14.Nxe4  Nxe4  15.dxe4  Qxd1  16.Rxd1⩲  is by no means an easy solution for Black. }
13... Be6 14. h3 Nd7
{ Black preapres ... Nc5/Nb6 while clearing the way for an eventual ...f5.   14...a5!  is the computer's suggestion, gaining queenside space.  15.Bd2  a4⩱ }
15. Be3
{ This isn't too bad, but it's not a fantastic idea to provoke ...d4 with tempo. Black could have considered it even without the bishop on e3.   15.Bd2  is better. and Black can choose between any number of logical and sound options. }
15... d4 16. Bd2 Nc5 17. Rec1 Qd6 18. cxd4 Nxd4 19. Nxd4 Qxd4 20. Bc3
{ This isn't awful at all, but there was a better way to inconvenience the opponent.   20.Be3  Qd6  21.Qd2  h5   21...Kh7  22.Qc3  Nb7  23.Bb3  swaps off the bad bishop.  22.Bh6=  and suddenly White is creating some annoyances on the kingside. }
20... Qd6 { Black is better, due to the weak d4-square and backwards d3-pawn. }
21. Bb4 Qb6 22. Qe3
{ 22.Bxc5  Qxc5  23.Bb3  is an option that makes sense to me; White simply wants to get rid of his bad light squared bishop.  23...Qd6  24.Bxe6  Rxe6=   22.Bd2  is another computer suggestion, but it's hard to imagine a human playing this considering the previous two moves.   22.Nf1  is another move that's probably not particularly easy for a human to make. It does, however, illustrate that the typical Nbd2-f1-g3 Ruy Lopez plan can sometimes be ineffective against ...g6 and ...Bg7. }
22... Bf8 23. Bc3 Rad8 24. Qf3 Bg7
{ 24...Nd7!  is a strong idea suggested by the computer. Spotting the weakness of d4, Black intends to transfer the knight via b8 to c6. }
25. b4 Na4 26. Bd2 Rd7 27. a3 Red8 28. Be3 Qb7 29. Rab1 Ba2 30. Ra1 Be6 31.
Rab1 Nc3 32. Ra1 f5 33. exf5
{ 33.Bb3!  Bxb3  34.Rxc3  Rxd3  35.Rxd3  Rxd3  36.Qe2  fxe4   36...Bc4  37.exf5  Rxa3  38.Qe1  Rxa1  39.Qxa1  is another possibility.  37.Qg4  Qc6  38.Nxe4  is unclear. }
33... Qxf3 34. gxf3
{ 34.fxe6!?  Qd5  35.exd7  Rxd7  is good for Black as well, but more complicated. }
34... gxf5 35. Bb3 { 35.Bd2  is better. } 35... Bxb3
{ 35...Ne2+!  is more accurate. The point is that after  36.Nxe2  Bxb3  the knight has been deflected from g3 and therefore f5 is not hanging.  37.Rc3  Rxd3  Black has picked up a pawn in addition to his already fantastic position. }
36. Rxc3 Be6
{ Black has the two bishops, threatens ...f4 and can now begin picking up pawns.   36...Rxd3??  37.Rxd3  Rxd3  38.Nxf5= }
37. Ba7 Rxd3 38. Rxc7 Rxf3 39. Re7 Bf7 40. Rc1 Bf6 41. Rec7 Bg5 42. Re1 e4 43.
Rc5 Rd7 44. Bb6 Be6 45. Rc8+ Kf7 46. Bc5 Rxa3 47. Rf8+ Kg6 48. Re8 Kf7 49. Rf8+
Kg6 50. Re8 Bc4 51. Rb8 e3 52. h4 exf2+ 53. Bxf2 Bxh4 54. Rb6+ Kg5 55. Be3+ f4
56. Ne4+ Kf5 57. Bf2 Rg7+ 58. Kh2 Bxf2 59. Nxf2 Ra2 60. Kh1 Bd5+ 61. Ne4 Rc7
62. Rf6+ Ke5 *

