[Black "½-½ Matthias Gleichmann (2547) vs. Horst Sikorsky (2536) email 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ 3...a6  4.Ba4  Nf6  5.d3  d6  6.c3  g6  7.O-O  Bg7  8.Re1  O-O  9.h3  would be one move order by which we could reach the position after White's ninth move in our repertoire. }
4. d3 d6 5. c3
{ 5.O-O  is more accurate. The point is that White benefits from the exclusion of ...a6/Ba4, because he can 'punish' an early ...g7-g6 with d3-d4. In 'our' version, delaying c2-c3 can be met with ...b5, Bb3 and ...Na5, wining the bishop pair.  5...a6   5...g6  6.d4⩲  6.Bxc6+   6.Ba4?!  b5  7.Bb3  Na5  bxc6  7.d4  and White is fighting for an edge. }
5... g6 6. O-O Bg7 7. Re1 O-O 8. h3 a6 9. Ba4 h6
{ This nice waiting move is our recommendation in the theoretical section. I FD reached this position from the Black side in 2016. I made four not particularly good moves in a row, and found myself in quite a bad position.   9...b5  This isn't horrible, but it's worth waiting to do this.  10.Bc2  Bb7  This is a natural enough developing move, but it's a bit vague, especially with the e4-pawn securely defended by its colleague on d3. I don't feel too bad about this decision though, considering it's actually the most common move here, and some very strong players have played it.  11.Nbd2   11.a4  is more annoying. A premature ...b7-b5 allows White to put pressure against this pawn.  d5  Breaking in the centre is a big part of Black's plans, but it's poorly timed here. The general rule is to do this only after White has committed to Nf1.  12.Nb3  This isn't the only move, and it might not even be the best move, but it does illustrate the problem with ...d5. The c5-square is now quite weak, and this problem is exacerbated by having a bishop on b7.  12...dxe4?!  13.dxe4  Qe7  14.Be3  Nd7  15.a4±  and I went on to lose.   9...Re8  is playable, but  10.Be3!  actually turns out to be slightly annoying. We'd like to be able to meet this with the ...f5 plan showcased in the game. }
10. Be3
{ 10.a3  is the computer's suggestion and was also recommended by Nils Grandelius on Chessable. We discuss this in the theoretical section, as well as the alternatives. }
10... Kh8
{ My experience is that normally it's worth resisting the temptation to go for a quick ...f5 in these lines. However, the presence of a bishop on e3 invites it.   10...Nd7!  immediately is probably the most accurate.  11.d4  Black should not be allowed a free hand on the kingside.   11.b4  f5  12.Bb3+  Kh7  13.exf5  gxf5  14.Na3  Ne7  and Black went on to win in Jovnik-Johansen, correspondence 2019.  15.Nc2  Ng6  16.a4  c6  17.a5  d5  18.Nh2  f4  19.Bd2  Nf6  20.Nf3  Re8  21.Bc1  Bf5  22.c4  Qd7  23.d4  This break arrives far too late.  23...e4  24.Ne5  Rxe5!  Not the only winning move, but it is effective.  25.dxe5  Bxh3  26.Nd4   26.gxh3  Qxh3  is not survivable for White.  Bxg2  27.e6  Qd6  28.cxd5  f3  29.dxc6  Qc7  30.Nf5  Ng4  0-1   11.Bb3  Kh8  12.d4  f5  13.exf5  gxf5  14.g3  f4  15.gxf4  exf4  16.Bc1  Nb6  17.Kh2  Qf6  with an eventual draw in Mityavin-Goreczny, correspondence 2019, although Black's position is clearly more pleasant.  11...f5!  12.exf5  gxf5   12...e4?  13.Bb3+  Kh8  14.Ng5!!  hxg5  15.fxg6  threatening mate in two with Qh5+.  15...Bh6  16.h4  and Black is in trouble.  13.dxe5  dxe5  14.Qd5+  Trying to prove that Black should have thrown in ...Kh8 at some point.   14.Bc2  Qe7=  14...Kh8  The following sequence is pretty much forced:  15.Bxc6  bxc6  16.Qxc6  Rb8  17.Bxh6  Rb6  18.Bxg7+  Kxg7  19.Qc4  e4  and now White should allow the f3-knight to be taken, as moving it gives Black a devastating attack after moves such as ...Ne5 and ...Rg6.  20.Nbd2  exf3  21.Nxf3  Bb7=  Three pawns for the piece, mutually unsafe kings. 0.00, naturally. }
11. Nbd2 Nd7 12. Nf1
{ 12.d4!  In general, White should react to these ...f5 plans with a break in the centre.  12...f5  13.exf5  gxf5  14.dxe5  dxe5  15.Bxc6  bxc6  is complicated, with mutual chances. However, I suspect that the inclusion of Nbd2 and ...Kh8 may turn out to favour White, as he can play:  16.Nc4⩲ }
12... f5 13. exf5 gxf5
{ White is now too late to directly challenge the centre, so Black should be fairly comfortable here. }
14. Bc1
{ This is very much a 'correspondence move'. White undevelops his bishop, but in doing so steps out of the way of ...f5-f4, and also clears the e-file. }
14... Nb6
{ Clearing the path for the c8-bishop to develop with tempo. It feels a bit illogical to send this knight to the queenside, but it could certainly return with ...Nd5 at some point.   14...Qf6  is a sensible alternative.   14...d5  15.Ng3  e4  16.Nh2  Nde5  looks menacing, but Black can easily find himself somewhat overextended.  17.Bc2⩲  with Nh5 coming, and it's hard to advance the pawns further due to White's control over the dark squares. There also exists the idea to capture on g7 at the right moment, weakening the area around the kingside. }
15. Bc2 Qf6 16. d4
{ If White delays this for too long, he can easily end up drifting into trouble, due to his opponent's space advantage and open lines on the kingside. }
16... e4
{ Black's pawns are menacing, but if White is careful, they can be contained.   16...exd4?!  17.Ng3  dxc3  18.bxc3±  with fantastic compensation. Having split up the e and f-pawn pair, the kingside just feels vulnerable. Nh5xg7 is an immediate idea, and taking on c3 probably just incurs even further risk. }
17. N3h2 Be6
{ The problem that Black has is that it's not easy to make much of his advanced kingside pawns. Playing ...f4 quickly will hang e4, meanwhile White is quick to establish a blockade.   17...d5  This threatens a very strong ...f4, but Black isn't really in time to play it. For that reason, Black may prefer to keep the d5-square open for a knight.  18.Ng3  f4??  Since this isn't good, White is in time to set up a dark square blockade. with Nh5.  19.Nh5  Qd6  20.f3+-   17...Bd7=  is preferred by Stockfish 15. }
18. Ng3 Ne7 19. Nhf1
{ 19.Nh5  is reasonable, although a hasty Nxg7 should be avoided, as  19...Qf7  20.Nxg7?!  Qxg7  followed by doubling on the g-file gives Black a strong attack. }
19... Bf7
{ Black opts to give up his light squared bishop for the knight. This makes sense, because theoretically it's the 'bad bishop'.   19...Qg6  20.Nh5  Ned5  is an alternative. Taking on g7 is playable, but risky, both due to weakening White's control over f4, and clearing the g-file for a potential attack. At the same time, it does pick up the bishop pair and weaken Black's kingside.  21.a4  a5  22.Ra3!?  Now Black has to watch out for the threat of c4 folowed by Rg3!  22...Rg8=  with still complicated play.   19...Qf7  20.Nh5  Rae8=  is also even. }
20. Nh5 Bxh5 21. Qxh5 d5
{ The remainder of the game is a maneuvering struggle, where neither side manages to really achieve much. }
22. Bf4 Rac8 23. Ng3 Nc4 24. a4 Qg6 25. b3 Nd6 26. Qh4 Rf7 27. Bd1 Qe6 28. Bh5
Rff8 29. Ne2 Bf6 30. Qg3 Rg8 31. Qe3 Kh7 32. Rad1 Bg5 33. h4 Bxh4 34. g3 Bg5
35. Kg2 Rg7 36. Rh1 Kg8 37. Rh3 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
