[White "Model Games"]
[Black "½-½ Peter Leko (2755) vs. Magnus Carlsen (2714) Tal Memorial 2007"]
[Result "*"]

{ This is, on the surface, not a very interesting game. However, it's important for the purposes of understanding that endgames don't have to be lost just because White has a kingside majority. Naturally, you have to be careful to avoid unfavourable scenarios, but simplification is by no means always horrible for the second player. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O Qf6 6. d4 exd4 7. Bg5 Qd6 8.
Nxd4 Be7 9. Bxe7
{ This is logical, as it eliminates Black's bishop pair. However, it turns out that the resulting position doesn't really put much pressure on the second player, at least in theory.   9.Be3  is generally thought of as more critical. }
9... Nxe7 10. Nc3 Bd7 11. Nb3 Qxd1
{ In thetheory section of the course, we recommend  11...O-O-O  which keeps more tension in the position. If White wants to swap queens, he'd have to undouble our pawns. }
12. Raxd1 b6
{ This is probably the only decent move, as it's quite important to stop the intrusive Nc5. }
13. Rd2
{ Doubling on the d-file is logical, but this doesn't really end up achieving much.   White should immediately begin advancing on the kingside, and is probably a bit better after  13.f4⩲ }
13... O-O-O 14. Rfd1 c5
{ The immediate  14...f5  is also possible. In general, this break is a key idea in the Exchange Spanish. The kingside majority is much less scary when the lead e-pawn has been swapped off. }
15. Nd5 Nxd5 16. Rxd5 f5
{ It's not mandatory to play this straight away, but if Black avoids it for too long, he may find himself in an unpleasant situation.   16...a5  is another totally possible move.  17.f3  a4  18.Nc1  and now it's important to play  18...f5!   18...Rhe8?!  19.g4⩲  prevents ...f5 and gives White a plus. It's still possible to fight with something like ...g6 and ...f5, but this is far more trouble than it needs to be.  19.exf5   19.e5  f4  This isn't the only move, but it makes sense to split the e5-pawn from the f3-pawn.  20.Ne2  Be6  21.Rxd8+  Rxd8  22.Rxd8+  Kxd8  23.a3  Allowing Black to capture on a2 would be risky.  23...g5=  Bxf5  20.Rxd8+  Rxd8  21.Rxd8+  Kxd8=  is similar to the game. }
17. exf5 Bxf5 18. Rxd8+ Rxd8 19. Rxd8+ Kxd8
{ This is the sort of endgame I wanted to draw attention to. White has a functional kingside pawn majority, with no doubled pawns. Meanwhile, it will be quite difficult for Black to create a passed pawn on the queenside without cooperation. This fact is a basic point of the Exchange Spanish. Nevertheless, Black has a bishop against a knight, which tends to be favourable on an open board with pawns on both sides such as this one. White's kingside pawns are a long way from queening, and the knight will struggle for an active role. In the game, White's knight ends up a bit stuck, and Carlsen quickly activates his king, basically eliminating any chances White may have had to slowly make progress. }
20. c3
{ Before doing anything else, White had to answer to the threat to his c2-pawn.   20.c4  is also reasonable. I've copied in the top line of the computer at a high depth for illustrative purposes. The following moves are far from forced, and both sides can deviate very reasonably at any number of junctures.  20...Ke7  21.f4  Kf6  22.Kf2  Bb1  23.a3  Kf5  Here we can see the issue with creating a passed pawn on the kingside; how does White achieve anything?  24.Ke3   24.Kf3??  Be4+  Black is now winning.  25.Kg3  Bc6  26.Nd2  This is pretty much forced to stop the king invasion on e4, but now White is in zugzwang, e.g.  26...a5  27.h4  h6-+  and at some point White has to allow eiether ...Ke4 or give up a pawn somewhere.  a5  25.Nd2  Bc2  26.h3  h5  If White were able to get g4 in simply, he might have some chances. One problem is that Black's bishop has great influence over the light squares, making, e.g. Kf3 and g4 hard to get in.  27.g3  Ba4  28.Nf3   28.Kf3  'Threatening' g4, which is hardly winning, but it would be a sign of some sort of progress. A few moves are fine, with  28...Bc6+  arguably being the most logical.  29.Ke3  Bg2  30.h4  Kg4  31.Kf2  Bc6=  White's majority is going nowhere.  Bb3  29.Ne5  Bd1=  There's not really any progress to be made. The g4-square is locked down, and trying to move the knight somewhere else can just be met by ...Bb3, dragging it back to e5. }
20... Be6
{ This nice move is what I was referring to earlier when mentioning that the knight ends up 'stuck'. It will take a few moves in order to untangle the a2/b3 construction without losing a pawn. }
21. Kf1
{ It feels logical to start pushing the kingside pawns quickly, but that is easier said than done.   21.f4?  is a poor way to start; the light squares now become weak.  21...Ke7  22.Kf2  Kf6  23.Ke3  Kf5  24.h3  h5∓  White now faces an unpleasant choice between allowing .. .h5-h4 and playing g2-g3, when the h3-pawn would become weak.   21.f3  is a better way to begin.  21...Kd7  22.Kf2  a5  23.Ke3  a4  24.Nc1  Kc6  25.a3  White pushes his a-pawn in order to free his knight. It is logical to put the pawns on the opposite colour to Black's bishop, but it also has some definite downsides. For one thing, it weakens the b3-square, and the knight may end up having to stay on c1 to prevent ...Kd5-c4-b3. Additionally, Black can play ... b5-b4 in the future in order to create counterplay. We'll see this theme later on.  25...Kd5  26.h4  Kc4=  We see this type of scenario in the game too. White's knight is tied down to defending the b3-square. Now the best move is }
21... a5 22. Nc1 Kd7 23. Ke2 Kc6 24. Kd2
{ 24.f3  a4  25.a3  Kb5  26.h4   26.g4  g5  This isn't forced, but it does feel logical.  27.Ke3  Kc4  28.f4  gxf4+  29.Kxf4  b5  30.h4  b4  Black is forcibly undoubling his pawns.  31.axb4  cxb4  32.cxb4  Kxb4  33.g5  c5  I won't show you the entire concluding sequence, but this does lead to a draw.  Kc4  27.Kd2  b5  28.Nd3  White has brought his pieces to the queenside in order to prevent ...b5-b4. This is fine, but there's not any means on progress on the kingside after playing this.  28...Bc8  29.g4  h6  Black's moves are not forced at all. Most options are okay.  30.g5  hxg5  31.hxg5  Bf5  32.Nf4  g6=  ...b4 next. }
24... a4 25. a3
{ I've already described the benefits and downsides of this move previously. It frees the knight and removes the pawn from the gaze of the bishop. However, it weakens b3 and makes ...b5-b4 a definite possibility.   25.f3  Black can play most sensible moves and be okay here. He can certainly consider ...a3, but doesn't have to play it. It's going to be difficult to do much with a less active king and knight stuck on c1.   25.Ke3?!  steps too far away from the queenside, and now Black can definitely play  25...a3!  26.b3   26.bxa3??  Kb5  27.Kd2  Ka4-+  b5  and now it's quite hard to see how the knight will ever leave c1, with ...Bxb3 being a winning shot if it does. }
25... Kd5 26. Nd3 Kc4 27. Ne5+ Kd5
{ 27...Kb3  28.Kc1  b5  is also sensible. White now needs to stop ...b4, but he has two decent enough ways to do that.  29.Nd3   29.Nf3=  prepares to meet ... b4 with a capture on b4, and Nd4+ if the pawn is recaptured. This is probably the less obvious way to do it, but it does work.  29...b4  30.cxb4  Kc4  30.Ne5+=  echoes the game. }
28. Nd3 Kc4 29. Ne5+ Kd5 30. Nd3
{ Leko opts to repeat. I hope that the variations that I've given throughout the notes to this game are a sufficient illustration of why he didn't feel that playing on was likely to be fruitful. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "0-1 Smilovici vs. Dunne Ottawa 2017"]
[Result "*"]

{ I generally like to add at least one of my own games in the annotated games section of my opening courses. They can never really be called 'model games' per se, and doubtless they provide quite a bit less instructional value than a game by a strong player. That being said, I like to show some of my practical experience in the relevant opening. In this game, my opponent played the Exchange Spanish, eliminated my bishop pair and then traded queens, but I was surprised to find that I had quite strong counterplay anyway. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6
{ Unfortunately, I can't share any of my efforts with the Open Spanish itself, as until quite recently I played things like the Chigorin, Marshall and Arkhangelsk. I haven't really played any serious chess since we started working on this course, so unfortunately I haven't been able to test the core of our repertoire in practical games. }
4... dxc6 5. O-O
{ I spent probably at least five minutes here choosing which line I wanted to play. The Exchange Variation is often a perennial annoyance for the 1.e4 e5 player who wants to play 3...a6 against the Spanish, so I was vaguely familiar with pretty much all of the sensible options available to Black here. That being said, I really didn't know any of them in any sort of detail. }
5... Bd6
{ I was somewhat acquainted with this line from browsing Milos Pavlovic's book Fighting the Ruy Lopez. I was later pleasantly surprised to see it recommended by Jan Gustafsson in his 1.e4 e5 course for Chessable.   We recommend  5...Qf6  in this course.   I used to play  5...Bg4  6.h3  Bh5?!  and even won a game against the same opponent two years prior. However, at some point I lost my belief in the soundness of this pawn sacrifice, so I didn't really want to repeat it.  7.g4  Bg6  8.Nxe5  Black has compensation for the pawn, but probably not enough. }
6. d4 { Other moves don't really give White any hope for an advantage. } 6...
exd4 7. Qxd4 f6 8. Be3 Be6 9. Nbd2
{ White would like bring this knight to c4, asking Black to give up one of his bishops. However, this requires a bit of preparing. }
9... Ne7 10. h3
{ In a vacuum, this looks like an odd choice. However, it makes sense in connection with the plan of Nc4. Black doesn't have to be afraid of this Nc4 idea, as he's quite alright even after giving up his light squared bishop. Meanwhile, the move h2-h3 doesn't particularly serve any function other than avoiding the ...Bxh2+ tactic at the moment. I suspected that my opponent was out of book and made a sensible-looking move, but looking at the ChessBase database, it turns out that he had already had this position four years earlier.   The immediate  10.Nc4?  walks into a trick that is standard for this line:  10...Bxh2+!  11.Kxh2  Qxd4  12.Nxd4  Bxc4∓  and Black picks up a pawn.  If White is wanting to play Nc4, you could argue that   10.Rad1  is the more useful way to prepare it. This stops the ...Bxh2+ tactic, because there will now be a recapture on d4 with the rook.  10...Ng6  11.Nc4  Bxc4  12.Qxc4  Qe7  As discussed below, when White goes for Nc4, the queen should probably go to e7 rather than d7.   10.Qc3  This has several functions; clearing the way for Nd4, clearing the d-file for a rook coming to d1, stepping away from ...c6-c5, etc. White's best approach in this variation is probably to avoid a quick Nc4. For example, Werle in his Chessable course recommends:  10...Qd7  As discussed below, the Nc4 plan is best met with the queen going to e7. Black now argues that Nc4 is not very effective here, because of the lost tempo with the queen; Qd4-c3xc4.  11.Rad1   11.Nc4  Bxc4  12.Qxc4  Ng6  12.Nb3 }
10... Qd7
{ When I was actively playing this line, one thing that confused me was when to play ...Qd7 and when to play ...Ng6 and ...Qe7. For example, Gustafsson recommends meeting 10.Rad1 with 10...Ng6 and 10.Qc3 with 10...Qd7.   10...Ng6!  may be slightly more accurate in this case. One idea is that:  11.Nc4  could be met with  11...Bb4!?   11...Bxc4  also makes sense.  12.Qxc4  Qe7  It seems that when White goes for this Nc4 plan, it's better to have the queen on e7 than d7. This may be true for a couple of reasons; it avoids the open d-file, and also makes Nd4 more difficult to play, due to ...Qxe4. }
11. Nc4 Bxc4
{ 11...c5!  is the computer's suggestion.  12.Qc3   12.Nxd6+  cxd6  13.Qc3  O-O =  would be alright for Black. The pawn on d6 feels like it could be a bit vulnerable, but it's defensible with ...Qc6, ...Rad8, etc.. In the meantime, he's undoubled his pawns and should have reasonable play.  Bxc4  13.Qxc4  Black does have to be careful here.  13...b5   13...b6?!  14.Rad1  Leaves Black's king high and dry in the centre.  14...Qb5!  is the only move to avoid serious risk.  15.Qe6  Qd7  16.Qxd7+  Kxd7  17.e5  fxe5  18.Nxe5+  Ke6  19.Nc4±   13...Qb5  is also possible.  14.Qc3  Qc6=  Next, Black can castle short, and everything looks fine. ...Ng6 can follow, with reasonable chances. }
12. Qxc4 Ng6
{ As I mentioned before, the queen would rather be on e7 here, both to discourage Nd4, and to avoid the open d-file.   12...O-O-O  is natural, and here  13.Nd4⩲  or either rook to the d-file is a bit annoying. }
13. Rad1 Qf7
{ This is an idea which I can remember having seen in some games before. It's fairly illogical-seeming to swap queens in an Exchange Spanish where you lack the Bishop pair, but it does solve the issue of the queen on d7 being misplaced, and the issue of the king needing to find a home. }
14. Qxf7+ Kxf7
{ This is the type of position which I wanted to discuss. It seems that White should be better, and indeed he is. However, what's interesting is how quickly this seemingly innocuous position went wrong for my opponent. I vaguely recalled seeing positions like this before being alright for Black. Despite the worse pawn structure and lack of bishop pair, Black can quickly swing his rooks to the open files and advance . ..g5, ...h5/...c5, ...b5 on either side of the board. For example, I recalled the game Howell-Hebden, Gibraltar 2005, where Black did alright. There were some differences in that game, as I now see; a2xb3 had been played, and Black was castled queenside. Anyway, I suppose Black should avoid this type of position if possible, but if it does arise, it's not totally hopeless. Like I mentioned, I wasn't really terribly familiar with this line at the time, aside from some vague ideas, and there are at least two improvements I could have gone for to avoid the situation that has arisen. White also can't play however he pleases; if he's not precise, Black has decent counterchances. }
15. Rfe1
{ This is natural, but a bit too slow. It's possible the rook should simply remain on f1, to support a future f2-f4. The e-pawn would be better supported by f2-f3 than with the rook on e1 anyway.   15.Nd4!  This should give White a slight edge. He prepares both Nf5 as well as f2-f3 to secure the e-pawn.  15...Rhe8  16.Nf5  Rad8  17.Nxd6+?!   17.f3⩲  There's no need to rush into an exchange on d6. White can continue slowly improving his position, e.g. Kf2, maybe doubling on the d-file, pushing the kingside pawns, etc.  Rxd6  18.f3  Red8  is what I gave in my notes to this game at the time. Black looks fine, because he either gains control over the d-file or gets to undouble his pawns.   18...f5!  might be more accurate. This pawn break is a common theme in the Exchange Spanish, and it's especially relevant when we have a major piece on the e-file and there's a loose bishop on e3.  19.exf5   19.Bc5  Rxd1  20.Rxd1  fxe4  21.Rd7+  Ke6  22.Rxg7  exf3  23.Rxc7  fxg2  24.Rxh7  Rg8  25.Rxb7  Nf4=  Rxe3  20.fxg6+  Kxg6  21.Kf2  Re5=   15.Nd2⩲  is another reasonable option. This doesn't look like an amazing square for the knight, but the point is to prepare f2-f4, covering e4 so it doesn't become too weak. }
15... Rhe8
{ Now Black has a fully equal position. Again, compared to 15. Nd4 Rhe8 16.f3, it's much less convenient to defend e4. }
16. Bd4
{ 16.Nd2  h5  17.f3  Rad8=  Black can continue with ...Ne5 or ...h4, with a fine game. }
16... Re7
{ It made sense to me to put further pressure on e4, but this is just one of many viable moves here.   16...Bb4!?  17.c3   17.Nd2=  is better.  Bd6  is an interesting idea. Now that the c3-square has been taken away from White's bishop, ...c5 followed by ...Rxe4 is a threat.  18.b4  Rad8  This is somewhere between equal and slightly better for Black.   16...a5  17.Bc3  a4=   16...c5  17.Bc3  b5= }
17. Nd2
{ This was better on the last couple of turns. Now, the arrangement of White's pieces could cause him some difficulties.   17.g3  Rae8  18.Nd2  h5= }
17... Rae8
{ This doubling is logical but a bit beside the point. Instead, it was better to immediately aim to exploit the awkward collection of pieces on the d-file.   17...Rd8  If Black gets another free tempo, ...Red7 would already be winning, as it's not possible to escape the d-file without losing material.  18.Nc4   18.--  Red7-+  Black is threatening ...Bf4, and even ...Bh2+, winning material.  19.Bc3   19.Kf1  Bf4  20.Nb3  c5!  wins material.  Be5!  is one way to win a piece.  Bb4   18...Red7  is also reasonable, e.g.  19.Ne3  Bb4  20.Bc3   20.c3??  Be7-+  This is mildly amusing; the threat is ...c5 to trap the bishop. If White moves the knight to create an open square on e3, the d1-rook will be undefended, meaning ...c5 wins the bishop regardless.  21.Ba7  Rxd1  22.Rxd1  Ra8  23.Bd4  c5  Bxc3  21.bxc3  Nf4⩱  19.c3  Red7  20.Re2  c5  21.Red2  Rxd4  22.Rxd4  cxd4  23.cxb4  h5⩱  is given by the computer, with a small edge for Black. }
18. f3
{ This does not help White's upcoming d-file predicament.   18.Kf1  One of the important points of this move is to dodge a ...Bh2+, once Black has doubled on the d-file and White has moved his two minor pieces away.  18...Rd7  19.Nc4   19.Bc3  Red8?!  20.Nc4⩲  Red8  20.Be3=   18.Be3  Rd7  19.g3  is another option, again, avoiding the ... Bh2+ idea.  19...h5  20.f4  h4  21.Kg2  hxg3  22.Kxg3  Rh8= }
18... Rd7
{ Now, Black can switch to the d-file, and it's surprisingly difficult for White to deal with it. The best approach is pretty much to evacuate as soon as possible. }
19. Nc4 Red8 20. Rd3
{ 20.Rb1  or another rook move away from the d-file, is what White needed to do.  20...Bb4  21.Bc3  This bishop would've been pinned if Rb1 hadn't been played.  21...Bxc3  22.bxc3  b6  23.Kf2  h5⩱  Control over the d-file, White's split pawns on the queenside, and potential to lock down some kingside squares with ...h5-h4 give Black a small advantage here.   20.Nxd6+??  Rxd6  and White loses a piece.   20.Be3??  Bh2+-+ }
20... Bb4 21. c3
{ 21.Bc3  is relatively best.  21...Rxd3  22.cxd3  Bxc3  23.bxc3  Rxd3  24.Na5  b5  25.Nxc6  Rxc3  26.Nb4  a5-+   21.Red1  Nf4-+  wins material }
21... Rxd4 22. Rxd4 Rxd4 23. Ne3 Ba5 24. b4 Bxb4 25. cxb4 Rxb4
{ As always, my technique can be queried, but fortunately this position is very winning for Black. }
26. Rd1 Nf8 27. Nf5 g6 28. Nh6+ Kg7 29. Ng4 Rb2 30. a4 Rb4 31. e5 fxe5 32. Nxe5
c5 { 32...Rxa4  Just get rid of the a-pawn. } 33. a5 b5 34. Rd5 Rb1+ 35. Kh2
Rc1 36. Rd8 c4 37. Ra8 b4 38. Rxa6 b3 39. Nxc4 Rxc4 40. Ra7 Rb4 41. Rxc7+ Kf6
42. Rc1
{ 42.a6  b2  43.a7  Ra4  44.Rb7  Rxa7  45.Rxb2  Ra4  This is winning, but it's much less winning than it was a second ago. }
42... b2 43. Rb1 Ne6 44. a6 Nc7 45. a7 Ke5 *

